<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards' Plummer Says Thumb's Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Three days after what he called one of the  
worst performances of his young career, Jake Plummer said Wednesday 
that his sore right thumb has improved and he's ready to forget 
that dreadful Sunday afternoon in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer, who sprained the thumb in the preseason, was able to  
take the most snaps yet in practice on Wednesday as the Arizona 
Cardinals prepared for their home opener Monday night against the 
San Francisco 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to get the reps,'' Plummer said, ``especially on the  
blitz drill. It's not as fast a game, but it's the fastest we have 
during the day. It's good to be able to see that stuff happening in 
front of me. It felt good to be able to get out there again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Vince Tobin had said it was more a lack of practice time  
than the injured thumb that has led to Plummer's problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jake did more today,'' Tobin said. ``It's still got some  
soreness to it, but I think it's better and we expect him to be 
ready to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 19-16 loss to Miami, the third-year quarterback threw  
four interceptions. He completed 11 of 27 passes for only 112 
yards. The last interception, on a ``Hail Mary'' pass on the final 
play of the game, could be excused. Plummer had no excuses for the 
other three. 
</P>
<P>
	In two games, he has seven interceptions and one touchdown pass.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously I'm not throwing how I was in camp or how I was last  
year,'' he said. ``I have an injury. You have to deal with it. My 
main thing is I don't want there to be an excuse. I don't want that 
to be the reason I threw three picks. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I was throwing to a wide-open guy, and it came out  
fluttering and it went high and it was intercepted, then yeah, I 
could blame it on my thumb and say my grip wasn't right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't what happened last weekend.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was a couple of poor decisions,'' Plummer said. ``The thumb  
has nothing to do with the decision-making process. That was my 
head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer said he was trying to force things.  
</P>
<P>
	``We knew we'd have a shot to make big plays against the defense  
last week,'' he said. ``What happened with me is I thought every 
play was a big play. It's over, though. We're going to get over it 
and come into this week ready to make some big plays.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plummer said he has to shrug off his bad afternoon or he won't  
be ready for the 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to have bad games and I'm going to have great  
games,'' he said. ``If I come in after a great game and think I'm 
so high and mighty, that's when you get knocked down the next week. 
If I come in with a bad attitude and moping and have a chip on my 
shoulder, sad and mad about this throw and that throw, then I'm not 
going to play up to my potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make matters worse, Plummer has been bothered by a sore  
groin, which has hampered his trademark scrambling ability. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more you think about it, the more apt it is to hurt,'' he  
said, ``and if you don't think about it, it kind of goes away.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:47:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dutch Journalist Killed in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- As international peacekeepers worked to  
restore order to East Timor, a Dutch journalist was killed and two 
other Western reporters escaped an armed attack without injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The attackers in both incidents remained unidentified Wednesday,  
although they appeared to be linked to pro-Indonesian militias that 
began rampaging across the territory after East Timorese voted 
overwhelmingly for independence in an Aug. 30 referendum. 
</P>
<P>
	Sander Thoenes, 30, a correspondent for the London-based  
Financial Times, had been in Dili less than two hours Tuesday when 
he hired motorcycle driver Florindo Araujo for a tour of the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Araujo said he took Thoenes to the suburb of Becora, where they  
approached a roadblock staffed by at least six armed men wearing 
the gray uniforms of the Indonesian police. 
</P>
<P>
	The two turned around, but some of the armed men gave chase,  
firing warning shots and eventually shooting out the motorcycle's 
rear wheel. Araujo, who fled, last saw Thoenes lying in the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoenes' mutilated body was found later. His death was believed  
to be the first killing of a foreigner since the intervention began 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Militiamen have vowed to kill Westerners, whom they accuse of  
helping East Timor break free of Indonesian occupation. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Federation of Journalists expressed outrage  
Wednesday over Thoenes' death, calling it a blatant attempt to stop 
journalists from reporting from East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Lambert, editor of the Financial Times, called Thoenes  
``one of the FT's finest foreign correspondents and a wonderful 
friend and colleague.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House also issued a statement, calling Thoenes' death  
``a tragic reminder of the dangers'' faced by East Timor's people, 
the international peacekeepers and the journalists there. 
</P>
<P>
	``The international media must have the freedom and security to  
shine a spotlight on events in East Timor,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoenes was the newspaper's Jakarta correspondent, and  
previously had worked as its Central Asia correspondent based in 
Almaty, Kazakstan. He also worked for The Christian Science Monitor 
and the Dutch news magazine Vrij Nederland. 
</P>
<P>
	At the United Nations, Secretary-General Kofi Annan's spokesman,  
Fred Eckhard, said Thoenes ``died in the act of seeking the truth 
about the calamity that has been inflicted on East Timor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ali Alatas, Indonesia's foreign minister, said he knew Thoenes  
well because the journalist had interviewed him several times. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very, very sorry to hear this news. And I very much  
regret this,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second incident, in the hills near Becora, a car carrying  
London Sunday Times correspondent Jon Swain and Chip Hires, an 
American photographer for the Gamma agency, was attacked by men in 
military uniforms, armed with M-16 rifles. 
</P>
<P>
	Hires said the men shot out the tires of their car.  
</P>
<P>
	``They say, `Get out of the taxi,' and we think OK, that's  
really it,'' Hires told Associated Press Television News. 
</P>
<P>
	The armed men began hitting their driver with their rifle butts,  
Hires said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took one good shot and basically his eye came out of the  
socket,'' Hires said. The armed men then started shooting in the 
air. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them told the journalists to run away, so they fled to a  
nearby forest. 
</P>
<P>
	The two waited until dark and called the Sunday Times on Swain's  
cell phone. Australian troops eventually rescued them. 
</P>
<P>
	Hires said the armed men were wearing Indonesian military  
uniforms and appeared to be Indonesian soldiers, who have backed 
the pro-Indonesian militias. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope they're rogue units, because if that's the overall  
politics it's a rogue army,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
