<DOCNO> APW19990922.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schott Pleased With Shaniowa's Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Chuck Schott was pleased when Shaniowa won the Iowa Breeders'  
Oaks at Prairie Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott wasn't the breeder, nor does he own, train or ride the  
3-year-old filly. 
</P>
<P>
	What he did was save her life at birth by giving her  
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation. Actually, it was mouth-to-nostril. 
</P>
<P>
	Then on Aug. 21 at Prairie Meadows at Altoona, Iowa, Shaniowa  
won the Iowa Breeders' Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	The 58-year-old Schott, the horseman's liaison for the track,  
was manager at Bruce Thoroughbred Farm at Perry, Iowa, when the 
filly was foaled. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the middle of the night,'' he recalled. ``I had  
closed-circuit television in my room and I saw the mare (Southern 
Myth) go down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So he went to the barn. There, he found a problem.  
</P>
<P>
	``The foal was hip-locked,'' Schott said. ``She was stuck. So I  
pulled her out. She had suffocated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schott, who worked at the farm of Doug and Mary Bruce before  
retiring two years ago, had seen this ``happen four or five times 
before. Generally, it doesn't work. I can think of two I saved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schott ``blew in one nostril while I held (blocked) the other  
nostril. It's better than blowing air into the mouth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first foal Schott saved didn't turn out to be much of a  
racehorse. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaniowa, owned by Dr. Philip Burford of Wichita, Kan., did not  
win in two starts as a 2-year-old last year. She earned $580. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, she seemed to get an her second wind. She opened her  
campaign with a 9-length win April 29, and she has four wins, two 
seconds and a third in 10 starts this year, with the biggest 
victory coming in the Iowa Breeders' Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Shaniowa, who had made all of her starts at Prairie Meadows,  
paid her own way with earnings of $83,324. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot of fun to see her run so well,'' Schott said.  
</P>
<P>
	Schott got a chance to come to her aid because Burford wanted  
the filly, who was conceived in Kansas, to be foaled in Iowa so she 
could be eligible for the Iowa-bred purse supplement. 
</P>
<P>
	Often there is criticism of horsemen and horse owners because of  
fatal injuries -- especially to horses such as Ruffian, Go For Wand 
and Prairie Bayou on national television -- and to career-ending 
injuries to such stars as General Challenge and Victory Gallop, 
also on national television. 
</P>
<P>
	Horsemen might often seem callous because death and injury are  
quickly put behind them, at least publicly. Racing, however, is a 
risky business, and if you're in it, you best look ahead every day 
-- or get out of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Abuse of horses, of course, does occur.  
</P>
<P>
	But Schott's successful effort is just one example of thousands  
of professionals -- from hot walkers to the top level -- who are 
dedicated to the welfare of horses ranging from a second-chance 
filly such as Shaniowa at Prairie Meadows to a superstar filly such 
as Silverbulletday at the nation's major race tracks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
