<DOCNO> APW19990922.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 16:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cornhuskers' Player Pleads Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Suspended Nebraska wingback Shevin Wiggins  
pleaded innocent Wednesday to a charge of sexual assualt of a 
child. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiggins, accused of fondling a 14-year-old girl in July,  
appeared briefly with his lawyer, Terry Dougherty, and entered his 
plea in Lancaster County District Court. Judge Paul Merritt set a 
tentative trial date of Nov. 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiggins, who will turn 25 on Monday, is accused of fondling the  
girl outside a foster home where she lived late July 25 or early 
July 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Another man, Floyd Brown III, 22, is accused of touching the  
girl and her twin sister. He pleaded innocent Wednesday to two 
counts of sexual assault of a child. 
</P>
<P>
	Sexual assault of a child is a felony punishable by up to 5  
years in prison and a $10,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiggins and Brown are free on $10,000 bonds.  
</P>
<P>
	University rules bar Wiggins from the team while the charge is  
pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiggins, who was listed as a starter before his suspension, was  
part of Nebraska's ``miracle catch'' that led to a victory at 
Missouri two years ago and kept the Huskers' undefeated record 
intact. Wiggins kicked Scott Frost's pass in the end zone and Matt 
Davison made a diving grab before the ball hit the ground to send 
the game into overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The Huskers return to Missouri for the first time since the  
famous catch on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiggins, a native of Palmetto, Fla., graduated in May with a  
degree in consumer science. The NCAA granted Wiggins another year 
of eligibility in April. Wiggins, who has a reading disability, was 
recruited in 1994 but sat out while gaining academic eligibility. 
He redshirted in 1995 and played the last three years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0007 </DOCNO>
