<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 06:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Expelled Student Shoots at Crowd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A gunman opened fire on a crowd of students as  
they walked home from a South Side high school, injuring two 
teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither of the wounded students was seriously hurt in the attack  
Tuesday afternoon outside Fenger High School. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said today no one had been arrested. Witnesses said the  
gunman was a 17-year-old boy who had been expelled from the school, 
said Lt. Joe Murphy. Police did not say why the student had been 
expelled. 
</P>
<P>
	Murphy said the shooting took place as members of one large  
group of students began arguing with a smaller group. 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman was in the smaller group and fired six to 12 shots  
from a handgun into the larger group, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear if the gunman was aiming at, or even knew, the  
students who were shot, the officer said. 
</P>
<P>
	A 14-year-old girl was hospitalized today in good condition with  
a wound to her foot. A 15-year-old boy was released after treatment 
for an abdominal wound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Convicted for Phony Memorabilia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A sports memorabilia dealer has been convicted of  
defrauding collectors by selling thousands of dollars of goods 
bearing the forged autographs of athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Austin, 42, of Newport Beach, Calif., was convicted  
Tuesday of eight counts of mail fraud by a federal jury. Sentencing 
was set for Dec. 10. Each count carries a maximum sentence of five 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses against Austin included Anthony Alyinovich, one of 11  
people who had pleaded guilty earlier in the federal government's 
Operation Foul Ball crackdown on sports memorabilia forging. 
</P>
<P>
	Alyinovich, of Chicago, acknowledged that he was the boss of a  
staff of forgers who signed the names of Michael Jordan and other 
big-time sport luminaries to jerseys, basketballs and other sports 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	Other stars whose phony signatures ended up on items included  
Scottie Pippen, Dennis Rodman, Joe Montana, Dan Marino, Troy Aikman 
and Emmitt Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Austin, an owner of Overtime Prowear Inc., insisted that he had  
done nothing wrong and had not realized the items Alyinovich sold 
him were forgeries. 
</P>
<P>
	Alyinovich was accused of creating and selling more than $2  
million worth of bogus goods. He was placed on five years of 
probation and fined $30,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 10:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oracle Unveils New Portal Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDWOOD SHORES, Calif. (AP) -- Oracle Corp. today introduced  
technology that helps companies quickly build corporate intranet 
Web sites that are viewed by employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle will use what it calls ``portlet'' technology, a standard  
method for assembling the components that make up a corporate Web 
site, such as company information, search features and software 
applications used by employees. The technology also makes it easier 
to produce corporate Web sites that have a common look and feel, 
the company said in a statement. The portlet technology is designed 
to work with Oracle's database applications. 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies such as Microsoft Corp., Lotus Development  
Corp., and SAP AG are promoting their own standardized corporate 
portal technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Oracle, based in Redwood Shores, Calif., is the leading producer  
of database software for businesses using computers or desktop 
machines linked in networks. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
