<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brown's Sentencing Reset </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- NFL Hall of Famer Jim Brown's sentencing on a  
misdemeanor conviction for vandalizing his wife's car was reset 
Wednesday to Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing originally was scheduled for Thursday, but Brown's  
lawyer, William Graysen, asked for time to prove that the vandalism 
conviction should not fall under domestic violence guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 63, was acquitted in Hollywood Municipal Court on Sept.  
10 of a misdemeanor charge of making terrorist threats against his 
wife, 25-year-old Monique Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	``If a man is found not guilty of domestic violence, he should  
not be given a domestic violence punishment,'' Graysen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Cleveland Browns running back faces a maximum of six  
months in jail. Prosecutors have said that, because domestic 
violence was involved, other conditions could be imposed, including 
probation, restitution and domestic violence counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown was prosecuted on the terrorist threat charge even though  
his wife recanted allegations that she made to police on June 15, 
saying he had threatened to snap her neck. 
</P>
<P>
	Monique Brown had gone to a neighbor's house, called 911 and  
reported that her husband had threatened her life and that there 
was a gun in the house. 
</P>
<P>
	She said later that she had made the call and lied to get  
attention because she believed her husband was having an affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown never denied that he smashed the car windows with a  
shovel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
