<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Tips for Avoiding Y2K Scams / On the Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There's something a little scary about the year  
2000, and it has nothing to do with the remote possibility of 
elevators malfunctioning, planes disappearing off radar screens or 
banks losing track of customers' life savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest fear right now, at least among government officials  
and consumer groups, is not any Y2K computer bug, but scam artists 
bugging unsuspected consumers and playing on concerns that the 
nation's computers might crash. (The fear is that computers may 
mistake ``00'' for 1900 instead of 2000.) 
</P>
<P>
	Some scams that have surfaced recently: someone pretending to  
represent a bank calling to ``confirm'' credit card or bank account 
numbers; someone selling bogus magnetic strips to make credit cards 
immune from computer problems; someone offering to hold individuals 
savings and investments in a ``safe place'' until after Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one scam has targeted the elderly. Someone posing as a  
government employee claims senior citizens will no longer get their 
Social Security checks and that paper money will be useless, then 
persuades his victims to send in their cash so he can turn it into 
gold and mail it back to them. Of course, he doesn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered reports of such incidents have even prompted Donna  
Tanoue, chairwoman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., to write 
a letter to syndicated columnist Ann Landers warning consumers to 
be ``skeptical, careful and vigilant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Y2K presents a perfect opportunity for criminals to cash in on  
fears of the unknown...,'' she wrote this month. ``No bank would 
ever ask for your credit card number over the phone, but a scam 
artist would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With several weeks to go before the new millennium, 99 percent  
of the nation's federally insured banks, thrifts and credit unions 
have successfully completed Y2K preparations, according to the 
FDIC. The Securities and Exchange Commission also estimates that 99 
percent of the brokerage firms and securities transfer agents are 
Y2K compliant. And the same percentage of the nation's power 
companies are ready, according to U.S. Energy Secretary Bill 
Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet that hasn't stopped the scam artists from attempting to  
incite fears and to cash in on them -- even at this late date. 
</P>
<P>
	Several groups and government agencies have issued warnings  
about Y2K fraud and have put out publications to educate consumers 
and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the many publications still available: ``Year 2000 and  
You,'' which features Y2K preparedness information compiled from 
the FDIC, Federal Trade Commission, the President's Council on Year 
2000 Conversion, the American Red Cross and the Council of Better 
Business Bureaus. It's available through the BBB Web site 
(www.bbb.org/library/y2k.html) or by writing the BBB at 4200 Wilson 
Blvd., Arlington, Va. 22203. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDIC's consumer advisory is available by calling  
1-800-934-3342 or visiting its Web site (www.fdic.gov/about/y2k). 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC's Y2K fraud advisory, ``Y2K? Y 2 Care: Protecting Your  
Finances from Year 2000 Scam Artists,'' is available on FTC Web 
site (www.ftc.gov or www.consumer.gov/y2k/) or by calling the FTC 
at 1-888-USA-4-Y2K. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forum for Investor Advice, a nonprofit organization of  
financial institutions, offers a free brochure, ``Keeping a Cool 
Head About Y2K,'' through its Web site (www.investoradvice.org) or 
by calling 1-800-200-1819. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the many suggestions offered by these groups:  
</P>
<P>
	--Don't give out personal information over the telephone or on  
the Internet unless you're familiar with the business or initiated 
the contact. 
</P>
<P>
	--Contact your financial institution immediately to report any  
suspicious request for confidential account information. 
</P>
<P>
	--Be alert for any unauthorized charges to your credit card as  
well as unauthorized debits to your checking or savings account. 
</P>
<P>
	--Review all account statements on a timely basis.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
