<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Finish Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures finished mixed Wednesday  
on the Chicago Board of Trade in a lackluster session marked by investors' 
caution over the ongoing harvests. 
</P>
<P>
        Soybeans edged higher but volume was light amid uncertainties  
over the current crop. 
</P>
<P>
        Investors also were reluctant to trade actively in corn futures,  
with the biggest harvest weekend of the year upcoming. By the first 
of the week, the crop size will be better known. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat prices were buoyed initially by overnight export sales  
but fell back, pressured by the hard spring wheat harvest. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery fell 1/2 cent to $2.69 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/2 cent to $2.10 1/4 a bushel; December oats were 
unchanged at $1.12 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1/4 cent to 
$4.85 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures advanced. 
</P>
<P>
        October live cattle fell .40 cent to 66.35 cents a pound; October  
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 79.32 cents a pound; October lean hogs 
rose .73 cent to 45.55 cents a pound; February frozen pork bellies 
rose 2.88 cents to 59.65 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
