<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Blue Chips Fall; Dow Ends Off 74.40 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell again Wednesday, extending  
Tuesday's 225-point plunge by the Dow Jones industrial average and 
pushing the index to its lowest level in three months. 
</P>
<P>
	But strength among technology shares and smaller-company issues  
bolstered the broad market, with the Nasdaq composite index rising 
back toward record territory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow fell 74.40 to 10,524.07, about 800 points below its  
record-high close of 11,326.04 set Aug. 25. Yet even with the slide 
from record levels, the barometer of 30 major companies still holds 
a gain of 14.6 percent for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Broad-market indicators were mostly negative. But the strength  
in technology stocks helped lift the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock 
index by 2.93 to 1,310.51, while the Nasdaq composite rose 37.06 to 
2,858.16, about 30 points shy of a new high. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.03 to 427.53.  
</P>
<P>
	Leading the Dow's retreat on Wednesday were Union Carbide, down  
2 5/16 to 54 7/8; United Technologies, down 2 1/4 to 58 5/8; Procter &AMP; 
Gamble, down 2 1/4 to 98; IBM, down 1 15/16 to 125 3/16; and Goodyear, 
down 1 7/8 to 45 7/16. 
</P>
<P>
	3Com rose 1 5/16 to 28 5/8 as the most active Nasdaq issue after  
the maker of computer network products and Palm Pilot organizers 
topped Wall Street forecasts with late Tuesday's profit report. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other leading Nasdaq technology names, Microsoft rose 1  
7/16 to 96 1/16, Yahoo! rose 9 15/16 to 179 1/2 and eBay rose 8 1/2 to 
149 1/8. MindSpring Enterprises jumped nearly 25 percent, rising 6 1/2 to 
32 7/8, after the Internet service provider announced an alliance with 
Ceridian, a business services technology company. 
</P>
<P>
	There was little reaction to a Wednesday afternoon report by the  
Federal Reserve saying ``moderate-to-brisk rates of growth'' in the 
economy are contributing to widespread labor shortages, a major 
force behind inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Fed said in one of its periodic surveys on regional  
business conditions, consumer prices have remained stable. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed policy-makers will use the report when they meet Oct. 5 to  
review the central bank's stance on interest rates. Investors have 
been worried that the Fed will raise interest rates for a third 
time this year to fight inflation, a move that would raise 
borrowing costs and erode corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	More worrisome Wednesday was another weak day for the dollar on  
foreign exchange markets. The dollar fell for a third straight 
session against the Japanese yen, spiraling back toward last week's 
3 1/2-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak dollar can be inflationary by making imports more  
expensive in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	With no major economic reports due until late next week, ``The  
dollar has become the main focus of attention -- the thought that 
the dollar in itself could become a reason to raise interest 
rates,'' said Richard A. Dickson, a technical analyst at Scott &AMP; 
Stringfellow Inc. in Richmond, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickson also stressed concerns that a sagging dollar makes U.S.  
investments less appealing to foreign investors by making the 
payoff less valuable in other currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other stock trading Wednesday, declining issues outnumbered  
advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the New York Stock Exchange, while 
Nasdaq decliners led by a smaller margin. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume of all NYSE-listed stocks totaled 977.22 million shares,  
up slightly from Tuesday's 970.43 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 3.39 percent,  
Germany's DAX index fell 0.83 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 fell 
0.73 percent and France's CAC-40 fell 0.97 percent. 




  	   	
</P>
