<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hero Officer's Suicide Puzzles N.J. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CRANFORD, N.J. (AP) -- He was a bona fide hero, a decorated  
police officer, a loving father, a loyal friend. By most accounts, 
Lt. Russell Wilde had it all. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the police chief's son and a 14-year veteran honored more  
than a dozen times with citations for bravery, including the 
prestigious Carnegie Medal for heroism in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was surprised when he worked 36 consecutive hours plus  
another full shift overseeing the emergency response to severe 
flooding caused by rains from Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	But they can't explain what happened next.  
</P>
<P>
	Wilde worked from Thursday morning through Friday night, then  
got a few hours rest before returning to work for a Saturday shift. 
That night, he took his wife, Tracy, to the wedding of rookie 
Patrolman Ed Davenport. 
</P>
<P>
	When they returned home, Wilde walked into his bedroom, pulled  
out his .45-caliber police-issue pistol and shot himself. Dead at 
33. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, about 350 mourners filled the pews of St.  
Michael's Roman Catholic Church to pay tribute. Wilde's coffin was 
escorted into the church by uniformed officers as the skirl of 
bagpipers outside mingled with the organ. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilde's suicide stunned this tranquil bedroom community of  
22,600 some 15 miles west of New York City. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just devastating,'' said Loretta Honeywell, 66, a  
crossing guard who has known Wilde since he was a teen-ager. ``He 
had it all. I can't imagine the strain that would get the poor kid 
to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suicide experts say it might have been triggered by deeper  
problems that Wilde kept hidden from others. Co-workers believe the 
exhausting work session pushed Wilde over the edge. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a model husband, a model father, a model policeman,''  
said police Lt. Robert Schafer. ``An intelligent man, a logical 
man. We have 50 people in our department. He would be No. 52 that I 
would expect this from.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Growing up, Russell Scott Wilde aspired to be just like his  
father, Police Chief Harry Wilde. He got a two-year degree in 
criminal justice and joined the force in 1985 at age 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years later, he was vacationing on Long Beach Island when he  
and two other men heard the screams of 11-year-old Amy Meissner and 
her 18-year-old sister Bonnie. They had been pulled out to sea by a 
riptide and were struggling to stay afloat. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilde and the other men swam 300 feet out, managed to load the  
girls onto a surfboard and return them to shore. Wilde ``wouldn't 
leave the girls alone to try to save himself,'' then-Police Chief 
Robert Guertin wrote in an application for the Carnegie Medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilde and the others each won $2,500 and a bronze medal.  
</P>
<P>
	On the job, he built a similar reputation. His personnel file at  
the Cranford Police Department is a 2-inch thick testimonial to his 
bravery, street smarts and compassion. 
</P>
<P>
	He solved killings, foiled carjackings, twice saved people's  
lives applying CPR, broke up a prostitution ring and arrested a 
burglary suspect believed responsible for a series of thefts, 
according to letters of citation in the file. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was the kind of guy who wouldn't ask you to do anything he  
wouldn't do,'' said Capt. Eric Mason. ``He didn't sit behind a desk 
and give orders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilde was right there when Hurricane Floyd's wrath spilled into  
the Rahway River, causing it to overflow. More than 350 people had 
to be evacuated from their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were working all-out, from Thursday on. He was the incident  
commander and he was the point man in the rescue and recovery 
efforts. Any complaints came to him. There was no rest,'' Mason 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, he did rest. But maybe not enough.  
</P>
<P>
	``I saw Tracy that day,'' said neighbor Kathleen Davis, the wife  
of a fellow officer. ``She was saying how he was really tired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the wedding, Wilde and his wife returned to their neatly  
kept $170,000 home. He pulled out his gun and shot himself. The 
couple's sons, Russell Jr., 7, and Hayden, 4, were not home at the 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a psychologist, but you go long hours without taking  
time off, that's got to be a contributing factor,'' Mason said 
Tuesday at police headquarters, where purple and black bunting hung 
over the entrances and officers wore black bands across their 
silver badges. 
</P>
<P>
	John Violanti, a University of Buffalo professor who has written  
books about police suicides, said Wilde may have been frustrated by 
his inability to help flood victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have people out there who think they have to be perfect  
cops,'' Violanti said. ``If in some way they feel they've failed 
that image of themself, it's devastating. Sometimes, those hero 
standards are hard to bear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Psychologist Lanny Berman, executive director of the American  
Association of Suicidology, said family problems and alcohol abuse 
are among the most prevalent factors in police suicides. 
</P>
<P>
	``Suicides don't just happen. There's more to the story. The  
long hours of work may have shifted his coping ability. He may not 
have been thinking real clearly. But that doesn't explain a 
suicide,'' Berman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family wasn't talking. A man who answered a knock at the  
door of Wilde's home waved off a reporter Tuesday. In a brief 
interview with The Star-Ledger of Newark, Wilde's father could shed 
no light on what happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Saying he was a model son doesn't do him justice,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
