<HEADLINE> Bonds Change Little in Quiet Market / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices moved little Wednesday in an  
uneventful session. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1/16  
point, or 62 1/2 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.08 percent from 6.09 
percent on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged, while intermediate maturities rose 1/32 to 3/32 
point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar and United States stock markets again drove what  
little activity there was in the bond markets. The dollar slipped a 
little more against the yen, and U.S. stocks fell for a third 
straight day. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors tend to seek the safety of fixed income securities  
such as bonds when stocks are sliding. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
rose to 4.81 percent, up from 4.77 percent Tuesday. The discount 
rose 0.03 percentage point to 4.68 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields rose to 5.06 percent with a discount of 4.86  
percent, up 0.01 percentage point. One-year yields slipped to 5.22 
percent as the discount fell to 4.95 percent, down 0.01 percentage 
point from Tuesday's level. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.25 percent from late Tuesday's 5.06 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds was unchanged at 112 13/32. The average 
yield to maturity was also unchanged at 5.89 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
