<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricanes Wash Away Small Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) -- Pelican Spit, a 37-acre chunk of sand  
dunes off the Georgia coast, was reabsorbed into the Atlantic Ocean 
as hurricanes Dennis and Floyd swept through. 
</P>
<P>
	The spit was an important nesting habitat for shore birds, but  
nature often creates and destroys sand bars, spits and even barrier 
islands, said Brad Winn, a biologist with the Georgia Department of 
Natural Resources. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Georgia's coastline was spared from the most serious  
hurricane damage and Pelican Spit probably will re-emerge, Winn 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pelican Spit was worn down by Hurricane Dennis earlier this  
month, leaving it as a few sand dunes above the Atlantic's lapping 
waves. After Floyd last week, the dunes disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	Pelican Spit historically supported colonies of nesting royal  
terns and black skimmers. This summer, the state labeled Pelican 
Spit as a critical bird habitat, prohibiting people from visiting 
nesting areas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
