<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury To Decide Fate of Supremacist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- Jurors today were considering whether to  
levy the death penalty against a white supremacist they had 
convicted of mutilating and killing a black man by dragging him 
behind a pickup truck. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence R. Brewer, 32, faces life in prison or death by  
injection for the 1998 murder of James Byrd Jr., who was chained by 
his ankles to the truck and dragged for three miles over a country 
road outside the East Texas town of Jasper. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at this man's life, if you put his life in a  
capsule, based on the evidence, he is not a future danger to 
society,'' Brewer's attorney, Lane Walker, said today in closing 
arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker said Brewer, a convicted burglar, had no history of  
violence while he was in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, that's the only place on this earth since he  
was 14 years old where he's been able to function,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said Byrd's death  
shows Brewer is dangerous and should be condemned. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Brewer) had no reason on earth to hurt him except for the  
color of his skin,'' Gray said. ``There can't really be any 
question ... sometime in the future, when they get a chance, when 
Russell Brewer gets a chance, he would hurt another person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jury must answer three questions: whether Brewer intended to  
kill Byrd, whether he is a future danger to society and whether any 
mitigating circumstances about him should be considered. 
</P>
<P>
	If the jury unanimously answers ``yes'' to the first two  
questions and ``no'' to the third, Brewer goes to death row and 
joins former prison buddy John W. King, 24, who in February was 
condemned for killing Byrd. 
</P>
<P>
	A third man, Shawn A. Berry, 24, is to be tried next month in  
the slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, a psychiatrist testifying for the prosecution said  
Brewer never reformed despite several chances, and would be a 
future danger. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unlike those of us who wonder what our own potential for  
violence might be, Mr. Brewer answered that question,'' said Dr. 
Edward Gripon. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution has contended Brewer was the racist ideologue  
who taught King and Berry his views, and that his position as 
leader of a white supremacist prison group, the Confederate Knights 
of America, showed the depth of his commitment to racism. 
</P>
<P>
	A clinical psychologist, Dan Roberts, testified for the defense  
that Brewer was a failure as the leader, or ``Exalted Cyclops,'' of 
the supremacist group because he was socially incompetent. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wanted to be the leader, but it was like Fred Flintstone  
wanting to be the Grand Poobah of the Water Buffalo Club,'' Roberts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd's father and Brewer's father met outside the courtroom  
Tuesday, shook hands and embraced. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish we'd met under different circumstances,'' Lawrence  
Brewer Sr. told James Byrd Sr. ``I want you to know I'm awful 
embarrassed by this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Verrett, James Byrd Jr.'s sister, comforted the defendant's  
mother, Helen Brewer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realize you're in pain, too,'' Ms. Verrett said. ``You did  
all you can to raise him and taught him. And that's all you can 
do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
