<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Tumble / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices posted their biggest one-day  
drop in nearly a year today following the Bank of Japan's decision 
to keep its monetary policy unchanged. The U.S. dollar fell against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average tumbled 607.03  
points, or 3.39 percent, to close at 17,325.76. On Tuesday, the 
average closed up 357.53 points, or 2.04 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline was the largest one-day drop for the Nikkei since  
Oct. 8, 1998, when the index fell 799.55 points to close at 
13,026.06. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 104.28 yen in late trading, down 0.48 yen from  
late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its New York level of 104.87 
yen. The dollar traded in a relatively narrow range between 104.13 
yen and 105.37 yen in today's dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, shares of export-driven and high-tech  
companies like Sony and Toshiba were the hardest hit after the 
BOJ's decision prompted speculation the yen will head higher. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unexpected move that shocked financial markets, the  
central bank said Tuesday that it would not use monetary policy to 
weaken the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think people are amazed,'' said Robert Sasaki, head of the  
quantitative strategy group at Jardine Fleming Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had said an easing could curb upward pressure on the  
yen by lowering long-term interest rates. A lower yen would help 
Japanese exporters by making their products more cost-competitive 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	A fall in U.S. stock prices Tuesday also weighed on Tokyo  
shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``The yen rise and New York's fall prompted selling among  
dealers, although foreign investors weren't seen selling 
particularly heavily,'' said Ken Yamano, general manager at 
Taiheiyo Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell  
225.43 points to 10,598.47, pulled lower by factors including 
growing concerns about the weakening dollar and the rising U.S. 
trade deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 591 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, up from 561.76 million shares 
on Wednesday. Decliners far outnumbered advancers by 1044 to 206, 
while 91 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 50.05 points, or 3.27 percent, to close at 
1,479.28. The index closed up 10.05 points, or 0.66 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar slid against the yen but traded  
in a narrow range ahead of a Japanese holiday Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said players were also wary following volatile  
dollar-yen movements on Tuesday, as well as from a sense of 
uncertainty over possible joint intervention in the currency market 
by U.S. and Japanese authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The focus for dealers now is whether the United States will  
decide at the Group of Seven meeting of financial authorities in 
Washington on Saturday to aid the Japanese government in its 
attempt to curb the yen's rise, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 109.57 yen, down  
from 110.79 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark Japanese government bond rose to  
1.8100 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.7600 percent. Its price 
fell 0.09 point to 99.05. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
