<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 09:50:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airbus Partner Talks Hit Snag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Europe's efforts to streamline its aerospace and  
defense industry suffered a setback Wednesday when partners in 
Airbus Industrie failed to draft proposals to turn the group into a 
private company. 
</P>
<P>
	The four partners were due to report this week to their  
respective governments about their plans for restructuring the 
consortium that competes with U.S. aerospace giants Boeing and 
Lockheed Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	But Aerospatiale Matra, one of four companies in the Airbus  
consortium, said that round table negotiations among the partners 
were reduced to bilateral talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The French government reacted swiftly, saying it would consult  
its German, Spanish and British counterparts on the report's delay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will see with my colleagues what we can do'' to press the  
partners to move ahead, Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus is made up of Aerospatiale Matra, British Aerospace,  
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace (Dasa) and Spain's Construcciones 
Aeronauticas (Casa), which is to merge with Dasa. 
</P>
<P>
	Aerospatiale and Dasa both hold a 37.9-percent stake in Airbus,  
British Aerospace has 20 percent and Casa has 4.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts seemed unfazed by the setback.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've been talking for a long time. There was a deadline set  
for 1999, but it is likely that will be pushed back now,'' said 
Nicolas Baudouin of the research concern Standard &AMP; Poor's in 
Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now they are in bilateral talks but it's very difficult to  
imagine that anyone will want to be left out. It's not in anyone's 
interest to remain isolated,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Antoine Nodet, a financial analyst at Pinatton, a Paris  
brokerage firm, said the partners likely felt no pressure to link 
up. ``At this point there is no need. There is no urgency,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been working this way for 25 years. There is no proof  
that being a company would bring more capability to Airbus. Boeing 
is a company and is having trouble. Airbus is a success,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aerospatiale Matra's own merger this year was seen as part of  
the European restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	The French state had been reluctant to give up its majority  
ownership but finally agreed, retaining a stake of nearly 48 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the arguments in favor of privatization was that  
Aerospatiale's status as a state-owned company was obstructing 
moves to turn Airbus into a private concern. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive Philippe Camus said Aerospatiale Matra was  
determined to ensure Airbus press ahead with its plans to build a 
``super-jumbo'' airplane, the A-3XX. 
</P>
<P>
	The four governments have said previously it would be easier for  
them to provide financial support to develop the ``super-jumbo'' 
once Airbus became a private company. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Wednesday, Aerospatiale Matra reported a loss of 105  
million euros, or $109.02 million, for the first half of the year 
compared with a profit of 285 million euros a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The first half loss was in line with market expectations.  
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose to 5.75 billion euros, or $5.97 billion, from for  
the first half from 5.62 billion euros a year earlir. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects a better performance in the second half of  
the year although operating profits for the full year would be 
below 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Aerospatiale's helicopter, missiles and services divisions all  
registered operating losses while sales of Airbus and other 
aircraft remained strong. 
</P>
<P>
	The first half loss included 401 million euros (dlrs 416.35  
million) in foreign exchange charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Aerospatiale said orders in the first half of the year were down  
three percent from the first six months of last year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 09:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress, Feds Examine Pension Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Critics of ``cash-balance'' pension plans say  
they can be used without prejudice to older workers by disclosing 
the plans' financial details and allowing employees to choose 
whether to adopt them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Millions of Americans are rightly feeling pension anxiety  
because under current law there is no guarantee that their pension 
benefits will not be cut tomorrow,'' said Rep. Bernie Sanders, 
I-Vt., sponsor of a bill to permit worker choice and require the 
disclosures. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders spoke after the Senate Health, Education, Labor and  
Pensions Committee held a hearing Tuesday on the growing concerns 
over the cash-balance arrangements, which change the way pensions 
are calculated and can reduce benefits 30 percent or more for 
millions of older workers. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 325 companies with more than $330 billion in pension  
assets have adopted cash-balance plans recently, including such 
large companies as IBM, AT&AMP;T, Eastman Kodak Co. and Citigroup Inc. 
Nine of those largest companies employ more than 1 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	While companies contend the switch yields numerous advantages,  
the complaint for older workers boils down to simple math. 
</P>
<P>
	In cash-balance plans, employees accrue benefits at a steady  
rate throughout their careers instead of having retirement payments 
based on later, peak earnings as in traditional pensions. In 
thousands of cases, this translates into a cut in projected 
benefits of 30 percent to 50 percent for older workers, government 
experts estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Midcareer workers with long years of service are most likely  
to be hurt,'' said Sen. Jim Jeffords, R-Vt., the committee 
chairman. ``Those midcareer workers are the ones who were counting 
on the traditional plan for most of their retirement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing was the latest in a series of recent federal actions  
on cash-balance pensions, including an age discrimination 
investigation by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and a 
halt by the Internal Revenue Service of automatic approval of the 
plans. Several bills that would regulate the plans are pending in 
Congress, and a case concerning the plans is before the U.S. Tax 
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM's switch this summer is quickly becoming a national  
barometer for the debate. After triggering a very public employee 
revolt that has yet to subside, the company announced changes last 
week to provide more older workers with a choice between the 
traditional plan and the new one. 
</P>
<P>
	But many feel permanently betrayed and say laws should be  
changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``IBM management has broken a bond of trust with all of their  
U.S. employees,'' Bill Syverson, a 19-year IBM employee from 
Vermont, told the Senate panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Like dozens of other companies, IBM executives say they had good  
reasons for converting their pension plan -- not the least of which 
was that 75 percent of its high-tech competitors, such as Microsoft 
Corp. and Cisco Systems Inc., don't even offer pensions and have 
more money for other expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM human resources chief J. Thomas Bouchard told the Senate  
committee that the cash balance plan, more flexible, allows 
employees to receive lump-sum payouts if they change jobs or get a 
deferred annuity beginning at age 65. And IBM was able to offer 
employees more stock options and salary increases with the pension 
savings. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order to compete to retain and attract the people required  
to succeed in the future, we had to adjust IBM's overall 
compensation package,'' Bouchard said. ``That meant rebalancing 
what we paid out in cash versus benefits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Janet Krueger, a 23-year IBM employee from Rochester, Minn.,  
who quit over the flap, said IBM did a poor job of explaining 
differences between plans. Ms. Krueger, now part of the IBM 
Employees Benefit Action Coalition, insisted Tuesday the lack of 
communication was designed to keep workers in the dark. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was not a clue how we might figure it out,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Several members of Congress are pushing for changes. Sanders and  
Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., want to require detailed disclosure 
45 days in advance if companies plan to reduce benefits. In 
addition, they want companies to offer all employees a choice 
between old and new pension plans or face financial sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Jeffords backs a less-sweeping measure, Republican  
support for such reforms has been slow in coming. And corporate 
America is sending a clear message: Without varied benefit options, 
more companies will opt not to offer pensions. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
