<HEADLINE> Penguins Release Errey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Bob Errey, a left wing who played on Mario  
Lemieux's line when the Pittsburgh Penguins owner was a rookie in 
1984, was released Wednesday by the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	Errey, 35, was invited to training camp on a tryout basis. He  
appeared in two exhibition games, going scoreless with two penalty 
minutes. Errey once was San Jose's captain when current Penguins 
coach Kevin Constantine coached the Sharks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins also released defenseman David Wilkie and assigned  
forward Martin Sonnenberg to Wilkes-Barre-Scranton of the AHL. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkie, 25, also was invited to camp on a tryout basis.  
Sonnenberg, 21, played 44 games for Pittsburgh last season, scoring 
one goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The roster moves leave the Penguins with 18 forwards, nine  
defensemen and three goaltenders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
