<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United Technologies Cuts More Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- United Technologies Corp. plans to reduce  
its worldwide workforce by an additional 9,000 jobs as the company 
looks to reduce costs amid a downturn in the aerospace industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hartford, Conn.-based company also announced Wednesday that  
it plans close 8.5 million square feet in manufacturing and other 
space. Most of those closures are expected overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks are the latest move by UTC to restructure its  
business. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, UTC's jet-control's division Hamilton Sundstand  
announced it was cutting 1,500 jobs and consolidating plants. 
Previously announced cuts included 1,500 jobs at Pratt &AMP; Whitney; 
1,100 at Sikorsky Aircraft; 400 at Carrier Corp.; 700 at Pratt &AMP; 
Whitney-Canada; and 165 at Otis Elevator. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined with Wednesday's announcement, UTC plans to slash more  
than 14,000 jobs or 10 percent of its workforce over the next three 
years. UTC spokesman Peter Dalpe said the company would not give 
specifics on exactly where the jobs will be eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	``These steps are intended to assure that we maintain our  
competitiveness throughout our markets worldwide,'' UTC chairman 
and chief executive George David said. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said they were surprised by the scope of the  
reductions, given the already deep job cuts made by UTC recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought UTC had restructured and rationalized their  
operations a while ago, but this goes to show that they still have 
areas where they can improve their efficiency by reducing their 
manpower,'' said Richard Pettibone, an aerospace and defense 
analyst at Forecast International, based in Newtown, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	The company expects to spend about $1.15 billion in  
restructuring charges in 1999. T The third-quarter charge is 
estimated at about $750 million, while about $75 million in charges 
have already been recorded in the first two quarters. The remainder 
will be recorded in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	UTC provides a broad range of high technology products and  
supports services to the building systems and aerospace industry. 
It operates in 183 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	UTC shares fell $2.25, or 3.7 percent, to $58.62 1/2 on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
