<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of Sept. 26-Oct. 2:  
</P>
<P>
	70 years ago: George Arliss and Joan Bennett starred in  
``Disraeli.'' Arliss won an Oscar for his performance in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	65 years ago: Karen Morley and Tom Keene starred in King Vidor's  
``Our Daily Bread,'' Hollywood's first serious drama about the 
Depression. 
</P>
<P>
	45 years ago: ``The Tonight Show'' debuted on NBC. The show was  
hosted by Steve Allen. 
</P>
<P>
	And Ronald Reagan was the host of the ``General Electric  
Theater.'' 
</P>
<P>
	40 years ago: ``The Many Loves of Dobie Gillis,'' starring  
Dwayne Hickman, premiered on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	And ``The Twilight Zone,'' created and hosted by Rod Serling,  
made its debut on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Beach Boys made their debut on ``The Ed  
Sullivan Show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roy Orbison's ``Oh, Pretty Woman'' began a three-week run on top  
of the U.S. charts. 
</P>
<P>
	And ``Gilligan's Island'' premiered on CBS. The series starred  
Bob Denver and Alan Hale Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: The Beatles' final studio album, ``Abbey Road,''  
was released in Britain. The album stayed at the No. 1 spot on the 
British charts for 11 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: ``Murder, She Wrote,'' starring Angela Lansbury,  
premiered on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	And the New York Film Festival opened with ``Country,'' starring  
Jessica Lange, Sam Shepard and Wilford Brimley. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Johnny Carson donated $100,000 to help build an  
arts center in his hometown of Norfolk, Neb. Carson, the retired 
host of ``The Tonight Show,'' had previously donated money to a 
number of projects in Norfolk, a northeastern Nebraska community of 
about 21,500 people. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``Bill was not much of an actor when I first met him, and he  
struck me as the angriest man alive. He had this tremendous chip on 
his shoulder, as if the world owed him a living.'' -- Actor Robert 
Culp, referring to ``I Spy'' co-star Bill Cosby. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``There have been times when I didn't think that I was suffering  
enough. But in actual fact, it didn't have to be that way. I don't 
believe any of us has to suffer more than we already are suffering 
-- not for art, not for anything.'' -- Singer Eric Clapton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
