<DOCNO> APW19990922.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 09:50:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Perry: North Korea To Suspend Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The United States expects North Korea  
to announce soon a moratorium on missile tests in return for the 
partial lifting of U.S. sanctions on the communist state, a U.S. 
policy coordinator said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	William Perry, Washington's pointman on North Korea, said months  
of negotiations between U.S. and North Korean officials have led to 
an understanding that Pyongyang should make a formal announcement 
``in the weeks ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Pyongyang's Stalinist regime breaches that promise and goes  
ahead with long-range missile tests, the United States will restore 
sanctions and contain the North's military threat, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope and expect that in the weeks ahead, North Korea will  
make a definitive statement about the suspension of missile 
tests,'' Perry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Perry, the former U.S. defense secretary,  
met South Korean President Kim Dae-jung to discuss North Korea 
policy recommendations that he presented to President Clinton last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton lifted on Friday a half-century of restrictions on  
trade, travel and banking against North Korea, the most significant 
gesture toward Pyongyang since the 1950-53 Korean War. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanctions remain on sales of U.S. weapons and unlicensed exports  
of ``dual-use'' goods or technology -- items that could have 
military uses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Much more work has to be done, but this is the first step ...  
toward the removal of the threat and danger of war on the Korean 
Peninsula, and toward normal relations among the countries in the 
region,'' Perry said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we are unsuccessful in persuading North Korea to remove the  
threat, we must take actions to contain the threat,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea, which welcomed the U.S. move, reportedly plans to  
send Deputy Foreign Minister Kang Sok Ju to Washington in late 
October to discuss improving ties with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Kang, a close confidant of North Korean leader Kim Jong Il, will  
be the first top North Korean government official to visit 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea rattled nerves in Asia and Washington after firing a  
missile over Japan last year. The United States feared the North 
was on the verge of testing another missile, this one capable of 
striking Alaska or Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States fought on South Korea's side during the Korean  
War, and about 37,000 U.S. troops remain in the South under a 
defense treaty. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sooners Finding Success Through Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORMAN, Okla. (AP) -- After two years with an offense that was  
usually offensive, Oklahoma is back near the top of the national 
charts -- third in total offense, sixth in scoring. Just like old 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	Except it's not at all like old times.  
</P>
<P>
	These Sooners throw the football. A lot. They have thrown 99  
passes in the first two games, victories over Indiana State and 
Baylor. Quarterback Josh Heupel has already set single-game school 
records for touchdown passes (5), pass attempts (54), completions 
(37), passing yards (420) and total offense (397 yards). 
</P>
<P>
	Heupel's 68 completions through two games are more than any  
quarterback completed in a season during Barry Switzer's 16 years 
running the wishbone. 
</P>
<P>
	The option game at Oklahoma has essentially been dead since  
Switzer left 10 years ago. but his three successors all sought a 
balance between passing and running. 
</P>
<P>
	This offense doesn't. Coordinator Mike Leach looks to throw  
first, then run. Of Oklahoma's first 20 plays against Baylor last 
weekend, 15 were passes. 
</P>
<P>
	First-year coach Bob Stoops said he isn't surprised the offense  
has been so effective. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen it for a long time, played against it for three  
years,'' said Stoops, who as defensive coordinator at Florida went 
against Kentucky, where Leach was offensive coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen it everywhere that they have run this offense and  
this system with coach Leach, they've put up these kind of numbers. 
Why would here be any different?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps because Oklahoma's offense was anemic in the recent  
past. Quarterback play that was average at best, coupled with 
indecision by coach John Blake over which offense he wanted to use, 
resulted in problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with a 1,000-yard tailback, the Sooners averaged only 315  
yards and 18 points per game in Blake's final two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The offense used by Leach gives the quarterback a lot of  
freedom, and therefore requires especially good play from that 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	Heupel impressed Leach right away with his desire to study game  
film. He picked up the offense quickly and established himself as a 
leader, so much so that he was voted a captain after being on 
campus just a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	The left-hander doesn't have a particularly strong arm, but  
doesn't need one to direct a passing game that generally relies on 
short, quick-hitting routes. He has completed 72 percent of his 
passes so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt all along that Josh was a strong quarterback,'' Stoops  
said. ``We love his attitude, love the way he prepares. With the 
summer he's had, the spring he had, we figured Josh would be pretty 
solid and he's definitely been that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Watson To Interview with Mariners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Bob Watson, set to interview for the Seattle  
Mariners' general manager spot, insisted Wednesday he's the right 
person to help turn around the struggling team. 
</P>
<P>
	Other candidates mentioned for the job include rising star Billy  
Beane, GM of the Oakland A's. Watson did not sound worried about 
his competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're in trouble. Take a look at my credentials. Across the  
board, from a player, a coach, an assistant GM, a GM, and you tell 
me they're not in trouble,'' Watson, 53, said in a phone interview 
from his Houston home. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariners GM Woody Woodward will resign effective Oct. 31.  
Seattle won the AL West in 1995 and 1997, but slumped to 76-85 last 
year and has been below .500 for much of this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners supposedly contacted Beane, 37, earlier this week.  
He has been credited with making trades that have enabled the A's 
to contend this year for a wild-card berth with a payroll of only 
$22 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson said he wasn't necessarily chasing a job when Mariners  
president Chuck Armstrong called him this week. Watson said he did 
not know what day his interview would take place. 
</P>
<P>
	Mariners manager Lou Piniella and Watson played together for the  
New York Yankees in the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson was GM of the Houston Astros for two years before  
becoming GM of the New York Yankees after the 1995 season. Watson 
helped build the Yankees into the 1996 World Series champions, but 
left prior to the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his experience as Yankees GM ``seasoned me to the point  
where I won't be surprised by anything. I wouldn't be remiss in 
saying my experience here in Houston would be something that would 
serve me well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watson acknowledged he'd have some catching up to do, after  
spending a year-and-a-half out of baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``The game changes basically every day,'' Watson said. ``There's  
a lot that goes on and I'll try and get up to speed as fast as I 
can if I'm the one they choose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watson said the Seattle job would be appealing for a number of  
reasons, including a new ballpark -- Safeco Field -- and star players 
Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have some of the top talent in the major leagues,'' he  
said. ``You probably have the marquee players in baseball in your 
center fielder and your shortstop,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey and Rodriguez are both eligible to become free agents  
after the 2000 season. Club officials have said retaining the two 
players is a priority, but so far no significant progress has been 
been made in that direction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
