<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jug's Top Two Favorites Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DELAWARE, Ohio (AP) -- It won't be difficult for the two  
favorites in Thursday's Little Brown Jug to keep an eye on each 
other. 
</P>
<P>
	Blissful Hall and The Panderosa will be right next to one  
another in the first of three divisions of the second leg of the 
Triple Crown of Pacing for 3-year-olds at Delaware County 
Fairgrounds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mile-long elimination, the first few feet could make all  
the difference. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're leaving,'' John Campbell, The Panderosa'a driver, said  
of his plans. ``We're not dropping back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the banked, half-mile track, the early front-runner has a  
huge advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'd be nice if we could step around The Panderosa before we  
hit the first turn,'' said Ron Pierce, driver for Blissful Hall. 
``We'll have to see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The top three finishers in each division advance to a second  
heat. If a division winner wins that, he wins the Jug. Otherwise, 
the four winners decide the Jug champion in a raceoff. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Pierce ended up in the sulky of Shady Character when  
Mike Lachance -- who had driven Shady Character to an elimination 
victory by four lengths -- elected to drive Artiscape in the final. 
Lachance ended up fourth, while Pierce got Shady Character off to a 
fast start, then held on to beat stablemate Cam Knows Best by a 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been thinking about it the last couple of weeks,'' Pierce  
said. ``I loved the experience I had last yea,r but it would mean a 
little more to me with this Blissful Hall colt because I have been 
driving him all along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He, however. wishes he wasn't outside The Panderosa at the post.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not really happy with the draw,'' Pierce said. ``Hopefully  
we'll overcome it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blissful Hall won the first leg of the Triple Crown, taking the  
Cane Pace three weeks ago by 2 1/4 lengths over Heartbeat Mindale. The 
horse has won eight of 11 starts with two seconds this year and has 
earned $529,395. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's quite a horse right now. He's a gorilla,'' Pierce said.  
``When you let him pace, he can really go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Panderosa, who has won five of eight starts, with one  
second, this year, will start in the No. 6 hole, with Blissful Hall 
next to him on the outside. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been questions about The Panderosa's mental and  
physical fitness after he broke stride in two of his last three 
starts -- including the Cane as he was making a move at the 5/8ths 
pole. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly got a break when The Panderosa broke,'' Blissful  
Hall trainer Ben Wallace said after the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Glazer, The Panderosa's owner, is anything but cocky even  
though his horse has won more than $1 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly aren't brimming with confidence,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Island Fantasy, with Lachance seeking a fifth Jug win, is the  
favorite in the second division. 
</P>
<P>
	The favorite in the third division of the 54th annual Jug is  
Grinfromeartoear, riding a two-racee winning streak, including his 
most recent start Sept. 11 in the Brown Jug Preview. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
