<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 04:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston To Greet 2000 a Bit Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Bostonians might want to begin chilling their  
champagne a bit earlier than usual on Dec 31. The city plans to pop 
the corks at 7 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Rejecting customary Eastern Standard Time, the city has  
announced it will ring in the New Year when it arrives in 
Greenwich, England. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be marking the millennium when it's midnight in  
Greenwich, according to Greenwich Mean Time, which is the 
universally accepted standard of time for the world,'' Mayor Tom 
Menino said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan means Boston would be the first U.S. city to celebrate  
the new millennium. Planners for the city's First Night celebration 
expect about 2 million attendees, about 500,000 more than in 
previous years. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwich Mean Time was established in 1884 by representatives  
from 25 countries who gathered in Washington to establish a 
standardized time system. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenwich was selected as the benchmark because the city's Royal  
Observatory played a key role in early navigation and timekeeping 
at sea by tracking celestial movements. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
