<DOCNO> APW19990922.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Asian Stock Markets Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed sharply lower  
Wednesday, taking a cue from Tokyo's plunge and Wall Street's 
overnight decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in Tokyo posted their biggest one-day drop this year  
following the Bank of Japan's decision to keep its monetary policy 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average plunged  
3.4 percent, or 607.03 points, to close at 17,325.76. On Tuesday, 
the average gained 357.53 points, or 2.04 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar continued to slide against  
the yen, following the central bank's unexpected decision Tuesday 
not to use monetary policy to weaken the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 104.28 yen in late trading, down 0.48 yen from  
late Tuesday in Tokyo and also below its New York level of 104.87 
yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of export-driven and high-tech companies were the hardest  
hit after the BOJ's decision prompted fears of a stronger yen. A 
lower yen would help Japanese exporters by making their products 
more cost-competitive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks closed lower, tracking losses in Tokyo and Wall  
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index shed 232.84 points, or 1.7 percent, to end  
at 13,187.62. On Tuesday, the index fell 51.91 points, or 0.3 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 225.43 points, or 2.1  
percent, to 10,598.47 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Bangkok, declines on regional bourses and a weaker baht  
currency continued to hurt sentiment and forced a sell-off in 
banking and finance stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 3.6 percent, or 15.39  
points, to 410.15. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kuala Lumpur, the key index tumbled 2.45 percent as  
profit-taking was made more relentless by the regional market 
weakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors moved quickly to cash in on Tuesday's steep 4.1  
percent gain in the key index, which was propelled by a central 
bank announcement that the country's controversial capital controls 
would be relaxed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's Composite Index ended at  
721.17 points, down 18.13 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Taipei's stock market was closed for a second day because of a  
deadly earthquake that rocked the island Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices in plummeted 2.0 percent on worries  
about the yen's strength and the overnight declines in New York. 
The benchmark Straits Times Index fell 41.38 points, or 2.0 
percent, to 2,067.66. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian share prices closed lower. The Composite  
Index lost 0.3 percent, or 1.816 points, to close at 545.448. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares fell on renewed concerns over a  
possible U.S. interest rate hike and Wall Street's overnight 
decline. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 18.81 
points, or 0.9 percent, to 2,107.73. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares closed lower, as investors cashed in  
on recent gains. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index ended down 
1.7 percent, or 15.85 points, to 941.57. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market bucked the regional trend,  
closing marginally higher on a stronger gold price and positive 
sentiment generated by the government's proposed cuts to company 
taxes. The All Ordinaries Index gained 2.9 points, or 0.1 percent, 
to 2,901.7. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower in line with  
regional losses. The NZSE-40 Capital Index closed 19.96 points, or 
nearly 1.0 percent, lower at 2,064.98. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Manhattan `Purchase' in 1626 Letter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A 1626 letter containing what is believed to be  
the only known mention of the Dutch purchase of Manhattan for $24 
has been put on display at the New York Historical Society 
</P>
<P>
	No deed or official document of Manhattan's sale to the Dutch  
from the Lenape Indians exists. The creased yellowed letter, 
written by a ship captain to the governors of the Dutch West India 
Company, briefly mentions the transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	``They (the Dutch settlers) have bought the island of Manhattes  
from the wildmen for the value of sixty guilders,'' it reads. The 
letter, put on display Monday, continues with a laundry list of 
items being sent to Amsterdam including beaver, rat, and mink 
skins. 
</P>
<P>
	Herbert Kraft, anthropologist and director of the Seton Hall  
University Museum, said the land transfer might not have been that 
big a deal, particularly because many of the Lenape lived in what 
is now New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the time it was not a great piece of property,'' Kraft said  
of Manhattan. ``There were loads of mosquitoes and it was very 
rocky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Rementer, a Lenape descendant and head of the Lenape  
Language Project in Bartlesville, Okla., said the Indians who 
``sold'' Manhattan to the Dutch did not share European notions of 
land ownership. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 19:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Showalter Involved in Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Moments after Arizona beat Colorado 11-3  
Wednesday, Diamondbacks manager Buck Showalter exchanged heated 
words with an unidentified man accompanying Rockies co-vice 
chairman Dick Monfort. 
</P>
<P>
	The man was passing in front of Arizona's third-base dugout. The  
man reportedly shouted at Showalter, who shouted back. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-year manager later had to be restrained by Arizona  
pitching coach Mark Connor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know who it was,'' Showalter said. ``I don't think  
that needs to be discussed except to say it was something that was 
unfortunate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Monfort, his brother Charlie nor anyone associated with  
the Rockies would comment on the incident. Nor was anyone available 
to identify the other person involved in the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never saw it,'' Colorado manager Jim Leyland said. ``I  
didn't know it happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leyland later called Showalter and offered an apology.  
</P>
<P>
	``I understand their frustration because we have been at the  
bottom,'' Showalter said. ``It is surprising because Colorado has 
been a first-class organization and will continue to be one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was the latest of several incidents involving Showalter and  
the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rockies accused Showalter and the Diamondbacks of spying on  
them in spring training before the 1998 season. Showalter and 
then-Colorado manager Don Baylor did not shake hands at the season 
opener for both teams last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona pitcher Omar Daal beaned Colorado star Larry Walker on  
May 22. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:00:22 </DATE_TIME>
