<DOCNO> APW19990922.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 02:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arkansas Forward No. 1 Pick in CBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Arkansas forward Derek Hood, who led the  
Southeastern Conference in rebounding last season, was taken by the 
Quad City Thunder on Tuesday as the No. 1 pick in the Continental 
Basketball Association draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-8 Hood, who wasn't taken in the NBA draft in June,  
averaged 9.5 points and 7.6 rebounds in his four years with the 
Razorbacks. His 10.3 rebound average last season was ninth in the 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a great honor to be selected as the top pick,'' said  
Hood, who will still try to make an roster when training camps open 
next month. ``The CBA's a fine place and a lot of people have gone 
through there on the way to the NBA. If it doesn't work out in the 
NBA for me I can follow the CBA track and use it as a stepping 
stone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The La Crosse Bobcats had the next two picks in the draft and  
selected Arizona center A.J. Bramlett and Texas swingman Kris 
Clack. Quad City took Nebraska center Venson Hamilton and 
Cincinnati guard Melvin Levett with the next two picks. 
</P>
<P>
	The final four picks of the first round were North Carolina  
Charlotte swingman Galen Young by Grand Rapids, St. Paul's forward 
Antwain Smith by Yakima, Villanova guard John Celestand by Sioux 
Falls, and Maryland swingman Laron Profit by Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-team league's draft lasted 10 rounds.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
