<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 03:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Working on Farmers' Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The cost of bailing out the nation's farm  
economy reached $8 billion as Republican congressional leaders 
introduced their plan to aid growers who have been hurt by low 
prices or lost crops to droughts and floods. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP plan, released Tuesday, closely tracks a $7.4 billion  
package that the Senate attached last month to an agricultural 
spending bill. But it added $500 million for weather-related 
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the money would go toward compensating farmers for a  
second year of depressed commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats were expected to push for hundreds of millions of  
dollars more in disaster aid, but some conceded that the $8 billion 
plan would be approved by the House-Senate conference committee 
that was writing the final version of the appropriations bill. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders, struggling to find a way to pay for even the $8  
billion without raiding the Social Security surplus, refused to go 
any higher, said Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., the lead Senate 
negotiator on the spending bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're up against the limit on our allocation,'' Cochran said.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans had hoped to finish work on the appropriations bill  
late Tuesday but the negotiations were put off until today because 
of a disagreement over dairy policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Cochran said Congress could consider additional aid in 2000 to  
cover this year's crop losses. North Carolina lawmakers were 
expected to seek $1 billion or more for crops and livestock 
destroyed by Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect the administration to monitor the situation  
closely'' and request more money if it's needed, Cochran said. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Department officials say they need $1 billion to  
compensate farmers for losses that already had occurred this year 
from drought in the East and flooding in the upper Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Kay Thatcher, a lobbyist for the American Farm Bureau  
Federation, said the GOP proposal was ``woefully inadequate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans control both the House and Senate, and one of the  
Democratic negotiators, North Dakota Sen. Byron Dorgan, said 
Republicans had the votes to pass the $8 billion plan. ``They're 
not talking to us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The House did not have the farm assistance in its version of the  
appropriations bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain prices plummeted during the financial crisis in Asia and  
have yet to recover because of overproduction worldwide. Prices for 
corn and soybeans are at their lowest levels in more than a decade. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:46:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Timorese Loot Government Warehouses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Thousands of desperate East Timorese  
looted warehouses in Dili today, hauling off sacks of rice, flour 
and cooking oil before international peacekeepers turned the hungry 
crowds back. 
</P>
<P>
	The multinational force has largely restored order to East  
Timor's razed capital after more than two weeks of mayhem, but 
pro-Indonesian militants pulled off what appeared to be their first 
show of resistance by killing a Western journalist. 
</P>
<P>
	About 150 helicopter-borne troops landed in Baucau, East Timor's  
second-largest town, securing the airport and extending the reach 
of the multinational force beyond the Dili area for the first time, 
said Brig. Mark Evans, commander of the land forces. 
</P>
<P>
	Baucau is 80 miles east of Dili, and its airport can accommodate  
heavy transport planes that could bring troops and food for 
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The looters were among thousands of residents who had returned  
to East Timor's capital, Dili, after days of hiding in nearby 
forests and mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Although relief flights took off from Australia for the first  
time in three days today, growing desperation boiled over when a 
mob besieged Indonesian government-owned warehouses in Dili, broke 
down the doors and started taking everything they could grab. 
</P>
<P>
	A small squad of Indonesian soldiers guarding the complex was  
overwhelmed by the numbers and let the people in. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes later, about 30 armed Australian soldiers arrived at the  
scene and pulled the crowd back, blocking the entrances, but not 
before hundreds of bags of food were stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	``We needed rice. We were hungry,'' said one man who ran from  
the scene with a sack of rice on his shoulders. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri, commander of Indonesian  
forces in the territory, said the body of Sander Thoenes, a 
30-year-old reporter for London's Financial Times newspaper, was 
found in the Dili suburb of Becora, the scene of heavy activity by 
militias and their Indonesian military backers. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoenes was killed after six men in Indonesian police uniforms  
fired at him while he was traveling on a motorcycle, according to 
the vehicle's driver, Florindo Araujo. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia's military said today it will stop flying journalists  
to East Timor because food, medicine and other necessities were too 
scarce. The decision was not related to the journalist's death, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate incident, a car carrying two journalists was  
attacked by what Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, the Australian commander 
of the force, said were assumed to be ``militia elements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cosgrove said the attacks were ``obviously a reaction to our  
presence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It would appear that the militia have attempted to step up  
some activities as a show that all is not yet secure. Well, I would 
agree with that,'' said Cosgrove. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the troops, which arrived Monday, were restoring a  
measure of order to Dili, ``on recent events, it is still a 
dangerous place,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In West Timor, the commander of the most notorious pro-Jakarta  
militia warned that East Timor ``will continue to seethe and there 
will be the possibility of a civil war,'' unless an acceptable 
solution for the territory is found. 
</P>
<P>
	That solution should be the division of East Timor, with  
pro-Indonesian forces getting a share, said Eurico Guterres, of the 
Aitarak militia. He was quoted by the Antara news agency from 
Kupang. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will fight until the last blood to defend our territory,''  
Guterres said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, Indonesia's security affairs minister, Faisal  
Tanjung, said the government would revoke martial law soon because 
the situation had almost returned to normal in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesians planned to transfer all law enforcement duties  
to the multinational force, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Western diplomat in Jakarta said Indonesian troops were  
pulling out of East Timor ``as fast as they can'' in an effort to 
avoid any incidents with the peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dili, the peacekeepers stepped up efforts to track down  
potential troublemakers and disarm everyone except authorized 
Indonesian soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans said hundreds of weapons had been confiscated, from  
machetes to rifles. ``We have lost count of the number of 
weapons,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian soldiers arrested a man being chased and kicked by a  
crowd that accused him of being a notorious militiaman involved in 
the killing and looting. Eight other suspected militiamen were seen 
sitting under guard. 
</P>
<P>
	A body was found in a water well in Dili, and residents said  
they feared more bodies were there. The well is behind the home of 
Manuel Carrascalao, a prominent pro-independence supporter. 
Australian peacekeepers were summoned to the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	In Darwin, Australia, Jose Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao and other  
East Timorese leaders began a weeklong session to begin planning a 
U.N.-administered interim government and the subsequent steps 
toward full independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Gusmao met Tuesday night with U.N. officials, their first  
meeting since the former resistance leader was released from 
Indonesian prison and house arrest earlier this month. He had been 
confined for nearly seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	About 3,000 peacekeepers were due to arrive by today, nearly  
one-half of the planned contingent of 7,500. 
</P>
<P>
	The militias spared almost nothing in their systematic  
destruction of Dili, the capital city of 120,000, after East Timor 
voted overwhelmingly for independence from Indonesia in an Aug. 30 
U.N.-supervised ballot. Hundreds have died and hundreds of 
thousands have fled their homes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:46:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
