<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Bank Eyes Currency Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- With Colombian President Andres Pastrana  
in Washington seeking a financial bailout, the country's central 
bank fought Wednesday to prop up the national currency as an 
economic crisis deepened. 
</P>
<P>
	Already stung by a string of credit rating downgrades and a  
nearly 30 percent devaluation of the Colombian peso, the government 
sold $70 million to support the beleaguered currency a day after 
disclosing an unprecedented plunge in economic output. 
</P>
<P>
	Gross domestic product plummeted 7.6 percent in the second  
quarter, compared with the same period in 1998 -- Colombia's worst 
three-month decline this century, the National Statistics 
Department announced Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reduction in economic activity for the trimester owes  
chiefly to a drop in agricultural production spurred by a decline 
in coffee production, which fell by 16.74 percent,'' said the 
agency's director, Rene Verswyvel. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee is Colombia's No. 2. legal export after oil, but the crop  
this year has yielded 20 percent fewer beans, while coffee prices 
have dropped abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	A lack of confidence in the economy's ability to recover in the  
near term has spurred demand for the U.S. dollar, which has gained 
28.1 percent against the Colombian peso so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a devaluation would help exports in a country with a strong  
manufacturing base, but Colombia is not such a country. Much of 
that owes to the influence of the trade in illegal drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	In large part because of Colombia's deepening civil conflict,  
the country has been rated an increasingly high risk for 
international investors. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Standard &AMP; Poors downgraded Colombia's  
investment-grade credit rating, encouraging a 0.7 percent drop in 
the value of the peso against the dollar. The peso closed at 1,993 
to the dollar on Wednesday -- at the upper end of the trading level 
the bank's directors say they are determined to defend. 
</P>
<P>
	A month ago, Moody's Investors Service Inc. similarly cut  
Colombia's prized investment-grade credit rating, restricting the 
country's access to cheap foreign loans. 
</P>
<P>
	With tax revenues falling, the government's budget deficit has  
grown to 5 percent of gross domestic product, or $5 billion, the 
Finance Ministry said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has asked the International Monetary Fund for a  
$3 billion line of credit to help spur economic recovery. But under 
such an agreement, it would likely be obliged to reduce the budget 
deficit considerably with a strict austerity plan. 
</P>
<P>
	That would mean less in government transfers for municipalities  
already unable to provide many basic services, a restructuring of a 
health care system that can't pay its bills and a broadening of the 
tax base in a country with widespread tax evasion. 
</P>
<P>
	A strict austerity plan also could trigger labor unrest. Unions  
called a two-day general strike in August to protest anticipated 
belt-tightening measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastrana has insisted Colombia will meet all its foreign debt  
obligations and in Washington was seeking $700 million from the 
Inter-American Development Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombian leader is seeking $3.5 billion in all from  
international sources -- chiefly the United States -- for a 
three-year plan to combat the drug trade, fortify the legal system 
and rescue endangered social programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastrana said on Wednesday that he received ``big support'' from  
President Clinton for his plan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
