<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 11:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Central Park Considers Fees for Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Throwing your next family picnic will be as easy  
as a walk in the park, the mayor says, despite a report that the 
city is planning to start demanding a $25 fee for large gatherings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily News reported today that the city wants to enforce a  
little-known law requiring any group of 20 or more people to pay 
the fee and apply for a permit 30 days in advance. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would require permits for any ``contest, exhibit,  
ceremony, parade, athletic competition, reading or picnic involving 
more than 20 people,'' the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said the story is false and there  
will be no change in the city's longstanding policy on large groups 
in parks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Parks Department has had for at least 15 years the same  
policy,'' he said. ``The same policy will remain in effect. ... If 
you want to have your children in the park, you're not going to 
have to pay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parks Commissioner Henry Stern said the permit regulation  
generally targets organized events like concerts or theatrical 
performances. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's enforced by the rule of reason,'' Stern said. ``If  
there's a private social gathering, you're not disturbing anyone, 
there's no one that's going around with a clicker to see when the 
21st person arrives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than 2,000 such permits were issued last year for the 326  
parks in Manhattan; no figures were available for the other four 
boroughs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Critics Weigh In on Diet Drug Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Paying for years of regular medical checkup for  
the people who took the diet drug fen-phen was supposed to be the 
hardest pill for American Home Products to swallow as part of its 
weight-loss medication quagmire. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's proven to be the easy part in the drug maker's  
settlement talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the tentative national settlement is likely to break  
down over how much the company wants to pay patients allegedly 
injured by the once-popular drug cocktail, say attorneys close to 
the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home has offered to pay $2.8 billion to settle claims  
by people who say they developed heart valve injuries from taking 
fen-phen. The company has also agreed to set up a $1.2 billion fund 
to provide medical monitoring of people who took the drug 
combination, but have no signs of injury, say lawyers familiar with 
the talks who spoke on condition of anonymity. An additional 
$410,000 would be paid to cover plaintiffs' attorneys legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the tentative deal, patients allegedly injured by  
fen-phen will have the choice to participate or to sue on their 
own. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys say most patients will choose to sue on their own  
because the $2.8 billion will not be enough once its divided among 
the many thousands who will seek damages. And that will allow 
American Home to back out of that part of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ridiculous how much they want to pay,'' said one attorney  
involved in the negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home Products and attorneys for patients who contend  
they were injured by the diet drug fen-phen are working out final 
details of a $4 billion national settlement, say lawyers close to 
the talks. An agreement could be reached within days. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4,100 suits, involving 8,000 people who took the diet  
drugs, have been filed against American Home, making it one of the 
largest product liability cases ever. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home officials refused to comment on the possibility of  
a settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	A civil trial is under way in New Jersey over whether the  
company should be liable for the cost of medical monitoring to 
detect any signs of heart or lung problems. In court documents, one 
economist estimated that the company would have to pay $1.5 billion 
for a decade of regular checkups for the 94,000 residents who took 
the drug combination for at least three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Securities analysts said the medical monitoring claims were most  
troublesome because they could go on for decades, and it would be 
difficult to estimate the total cost for American Home. 
</P>
<P>
	About six million people took the drug combination.  
</P>
<P>
	Jerrold Parker, a New York attorney who said he has filed suits  
on behalf of hundreds of patients, said most people who need 
medical monitoring already have health insurance to cover the 
costs. He said more money needs to be set aside for patients who 
have been injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Other attorneys say the injury portion of the deal is probably  
too low because many victims have yet to file suits. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Becnel, a plaintiff attorney in Reserve, La. said he has  
filed suits on behalf of 60 patients, but knows of nearly 1,000 
more who may eventually sue. 
</P>
<P>
	Becnel is also concerned because a number of states including  
Louisiana won't allow plaintiffs to receive damages for medical 
monitoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Unresolved issues on Tuesday included the structure of the  
payments to patients, including how those payments will keep up 
with inflation over a number of years, an attorney close to the 
talks said. Also unresolved is how to guarantee American Home 
follows through on its agreement, said the attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Any settlement would need a federal judge's approval.  
</P>
<P>
	American Home made fenfluramine, the ``fen'' in the fen-phen  
combination and gave the drug a brand name of Pondimin. It also 
made Pondimin's chemical cousin Redux and marketed both until 
September 1997. That was when the U.S. Food and Drug Administration 
pushed for their withdrawal after a Mayo Clinic study linked the 
drugs to potentially fatal heart valve damage. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:40:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith Shares Glory With Dorsett </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Emmitt Smith's latest milestone was an  
emotional one, once he realized it. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith passed Tony Dorsett to become fourth on the NFL's career  
rushing list with a 7-yard touchdown run in Dallas' 24-7 victory 
over Atlanta Monday night. Among the first to greet Smith on the 
sidelines was Dorsett, who was at the game to help celebrate the 
Cowboys' 40th anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `Congratulations,' and I said `Thank you,''' Smith  
said. ``Then I kept on moving to go sit down. I didn't even realize 
what he was saying congratulations for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith wasn't seated long when he heard the good news over the  
Texas Stadium loudspeaker. As fans cheered, he went back to 
Dorsett, hugged him and whispered a few words. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to go tell him in his ear how much I greatly appreciate  
what he's done, the standards he has set,'' said Smith, who last 
season passed Dorsett as the leading rusher in team history. ``I 
wanted him to know that I greatly, really, truly in my heart 
appreciate him as a person, as a Dallas Cowboy and as a football 
player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith wasn't finished with his thank-yous.  
</P>
<P>
	He also sought Daryl Johnston, Smith's lead blocker in 131 of  
his 142 games, but probably no longer. Johnston re-injured his neck 
in the opener and won't return this season. Although he's going to 
try coming back next year, the odds are long. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston will remain with the team for moral support and advice.  
On Monday night, the guy affectionately known as ``Moose'' was 
walking the sidelines carrying a clipboard. Fans gave him a 
``Mooooose'' call when he was shown on the stadium's television 
screen early in the first quarter. He got more air time when Smith 
hugged him following the milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not having him out there is different for me because this guy  
has led me for all these years and all those yards,'' said Smith, 
who came into the league in 1990, a year after Johnston. ``Not to 
have him is like losing a brother almost. That's an unfortunate 
part of the business. He's truly going to be missed by me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Talking about Johnston made Smith choke up a bit. He ended a  
group interview with that response and hurried away. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Sanders is retired. Jamal Anderson is hurt and out for the  
year. Terrell Davis is struggling without John Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	And Emmitt Smith just keeps going.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's a real competitor, a fighter,'' quarterback Troy Aikman  
said. ``He's still got a lot left in the tank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two years after career lows of 1,074 yards and four touchdowns,  
Smith has opened 1999 with consecutive 100-yard games and three 
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Against Atlanta, he had his longest run in two years, a  
37-yarder, and he proved he's still durable with 29 carries. Dallas 
is 15-1 when he has that many attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can stand here with a smile on my face knowing that my  
career is long from being over,'' said Smith, whose three rushing 
TDs extend his NFL record to 128. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's 108 yards against the Falcons give him 12,783 in his  
career. Dorsett had 12,739. 
</P>
<P>
	Before he can get to Walter Payton (16,276) or Barry Sanders  
(15,269), Smith must catch Eric Dickerson (13,259). That's likely 
to happen in five games, maybe six. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be fitting for it to happen in six games, which would  
be Nov. 8 at Minnesota, another Monday night game. 
</P>
<P>
	In 20 Monday night games, Smith has 2,057 yards, the most of any  
player in the series' 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
