<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pharmaceutical Chief Survives Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Milan Panic has been ousted as prime minister of  
Yugoslavia, paid $600,000 to settle a federal securities charge and 
millions more to settle six sexual harassment suits. On Wednesday, 
Panic won his latest confrontation, surviving a shareholder revolt 
to remove him as chairman of the pharmaceutical company he founded 
in 1960. 
</P>
<P>
	But the flamboyant, outspoken businessman still faces a civil  
lawsuit brought by the Securities and Exchange Commission that 
alleges he misled investors about the prospects of an experimental 
drug. The suit seeks to prohibit Panic (pronounced PAHN-eech) from 
running any public company. 
</P>
<P>
	Panic, a Serb-born American businessman who served as Yugoslav  
leader for eight months in 1992 and 1993, on Wednesday faced many 
of his biggest critics at the annual meeting of his ICN 
Pharmaceuticals held in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	About 37 percent of shareholders who cast ballots voted to  
remove Panic as chairman, far short of the two-thirds majority 
needed. The revolt was led by the company's largest shareholder, 
Heartland Advisors of Milwaukee, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Heartland president William Nasgovitz said Panic's many legal  
problems and his arrogant style has hurt ICN's stock, which has 
fallen more than 37 percent since July. Nasgovitz said the Costa 
Mesa, Calif.-based company needs new leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Panic, who charged that Nasgovitz is trying to hurt ICN with his  
attack, said the company's sales and profits are at record levels. 
Panic said he does not know why the stock has slipped so badly. 
</P>
<P>
	ICN stock dropped from $30 a share to Wednesday's closing level  
of $18.75 after the company's second-quarter results fell below 
analyst forecasts. The company, which sells more than 40 percent of 
its drugs in Eastern Europe, has been hurt by a currency collapse 
in Russia, where it sells many of its products. About half of ICN's 
$439 million in sales last year came from Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I should spend more time selling the stock than building  
profits,'' Panic said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokerage firm officials and securities analysts at the meeting  
also expressed frustration with Panic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your feigning ignorance implies a lack of responsibility,''  
Patricia Loepker, portfolio manager with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons, told 
Panic. She said ICN's stock is down because the company's 
performance has fallen short of Wall Street projections, and Panic 
has done poorly at communicating with investors about changes 
affecting the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Panic said the SEC's lawsuit, which followed a 4 1/2-year-long  
investigation, has no merit. The SEC initially accused Panic of 
insider trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation targeted Panic's sale of $1.24 million of ICN  
shares in December 1994, after the company allegedly learned its 
bread-and-butter product, the antiviral drug Ribavirin, would not 
be approved by the Food and Drug Administration to treat hepatitis 
C. 
</P>
<P>
	The bad news wasn't revealed to investors until February 1995.  
ICN's stock fell 41 percent in six days, to $13.25 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC eventually dropped the insider trading allegation, but  
on Aug. 11 of this year, the commission filed suit in California 
alleging that Panic and other top executives made fraudulent 
statements about Ribavirin. The suit seeks a $500,000 fine and try 
to prohibit Panic from serving as an officer of a public company. 
</P>
<P>
	Ribavirin, sold under the name Virazole, is now used in more  
than 40 countries including the United States to treat herpes, 
influenza, chicken pox, hepatitis, and AIDS. In June 1998, the FDA 
approved a potent drug cocktail that includes Ribavirin to treat 
hepatitis C patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Panic acknowledges his company has a reputation problem. ``The  
problem is investor relations and what you perceive of us not what 
we are,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Panic has settled six sexual harassment suits including one for  
$3.5 million from his former secretary. Last year, a court ordered 
him to pay child support for a son he fathered with the woman. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, Panic paid $600,000 without admitting wrongdoing to  
settle an SEC charge of making false and misleading statements 
about Virazole for treating AIDS. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clash 2, MetroStars 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Ronald Cerritos scored the game  
winner early in the second half with his team-record 14th goal and 
the San Jose Clash defeated the New Jersey-New Jersey MetroStars 
2-1 on Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Dario Brose had a goal and an assist and goalkeeper Joe Cannon  
stopped a penalty kick late in the first half in the battle of two 
MLS teams already eliminated from playoff contention. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Zambrano scored for the MetroStars, but also was stopped  
by Cannon on the penalty kick as New York-New Jersey lost its 
seventh straight at Giants Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd for the MetroStars' final home game was announced at  
7,215, but it seemed even less. 
</P>
<P>
	Cerritos' game-winner came in the 53rd minute on assists by  
Brose and Alejandro Sequeira. Brose chipped the ball to Sequeira, 
who headed it to Cerritos for a tap-in past goalkeeper Mike Ammann. 
</P>
<P>
	Cerritos ('98) and Paul Bravo ('96) shared the old team record  
of 13 goals. 
</P>
<P>
	The MetroStars missed tying the game twice in the final 18  
minutes. Petter Villegas was wide from 25 yards in the 72nd minute 
and Mike Petke's header off a corner kick in the 87th minute also 
slid wide of the goal post. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was the second straight for the Clash under interim  
coach Jorge Espinoza. Lothar Osiander will take over the team on 
Friday, replacing Brian Quinn, who was fired last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The only reason the MetroStars didn't leave the field at  
halftime with a 2-1 lead was Cannon. The rookie came off his line 
to stop Zambrano on a penalty kick in the 44th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	The penalty was set up when Mauricio Wright tripped Zambrano in  
the penalty area. 
</P>
<P>
	Zambrano had tied the score in the 35th minute. He took a pass  
from Brian Kelly, outran Wright down the left touchline and beat 
Cannon with a sharp angle shot just inside the outside goal post. 
</P>
<P>
	Brose beat Ammann from 25 yards on a free kick in the 12th  
minute to give San Jose the early lead. It was his fourth goal and 
second in as many games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clash 2, MetroStars 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Ronald Cerritos scored the game  
winner early in the second half with his team-record 14th goal and 
the San Jose Clash defeated the New Jersey-New Jersey MetroStars 
2-1 on Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Dario Brose had a goal and an assist and goalkeeper Joe Cannon  
stopped a penalty kick late in the first half in the battle of two 
MLS teams already eliminated from playoff contention. 
</P>
<P>
	Henry Zambrano scored for the MetroStars, but also was stopped  
by Cannon on the penalty kick as New York-New Jersey lost its 
seventh straight at Giants Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd for the MetroStars' final home game was announced at  
7,215, but it seemed even less. 
</P>
<P>
	Cerritos' game-winner came in the 53rd minute on assists by  
Brose and Alejandro Sequeira. Brose chipped the ball to Sequeira, 
who headed it to Cerritos for a tap-in past goalkeeper Mike Ammann. 
</P>
<P>
	Cerritos ('98) and Paul Bravo ('96) shared the old team record  
of 13 goals. 
</P>
<P>
	The MetroStars missed tying the game twice in the final 18  
minutes. Petter Villegas was wide from 25 yards in the 72nd minute 
and Mike Petke's header off a corner kick in the 87th minute also 
slid wide of the goal post. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was the second straight for the Clash under interim  
coach Jorge Espinoza. Lothar Osiander will take over the team on 
Friday, replacing Brian Quinn, who was fired last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The only reason the MetroStars didn't leave the field at  
halftime with a 2-1 lead was Cannon. The rookie came off his line 
to stop Zambrano on a penalty kick in the 44th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	The penalty was set up when Mauricio Wright tripped Zambrano in  
the penalty area. 
</P>
<P>
	Zambrano had tied the score in the 35th minute. He took a pass  
from Brian Kelly, outran Wright down the left touchline and beat 
Cannon with a sharp angle shot just inside the outside goal post. 
</P>
<P>
	Brose beat Ammann from 25 yards on a free kick in the 12th  
minute to give San Jose the early lead. It was his fourth goal and 
second in as many games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
