<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> VP Argues for Medicare Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 1 million Medicare recipients in  
HMOs will lose their zero co-payment coverage for prescription 
drugs next year, Vice President Al Gore said today in arguing for 
the administration's Medicare legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a Health Care Financing Administration review of  
HMO plans for 2000, annual dollar caps on drug coverage will also 
be imposed more widely. This year, only 21 percent of the managed 
care plans that serve Medicare beneficiaries had a per enrollee 
drug limit of $500 or less. Next year, nearly one-third of such 
plans, 32 percent, will have such limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Also next year, all plans will charge co-payments for  
prescription drugs, with an individual's average out-of-pocket 
payment for brand-name drugs increasing by 21 percent. For generic 
drugs, HCFA estimates the co-payment will increase by 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1 million Medicare patients currently get prescription  
drugs with no co-payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, who is running for president, released the HCFA findings  
on behalf of the Clinton administration at a Washington meeting of 
the American Medical Association. He urged doctor-lobbyists headed 
today to Capitol Hill to press Congress on President Clinton's 
proposal to add a Medicare prescription drug benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tell them it's doctor's orders,'' Gore said.  
</P>
<P>
	``The need for affordable prescription drugs is only becoming  
more important. That's why, if we use the (federal budget) surplus 
to strengthen Medicare for the future, we ought to help seniors who 
have their benefits cut by Medicare HMOs by ensuring that all those 
in Medicare have an affordable prescription drug benefit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 6.2 million of the 39 million Medicare enrollees get  
health insurance through HMOs. Many senior citizens sign up with 
HMOs as an alternative to Medicare's traditional fee-for-service 
coverage because the HMOs, in addition to providing Medicare 
benefits, usually offer prescription drug coverage, fewer 
co-payments and other additional benefits. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
