<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delaware Governor To Run for Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Democratic Gov. Thomas Carper has announced  
he will run for the U.S. Senate seat of Republican William Roth 
Jr., a five-term incumbent and the third-oldest member of the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Carper, 52, has won statewide office 10 times, including five  
terms holding Delaware's only seat in the U.S. House of 
Representatives. He has also presided over a robust economy and a 
time of low unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth, 78, is chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, with his  
name attached to the Roth IRA, a popular retirement account he 
helped create. 
</P>
<P>
	``Elections are not just about the past, they are largely about  
the future,'' Carper said. ``When voters go to polls a year from 
this November, they're not going to be choosing a senator for the 
20th century, but one for the 21st century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roth said he looked forward to running on his record.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is a proven record that has been and will be a strong voice  
for the people and the state of Delaware,'' Roth said. 
</P>
<P>
	State GOP Chairman Basil Battaglia said Carper's entry into the  
race will not change Roth's election strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll run on his record -- lower taxes, more retirement  
security and IRS reform,'' Battaglia said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
