<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Mulls Legality of NATO Air War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Italy, one of NATO's most stalwart  
members, on Wednesday questioned the legality of the Western 
military alliance's air war against the forces of Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany, another key NATO ally, also said NATO's intervention  
without the blessing of the U.N. Security Council should remain an 
exception, not a precedent for similar incursions to protect human 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that the interventions that have taken place in recent  
times, on the urge to put an end to massive violations of human 
rights ... are not codified and raise the sizable question of 
legitimacy,'' Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini told 
reporters. ``The intervention in Kosovo took place without the 
mandate of the United Nations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 78-day air war began in response to Serbia's campaign to  
drive the Albanian majority out of the province of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States and Britain wanted to intervene, but they  
feared a veto in the U.N. Security Council by China and possibly 
Russia if the issue were raised there. They steered the Kosovo 
crisis away from the United Nations and dealt with it through NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	China -- long criticized for its human rights practices and its  
occupation of Tibet -- has always been reluctant to approve outside 
interference in a nation's internal affairs. Russia might have 
considered casting a veto to protect its Slavic Serb brethren from 
air raids. 
</P>
<P>
	``The international community, but not all of it, decided that  
an intervention was urgent and took the law into its own hands,'' 
Dini said. ``This cannot be repeated. I think that the principle of 
sovereignty must be upheld, generally.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But later, in an interview with The Associated Press, Dini said,  
``I think that Kosovo was a just cause and the need for immediate 
intervention was justified by the tragedy that was taking place. In 
the end, the matter was reviewed in the United Nations, and the 
subsequent actions have all been under a U.N. resolution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech Wednesday, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer  
warned the U.N. General Assembly that ``a practice of 'humanitarian 
interventions' could evolve outside the U.N. system. This would be 
a very problematic development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the intervention in Kosovo was justified because Kosovo  
needed emergency assistance and the Security Council had ``tied its 
own hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``this step ... must not set a precedent for  
weakening the U.N. Security Council's monopoly on authorizing the 
use of legal international force.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
