<HEADLINE> Alleged Stephanopoulos Stalker Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge on Tuesday ordered a psychiatric  
examination for a former White House intern accused of stalking 
George Stephanopoulos, but refused to hold her in contempt for not 
staying away from him. 
</P>
<P>
	The exam was ordered for Tangela Burkhart, 32, who was arrested  
Friday at an Upper West Side coffee shop that Stephanopoulos 
frequents. She was sitting in the cafe when Stephanopoulos arrived. 
He went to a telephone and dialed 911. 
</P>
<P>
	Burkhart was arrested twice last year for allegedly harassing  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	But the judge said the latest police complaint was defective  
because it offered no evidence that the woman knowingly violated 
the court order. 
</P>
<P>
	The cafe is in Stephanopoulos' new neighborhood, some 30 blocks  
south of the Columbia University area where Burkhart lives and 
Stephanopoulos recently left. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephanopoulos rose to national prominence during the 1992  
Clinton-Gore campaign and eventually became White House 
communications director. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
