<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 23:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Learned To Help Himself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dinnertime at Pat Buchanan's childhood home  
could be intimidating for visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's father quizzed the children at the table like a  
civics professor, asking their opinions on national issues of the 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``What struck me was how much the kids knew, even the little  
kids,'' recalled lifelong Buchanan friend Tom McCloskey of 
Kensington, Md. ``I didn't know nearly as much as they did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In this challenging environment in the suburbs in northwestern  
Washington, Patrick Joseph Buchanan learned early how to fend for 
himself in the world of politics and ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	He's been jockeying for the best strategy to continue that  
debate ever since -- first as an editorial writer, then as a 
political aide, then a TV commentator and finally as a presidential 
candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were immersed at our dinner table in national and world  
politics, rather than local and state issues,'' the 60-year-old 
Buchanan said in an interview with The Associated Press. ``It was 
basically my father's influence. I grew up during World War II. We 
talked about the war in Europe and the war in Japan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan recounted his years growing up as one of nine children  
in a close-knit Catholic family and his intense admiration for his 
accountant father, William B. ``Bill'' Buchanan, in his 
autobiography, ``Right From The Beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Buchanan was a devoted Catholic, a Republican, a stern  
disciplinarian and an admirer of the pre-World War II isolationists 
who believed in an ``America First'' policy. 
</P>
<P>
	He made his boys attack punching bags -- 300 swats a session --  
and took pride when they won a scrap with someone else while 
growing up in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was the brainy brawls over dinner that gave Pat Buchanan  
a taste for political debate that surfaced frequently, especially 
in his college years when he gathered with friends at the apartment 
of Charles ``Chick'' Leasure. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pat would be the instigator of these discussions,'' Leasure  
said. ``We could chime in, but he was the mover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his upbringing, Pat Buchanan developed a reverence that  
has never dimmed for the America of the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot recreate the 1950s, but you can recapture that  
sense of community and patriotism,'' Buchanan said. ``There's 
something that's been lost that everybody wants to recapture -- the 
sense that we are a good people and one nation on one voyage 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, a longtime Republican like his father, is running for  
president this year for the third time -- against the advice of some 
friends and associates who thought he could have more influence 
from the sidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan challenged President Bush in 1992 after deciding Bush  
had moved away from the Reagan agenda. He ran against Bob Dole in 
1996, even winning the New Hampshire primary. 
</P>
<P>
	But this time around, he has become increasingly dissatisfied  
with the Republican Party and says he is seriously considering 
seeking the Reform Party nomination. A final decision, he says, 
will be made in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought the second run he did because he enjoyed the first  
one,'' said Robert Novak, a conservative columnist and commentator 
who knows Buchanan well. ``This time he went into it with a little 
less joy, and a feeling that nobody was picking up this torch. The 
vast majority (of his associates) encouraged him not to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the TV commentator and former aide to Presidents Nixon and  
Reagan felt the campaign trail this year was the best place to keep 
alive his battle over the direction of the conservative movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly I hope to keep our ideas and beliefs front and center  
and make sure they are advanced,'' Buchanan said. ``But I would not 
run if I didn't think I could win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan has never stopped campaigning since his college  
days, when he would read the National Review and first recognized 
that his beliefs came under the conservative label. 
</P>
<P>
	His view of conservatism includes a foreign policy that puts  
America's military and economic interests over global goals -- and 
he rejects descriptions of that as isolationism in his new book, 
``A Republic, Not An Empire.'' He wants tighter limits on 
immigration and he's a social conservative who is strongly 
anti-abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	After he graduated from Georgetown University, Buchanan went to  
Columbia University's graduate school of journalism on a 
fellowship. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia journalism professor emeritus John Hohenberg, who now  
lives in Knoxville, Tennessee, remembers Buchanan as a very bright 
and assertive student, who spent much time in class trying to sell 
his point of view. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did all the talking when we were in a discussion in the  
class,'' Hohenberg recalled with a laugh. ``His views were extreme. 
This is a bonanza as far as a teacher is concerned. You can match 
students against students and see how they react to each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After completing his journalism degree, it took Buchanan about  
three months to move from rookie reporter to the editorial page. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was assigned to a low-rung job in the financial department,  
pasting up soybean prices and he volunteered to do some 'think 
pieces' ... that attracted the attention of our publisher,'' said 
Martin Duggan, news editor at the St. Louis Globe-Democrat when 
Buchanan joined the paper. 
</P>
<P>
	Duggan recalled how Buchanan, several years later, was able to  
finagle an invitation to a reception for Richard Nixon. Buchanan 
eventually was offered a job as Nixon's assistant in the years 
before the former vice president ran for president. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan found a common bond with Nixon, though Buchanan was  
more conservative. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, Nixon was my mentor on political strategy and  
tactics,'' Buchanan recalled. ``Nixon relished political combat and 
I did as well. We developed a plan on how to break up the New Deal 
and bring over (to the GOP) elements of the Democratic Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nixon called him ``the only extremist I've ever known who has a  
sense of humor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, his blunt honesty has brought criticism that he  
is intolerant -- even anti-Semitic -- a claim Buchanan denies. While 
his rhetoric is sometimes harsh, Buchanan tends to be personally 
warm and engaging, associates say. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't have a mean streak,'' said L. Brent Bozell III, a  
former campaign aide. ``It's the Irish brawler in him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's been married to his wife Shelley, whom he met in the Nixon  
White House, since 1971. They have no children. He's traded in the 
German-built Mercedes Benz, that brought criticism in the campaign 
seven years ago as he argued for limiting foreign trade. He now 
drives a Navigator, a Lincoln sport utility vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan's determination to keep his focus on political strategy  
paid off at one key moment in his career. He was asked to head up 
the White House investigative unit that eventually became known as 
``the plumbers,'' set up to stem leaks and targeted anti-war 
activist Daniel Ellsberg, but he refused. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were taking me off track,'' Buchanan said. ``I wanted to  
do battle on political conflict and issues. The idea of running an 
investigation seemed to be a dead-end street for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan returned to writing a syndicated column after working  
for Nixon and later became a television commentator. In a 
revolving-door pattern that continues to this day, he returned to 
politics as a White House aide during President Reagan's second 
term. 
</P>
<P>
	What does Buchanan hope to accomplish with his lifelong  
campaign? 
</P>
<P>
	``The preservation of the American republic forever,'' he said.  
``That's what I will achieve before they lower me into the 
ground.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
