<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in  
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors 
watched closely for news of the ongoing harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean prices, down more than 25 cents a bushel in the past  
week, received more pressure from the accelerating harvest with 
forecasts predicting dry weather in the soybean belt through the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn inched higher before falling back as investors searched for  
the right price ahead of what could be the biggest harvest weekend 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat avoided a price dip, buoyed by export sales overnight.  
Egypt bought 55,000 tons of U.S. winter wheat, and Japan bought 
110,000 tons of U.S. wheat out of a total of 150,000 tons purchased 
from the United States, Canada and Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery was unchanged at $2.70 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/4 cent to $2.10 1/2 a bushel; December oats rose 1 3/4 
cent to $1.14 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans fell 1 cent to $4.84 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
beef futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle fell .10 cent to 66.65 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .18 cent to 79.55 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .28 cent to 45.10 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies rose 1.68 cents to 58.45 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
