<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Lower; Gold Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against most other major  
currencies in European trading, but gained against the Japanese 
yen. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0507 in late European trading, up from  
$1.0383 Tuesday. The euro began rising Tuesday after the German IFO 
index, a barometer of business confidence, signaled growing 
optimism by German business executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro traded at  
$1.6358. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 104.22 Japanese yen, up from 104.09 late  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's gain against the yen followed a sharp decline in  
the U.S. currency Tuesday when the Bank of Japan decided not to 
relax its monetary policy to take some steam out of the yen's 
recent rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday,  
included 1.5252 Swiss francs, down from 1.5448; 1.4698 Canadian 
dollars, down from 1.4740. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6388, up from $1.6278.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 104.05 yen, and  
the pound was worth $1.6358. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8615 German marks, down from 1.8837; 
6.2430 French francs, down from 6.3176; 2.0974 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1224; 1,842.04 Italian lire, down from 1,864.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $264.20 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$259.25 on Tuesday. Gold prices turned sharply upwards on Tuesday 
following the Bank of England's second sale of 25 metric tons from 
British gold reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $264.05, up from $259.65. Gold rose  
$7.60 in Hong Kong to $262.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.27 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.20. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
