<HEADLINE> Crude Futures Soar on OPEC Decision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OPEC's decision to stick to production cuts for another six  
months had an immediate impact on the futures market Wednesday, 
driving already-soaring crude oil prices even higher and sending 
gasoline prices surging too. 
</P>
<P>
	In other markets, gold and pork belly futures both rose sharply  
for a second straight day. 
</P>
<P>
	Expected though it was, the unity displayed by the Organization  
of Petroleum Exporting Countries at its meeting in Vienna nudged 
oil back toward the $25-a-barrel level it flirted with last week -- 
more than double the price of last spring. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC agreed to extend cuts of 4.3 million barrels a day that  
have whittled down the abundance of oil on the world market and 
spurred talk in Washington of tapping the U.S. strategic petroleum 
reserve to help relieve surging prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The cartel's ministers contended that oil reserves are still  
more than plentiful. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the remaining high level of stocks, OPEC member  
countries have reaffirmed their strong commitment to the agreement 
reached in March 1999 until at least the end of March 2000,'' they 
said in a communique. 
</P>
<P>
	West Texas intermediate crude oil for delivery in November rose  
18 cents to $24.12 on the New York Mercantile Exchange, while 
October unleaded regular gasoline increased 1.71 cents to 69.84 
cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent crude rose 25 cents to $22.93 on the  
International Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of surprises in Vienna left no obvious barrier to oil's  
price rise for the foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any reason why this market won't continue to work  
its way higher until at least January,'' said Tim Evans, senior 
energy analyst for the Pegasus Econometric Group in New York, 
predicting a price of between $27 and $31 a gallon by the beginning 
of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	After January, he said, the outlook becomes more uncertain due  
to peaking seasonal demand for gas and the likelihood that OPEC 
members will raise prices at their next meeting in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Other energy futures were mixed Wednesday. October heating oil  
rose 0.43 cent to 60.21 cents a gallon, and October natural gas 
fell 0.01 cent to $2.426 per million British thermal units. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures, after a $6 gain the previous day, increased by  
another $3.60 to $265.40 per troy ounce on the New York Mercantile 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	That's still a far cry from the lofty prices the metal once  
commanded as the premier investment hedge. But its status inched 
higher after South Africa-based Gold Fields Ltd., the world's No. 2 
gold producers, said it bought heavily at a British gold auction 
Tuesday because it expects the price to rise due to demand from 
jewelers. 
</P>
<P>
	This week's rally began after the British Treasury fetched  
above-market prices when it sold 25 metric tons from its reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork belly futures have risen more than 11 percent on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Both pork bellies and hogs climbed Wednesday on speculation  
about the shrinking size of the U.S. hog herd at a time while North 
Carolina farmers are still counting their losses as a result of 
Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	February frozen pork bellies rose 2.88 cents to 59.65 cents a  
pound. October lean hogs rose 0.73 cent to 45.55 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
