<HEADLINE> Justice Dept. To Sue Tobacco Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department is ready to sue major  
tobacco companies today in an effort to recover billions of dollars 
taxpayers have spent on smoking-related health care, a government 
official said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Attorney General Janet Reno is expected to  
formally close, without charges, a nearly 5-year-old criminal 
investigation of whether tobacco companies lied to Congress or 
regulatory agencies about the addictive nature of tobacco. That 
decision has been expected since last spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-anticipated civil lawsuit prepared by a Justice  
Department task force over the past year would allege that the 
companies engaged in a conspiracy to cover up the health risks of 
smoking in violation of the federal law against civil racketeering, 
The Associated Press learned. 
</P>
<P>
	``American taxpayers have been forced to spend billions of  
dollars on smoking-related illnesses and the Justice Department is 
working on a way to get them their money back,'' a government 
official said, requesting anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was expected to be announced at a news conference by  
Reno and acting civil division chief David Ogden late this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco industry spokesmen have questioned whether the  
government has authority to bring such a lawsuit, particularly 
given more than three decades of federal government warning to the 
public about the health dangers of smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a legal standpoint, it's just pure politics,'' said  
Michael York, a lawyer for Philip Morris, the nation's largest 
cigarette-maker. ``When we look back we'll find the best legal 
minds in the Justice Department thought the facts and law didn't 
support it. It's hypocrisy to think the tobacco companies misled 
the federal government about the risks of smoking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea of suing the tobacco companies to recover an estimated  
$25 billion spent by federal civilian and military health insurance 
programs on smoking-related illnesses was a surprise element in 
President Clinton's State of the Union speech last January. 
</P>
<P>
	It followed an expensive settlement by the cigarette-makers with  
most state governments last year, based on their outlays for health 
insurance. The industry agreed to pay the states more than $240 
billion over 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement with the states followed the collapse of an  
effort to write federal legislation that would have substantially 
increased the cost of cigarettes through taxes and would have 
restricted the marketing of tobacco. Congressional Republicans 
blocked that bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil lawsuit follows a stalled Justice Department criminal  
investigation of whether the industry had lied to either Congress 
or regulatory agencies about the addictive effects of cigarettes 
and the industry's knowledge of that addictive power. The 
department began scaling back that criminal investigation this 
spring, and this summer, several deadlines for filing criminal 
charges passed without any action. 
</P>
<P>
	Department officials have been debating for weeks whether any of  
the evidence gathered during the criminal investigation could be 
used by the task force preparing the civil lawsuit. One official 
said department lawyers had decided to try to use that data in the 
civil lawsuit but believed they needed permission from the U.S. 
District Court here which supervises the grand jury which obtained 
it. It was not clear whether that permission had been obtained yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, the department's request for $20 million to pay for  
expert witnesses and 40 government lawyers in the fiscal year 
beginning Oct. 1 remains in limbo on Capitol Hill. The 
Republican-controlled Congress has refused so far to put the money 
into appropriations bills working their way through the Capitol but 
deleted a prohibition against Justice bringing the lawsuit. Justice 
officials expressed continued hope today that the money will be 
approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the department hired a Minneapolis law firm,  
Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP; Ciresi, which helped Minnesota reach a 
$6.6 billion settlement with the industry last year, to help it 
analyze more than 200,000 pages of industry documents disclosed 
during the Minnesota lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	In the civil lawsuit the government will claim that tobacco  
companies engaged in consumer fraud by conspiring to conceal from 
the public the risks of cigarette smoking. The suit will attempt to 
recover claims paid to veterans, military personnel, federal 
employees and the elderly. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
