<HEADLINE> Floyd Causes Hospital Water Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- A hospital where the water was knocked  
out by Hurricane Floyd has turned to its rehabilitation swimming 
pool to keep toilets flushing and medical machines operational. 
</P>
<P>
	With water service sporadic because of massive flooding along  
the Tar River, Pitt County Memorial Hospital has been getting water 
trucked in from fire trucks and water tankers. 
</P>
<P>
	The pool is usually used to rebuild bodies weakened by illness  
or injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire department pumper trucks are used to suction the greenish  
water from the pool and circulate it through the hospital's 
plumbing system. Toilets flush, the lab has remained open and key 
medical machines that depend on water pressure are running. 
</P>
<P>
	Bottled water is used for drinking.  
</P>
<P>
	``The pool is pretty effective for its intended purpose, but it  
has worked pretty effectively for this unintended purpose as 
well,'' hospital spokesman Tom Fortner said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital estimates that since Tuesday, several hundred  
thousand gallons of water have gone into the 80,000-gallon swimming 
pool -- described as roughly half the size of an Olympic-size pool -- 
and then into the hospital's water system. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury-rigged system has enabled the 731-bed hospital to  
continue to serve several counties in eastern North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a truck exploded Wednesday night outside the  
hospital. No one appeared to be hurt and firefighters quickly 
doused the blaze. The cause of the blast wasn't immediately 
apparent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
