<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Woman Bakes To Pay Farm Taxes / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOLON, Iowa (AP) -- When her husband died three years ago, Peg  
Stritesky knew it was up to her to pay the taxes on the family 
farm. She turned to cooking, her strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Stritesky, 59, and her daughter, Lisa, 28, began selling $7 pies  
at the Solon farmers market. It has become an annual part of their 
lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will always be a struggle just to preserve our lifestyle,''  
Peg Stritesky said. ``We do it not to get rich but to do what we 
enjoy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stritesky said she got started that year because she had such  
good apples. The rhubarb, peaches, strawberries and raspberries 
were good, too. When her neighbor had more fruit than she could use 
herself, she gave it to Peg. That is how Peggy's Pies was born. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've built my business on fresh fruit. We don't start at the  
farmers market until August. Until then, we're getting the fruit 
ready and gardening or farming,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Picking apples for her customers' favorite flavor of pie is  
easy, but Peg works hard to please others by picking wild 
blackberries in the timber. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wear long sleeves and a leather glove on one hand. I get all  
scratched up, but people like blackberry,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	The fruit they prepare goes into three freezers and four  
refrigerators and waits until the rush of pie-making days. 
</P>
<P>
	For Wednesday's market, Stritesky starts Monday by making dough.  
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesdays, she stands for hours at the corner of the kitchen  
cabinet and rolls out pie crusts. 
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Stritesky and Chris Davis, 11, a neighbor who spends time  
with them, work at the table across the kitchen. They open freezer 
bags of fruit, divide it and add sugar and other ingredients. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesdays are for making fruit pies. Cream pies and kolaches -- a  
bun made of sweet dough and filled with jam or fruit pulp -- are 
made Wednesday morning, with Peg turning the kitchen light on well 
before dawn. The two women will bake for 36 hours and then sell the 
pies, kolaches, 36 loaves of quick bread and dozens of cookies in 
three or four hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The farmers market is open two afternoons, Wednesday and Friday,  
but Peggy's Pies and baked goods are available only on Wednesday -- 
the rest of the week is for farming. 
</P>
<P>
	Peg and Lisa bought 30 lambs in the spring that had been  
rejected by their mothers and fed them by hand until they could eat 
on their own. The lambs are at market weight now and are helping 
the farm's finances as they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm is home to 32 cows and a bull, plus their offspring,  
which are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm also produces firewood and garden vegetables and has  
200 acres in hay and pasture and 70 acres in crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Peg says her heart has always been with the farm. When she was 6  
or 7 years old, she wanted to drive a tractor. Her father was in a 
hurry and asked Peg's mother if he should take the time to teach 
her how to drive a tractor. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mom said, 'Some day you may be glad you did,''' Peg says.  
</P>
<P>
	Not many women can bake as well as her mother and then cut hay  
and check the cattle, Lisa says. 
</P>
<P>
	Peg faces August, the beginning of the three-month pie season,  
with mixed emotions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of dread some of the work, but it's fulfilling,  
rewarding to see all the baked goods,'' she says. ``We always 
learned we had to do what we had to do to survive. This is one of 
those things.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
