</P>
<P>
	Fed Finds Moderate-to-Brisk Growth  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation is enjoying ``moderate-to-brisk  
rates of growth'' with industrial activity on the rise across most 
of the country and retail sales showing strength, the Federal 
Reserve said today. It also noted there were few reports of 
pressure on wages and salaries despite a continuing tight labor 
market, and stable consumer prices. However, it found the cost of 
healthcare benefits increasing in some areas. The report compiled 
from data from the Fed's regional banks helps guide policy makers 
who will meet Oct. 5 to review interest rates. 

</P>
<P>
	Justice Dept. Sues Tobacco Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department sued the tobacco  
industry today to recover billions of dollars taxpayers have spent 
on smoking-related health care, accusing cigarette-makers of a 
``coordinated campaign of fraud and deceit.'' The lawsuit filed in 
U.S. District Court in Washington alleges the cigarette companies 
conspired since the 1950s to defraud and mislead the American 
public and to conceal information about the effects of smoking. 
Attorney General Janet Reno said that smoking is ``the nation's 
largest preventable cause of death and disease, and American 
taxpayers should not have to bear the responsibility for the 
staggering costs.'' 

</P>
<P>
	OPEC Maintains Oil Output Cutbacks  
</P>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Consumers in North America and Europe  
will likely pay steeper fuel bills this winter in view of OPEC's 
decision today to maintain deep cuts in oil output until at least 
next March. The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries 
announced its widely expected move in a communique issued during a 
semiannual meeting of its 11 oil ministers. OPEC will stick to cuts 
of 4.3 million barrels per day that it has made over the past two 
years. OPEC will review market conditions in March 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Launch Fall Fare Sale  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Air fares to Europe and some domestic  
destinations were put on sale today, with flights to London as low 
as $188 for round-trip travel. The London sale launched by British 
Airways is good for tickets purchased only through Friday. The 
fares of $188 are for round-trip travel from several East Coast 
cities on a Wednesday. Air fares from West Coast cities start at 
$298. The sale fares are available from 22 U.S. cities. Mwanwhile, 
US Airways is offering discounts up to 35 percent off two-week 
advance purchase fares for travel within the United States between 
Oct. 5 and Dec. 15. The sale fare from Washington, D.C.'s Reagan 
Airport to Denver, for instance, is $315 roundtrip if the flight 
includes a Saturday night stay, and fare from Charlotte, N.C. to 
Kansas City is $229. The sale fares must be purchased by Oct. 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Predicts No Y2K Disasters  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One hundred days before computers run up  
against the year 2000 date, a Senate panel said today that the 
world won't end on Jan. 1 with a Y2K-related computer crash, but 
Americans should be ready for short-term disruptions. It said 
federal agencies and the national infrastructure are in solid 
shape, but seven states remain in the ``danger zone'' with fewer 
than 70 percent of computer systems ready, the Y2K panel said in 
its final report. The situation is similar in the private sector, 
with big businesses, particularly in the banking and investment 
industry, confident their computers are ready while many smaller 
businesses could run into trouble. 

</P>
<P>
	United Technologies Cuts More Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- United Technologies Corp. plans to reduce  
its worldwide workforce by an additional 9,000 jobs as the company 
looks to reduce costs amid a downturn in the aerospace industry. 
The Hartford, Conn.-based company also announced today that it 
plans close 8.5 million square feet in manufacturing and other 
space. Most of those closures are expected overseas. The cutbacks 
are the latest move by UTC to restructure its business. 

</P>
<P>
	Xerox To Acquire Tektronix Division  
</P>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Xerox Corp. will buy the color printing  
division of Tektronix Inc. for $950 million in a deal that will 
make Xerox second only to Hewlett-Packard in the office color 
printing market. The deal, announced today, will give Xerox the 
Tektronix line of Phaser color laser and solid ink printers, which 
last year logged nearly $725 million in sales. Xerox's distribution 
capacity will nearly double to more than 16,000 resellers and 
dealers worldwide. 

</P>
<P>
	Airbus Partner Talks Hit Snag  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Europe's efforts to streamline its aerospace and  
defense industry suffered a setback today when partners in Airbus 
Industrie failed to draft proposals to turn the group into a 
private company. The four partners were due to report this week to 
their respective governments about their plans for restructuring 
the consortium that competes with U.S. aerospace giants Boeing and 
Lockheed Martin. The French government said it would consult its 
German, Spanish and British counterparts on the report's delay. 

</P>
<P>
	Singapore, Indonesia Sign Gas Deal  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Singapore Power Ltd. signed a  
preliminary agreement today to purchase $7 billion worth of natural 
gas from Pertamina, Indonesia's state-owned oil and gas company. 
The contract is expected to be signed in December. Under the 
agreement, Pertamina will sell 2.27 trillion cubic feet of natural 
gas from fields in south Sumatra over 20 years starting in 
mid-2002. Singapore Power signed the agreement through its 
subsidiary PowerGas Ltd. 

</P>
<P>
	Quake Affects Taiwan High Tech  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The earthquake that hit Taiwan will cause  
computer chip companies to lose more than a week of production and 
may lead to an increase in worldwide prices, analysts said today. 
The U.S. investment firm Merrill Lynch said in a report that the 
powerful quake, which struck yesterday, would affect output for 
between one and 1 1/2 weeks. The quake knocked out power supplies at 
most companies in a science-based Technology Park. As of this 
morning, only partial power had been restored to several leading 
chipmakers located there. Prices on the chip spot market have been 
rising recently because of a short supply and high demand, and 
analysts said the disruption in Taiwan could drive them even 
higher. 

</P>
