<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Reaffirms Cuts in Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- The outcome of the latest OPEC oil  
ministers' meeting -- a decision to prolong cuts in oil output -- 
seemed well-scripted and came as no surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the same time, Wednesday's move has fed uncertainty about  
future trends in petroleum prices and supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're going to be in for a very volatile market over  
the next few months,'' said Mehdi Varzi, an industry analyst in 
London with the investment bank Dresdner Kleinwort Benson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries announced  
its widely expected decision during a semiannual meeting of its 11 
oil ministers. OPEC will stick to cuts of 4.3 million barrels per 
day that it has made over the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC ministers have said they hope to see prices increase  
further, and they expressed concern over what they see as a 
continued oil surplus in world markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the remaining high level of stocks, OPEC member  
countries have reaffirmed their strong commitment to the agreement 
reached in March 1999 until at least the end of March 2000,'' the 
group said in a communique. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC will review market conditions at that time and act to  
ensure ``continued market stability,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	But some analysts said oil prices have become divorced from the  
underlying fundamentals of supply and demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders have already factored in the anticipated uptick in  
winter demand for heating oil in much of the industrialized world. 
Prices have more than doubled since February, even though 
inventories have been slow to decline. 
</P>
<P>
	``I must stress that the market situation still seems to be  
fragile, contrary to what present price levels might indicate,'' 
OPEC President Youcef Yousfi told ministers in an opening speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no shortage of oil in the market, and ... stock  
levels are still high and could at any time have a negative impact 
on prices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kuwait's oil minister, Sheikh Saud Nasser al-Sabah, told  
reporters that the price increase since March has fallen short of 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dale Steffes, president of Houston-based Planning and  
Forecasting Consultants, said OPEC is trying to keep the oil price 
artificially high. OPEC will lose significant market share as the 
high prices make it profitable for other countries to pump more 
crude, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They only missed two points,'' Steffes said of the OPEC  
ministers. ``Supply and demand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC's last round of cuts, taken in March, helped revive prices  
from 12-year lows. Now that the group has reaffirmed the cuts, 
analysts say OPEC's restraint will hit Americans hardest of all. 
</P>
<P>
	Taxes account for as much as 80 percent of the price for  
gasoline in Europe and 60 percent of the gas price in Japan, said 
Leo Drollas, chief economist at the Center for Global Energy 
Studies in London. By comparison, the U.S. tax rate on gasoline is 
only about 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Any increase in oil prices would therefore cause a  
proportionally sharper rise in prices Americans must pay at the 
pump. Drollas estimated that gasoline prices have already risen 
four times faster in the United States this year than in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lukman, speaking at a final news conference after the  
meeting ended late Wednesday, said the ministers did not specify a 
target price or price range. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC produces more than 26 million barrels of crude each day, at  
least 35 percent of the of the world's total. In March, it agreed 
together with major non-OPEC producers to curtail daily production 
by 2.1 million barrels, or 2.6 percent of the global supply. Prices 
have risen steadily since. 
</P>
<P>
	The price for the November contract of U.S. West Texas  
Intermediate crude was trading up 29 cents at $24.23 per barrel in 
New York, more than twice its year-to-date low of $11.26, set Feb. 
17. 
</P>
<P>
	Average pump prices for a gallon of gasoline in the United  
States stood at nearly $1.32 a gallon this month, up from less than 
$1 in February, according to the Lundberg Survey. 
</P>
<P>
	And U.S. heating oil prices are expected to average about $1.04  
per gallon this winter, up from 80 cents per gallon last year, the 
U.S. government has estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	But Roger Diwan, manager of global oil markets for The Petroleum  
Finance Co., a Washington-based consulting firm, said prices are 
not sustainable at current levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to come down. You're going to have a strong  
retreat,'' he said. ``The question is when.'' 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC comprises Saudi Arabia, Iran, Venezuela, the United Arab  
Emirates, Kuwait, Qatar, Nigeria, Libya, Algeria, Indonesia and 
Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's oil ministers will meet again in Caracas, Venezuela,  
on March 27. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
