<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Relief Proposals Get a Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The world's poorest countries moved closer to  
easing their huge burden of debt when the Clinton administration 
asked Congress for a big increase in money to finance a debt-relief 
initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	Poverty-fighting groups praised the U.S. move Tuesday as a  
dramatic gesture that would salvage the effort to help 41 of the 
poorest nations, mostly in Africa, obtain $90 billion in debt 
relief. The big industrial nations pledged at a summit in June to 
expand the debt initiative so countries receive more help faster. 
</P>
<P>
	Since that time, however, the proposal had run into roadblocks  
that included a campaign by the gold industry to block direct sales 
of gold from reserves of the International Monetary Fund to finance 
part of the debt relief. Members of Congress from gold-mining 
states and lawmakers critical of the IMF's overall performance 
joined the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials indicated the IMF was close to approving an  
alternative gold sale plan for the debt-relief plan. They hope to 
get approval for an overall debt-relief package when the 182-nation 
IMF and its sister institution, the World Bank, hold their annual 
meetings in Washington next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to set an example for other rich countries, Treasury  
Secretary Lawrence Summers told reporters Tuesday the 
administration sent Congress a request to more than triple the 
amount the United States will offer in debt relief in the fiscal 
year starting Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	And Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., a leading supporter of debt  
relief, expressed optimism that Congress will approve the 
administration's increased funding request. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cost of funding debt relief is $1.20 a year for every man,  
woman and child in the United States over the next three years,'' 
Bachus said, ``and the cost of not doing it will be the deaths of 
tens of thousands of people every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard economist Jeffrey Sachs, a persistent critic of the IMF,  
said the administration's plan was a step in the right direction 
but the United States should be bolder and directly cancel debts 
owed by poor countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's crucial to allocate the sums the administration is  
talking about in the right way to break the hammerlock of the IMF 
on poor countries, '' Sachs said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said by directly cancelling poor country debt owed to the  
United States, the administration could leverage up to $100 billion 
from other nations for debt relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally, the administration's budget had included $120  
million to support debt relief next fiscal year. Summers said the 
new request would boost that total by another $250 million, 
bringing next year's total request to $370 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to that, the administration asked Congress to  
approve another $600 million for another three years of U.S. 
contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is essential moral policy to write off debts to nations in  
significant parts of the world where a child is more likely to die 
by the age of five than attend secondary school,'' Summers told 
reporters after testifying at a congressional hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of religious and other poverty organizations, known as  
Jubilee 2000, pushed leaders of the industrial nations to do more 
for debt relief at their annual summit. 
</P>
<P>
	Seth Amgott, a spokesman for Oxfam International, praised the  
administration's new proposal as a potential spur to wealthy 
nations, the IMF and the World Bank to be more generous. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration released a fact sheet estimating that if  
wealthy creditor nations and organizations such as the IMF and 
multinational development banks meet obligations envisioned by the 
industrial nations, current debt of $127 billion held by the 
world's poorest nations could be cut to $37 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
