<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BYU Coach Signs Five-Year Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- When LaVell Edwards became coach at BYU,  
some said he wouldn't last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	That was 27 years ago, before Edwards engineered BYU's rise to  
national prominence. On Wednesday, he signed a five-year contract 
extension that will keep him in Provo through 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	``He built this program and he can stay as long as he wants,''  
linebacker Rob Morris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms weren't disclosed but published reports have placed  
Edwards' salary at $250,000 annually. Edwards, 68, declined to say 
if he had received a raise in the new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards has a career record of 245-91-3 and ranks eighth among  
active NCAA Division I coaches, winning 72 percent of his games. 
The Cougars won the 1984 national title after beating Michigan in 
the Holiday Bowl to finish 13-0. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards recalled that he once planned to coach until he was 60.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was about 62 before I ever remembered that's what I had set  
up. ... Now I'm already making plans for next year and recruiting. 
That's the reason for this. I just feel good right now,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards needs 11 victories to pass Nebraska's Tom Osborne for  
sixth place on the list of career coaching victories. Edwards turns 
69 next month but Morris said he sees no signs that his coach has 
slowed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seems to have found the fountain of youth for coaching. All  
he does is drive around in a golf cart all day. I could do that,'' 
said Morris, the team jokester. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cougars (2-0) are ranked No. 17 and play Virginia on  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Val Hale said the extension came early in the  
season to help Edwards with recruiting. Speculation had persisted 
since summer that Edwards was ready to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``This announcement should send a clear message to recruits and  
fans that BYU football will continue its winning ways into the next 
century,'' Hale said. 
</P>
<P>
	Before leaving, Edwards said he hopes to improve BYU's  
facilities, including the construction of an indoor practice field. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have good young players in the program and strong schedules  
in the coming years,'' he said. ``The future looks bright for BYU 
football. I also want to get a number of projects off the ground 
before I retire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Edwards took over in 1972, he had been a BYU assistant for  
10 years, the last few as defensive coordinator. As coach he 
devised a passing game to offset the more physical opponents on 
BYU's schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had changed coaches every three or four years before my  
getting the head job,'' Edwards said. ``It was just going to be a 
matter of when I got fired. There were a lot of people that felt 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cougars developed one of the most prolific passing offenses  
in NCAA history, grooming quarterbacks like Marc Wilson, Jim 
McMahon, Steve Young, Robbie Bosco and 1990 Heisman Trophy winner 
Ty Detmer. 
</P>
<P>
	Through two games this fall, quarterback Kevin Feterik leads the  
nation in total offense, averaging 491 yards per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Edwards, BYU also won 18 Western Athletic Conference  
championships and the Cougars have played in 21 bowl games, 
including 17 straight from from 1978-94. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
