<HEADLINE> Calif. Probes Four Women's Prisons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Sexual misconduct allegations at four  
women's prisons have led to the resignations of five prison 
employees and the investigation of 12 others, state officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	The male employees, some of them correctional officers, have  
been accused of sexual assaults and of illegal consensual sexual 
relations with female inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	One employee has been placed on administrative leave and faces  
sexual assault charges in San Bernardino County, prison officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another correctional officer allegedly fathered an inmate's  
child, prison officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ongoing investigation could include as many as 40 additional  
employees at the California Institution for Women in Frontera 
alone, said state Corrections Department spokeswoman Kati Corsaut. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation began in November 1998 when the Fontera warden  
asked the state to investigate an inmate's accusation that a 
correctional officer had fathered her child. That officer has since 
resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	California has 11,249 female inmates housed in four prisons. One  
is in Frontera, two are next to each other in Chowchilla and one is 
in Stockton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
