<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 09:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prisoner Escapes on Cigarette Break </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COUNCIL GROVE, Kan. (AP) -- A man let out of his jail cell to  
smoke a cigarette climbed a fence topped with razor wire and 
escaped hours after he was sentenced to almost 42 years in prison 
for shaking a toddler to death. 
</P>
<P>
	About 60 law enforcement officers used horses, helicopters and  
dogs to search for Scotty Adam today in woods near the Morris 
County Jail, said Scott Teeselink, spokesman for the Kansas Bureau 
of Investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge went beyond sentencing guidelines to give Adam, 24,  
double the recommended sentence for second-degree murder. The 500 
months imposed by Morris County Judge Morris Platt was the maximum 
allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	Platt said Adam's 1993 involuntary manslaughter conviction in  
the stabbing death of a 19-year-old man was the reason he exceeded 
the guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two lives taken by you is enough,'' Platt said.  
</P>
<P>
	Adam escaped Tuesday when deputies let him into a recreation  
area outside of the jail for a smoke, Teeselink said. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam, charged with first-degree murder, pleaded guilty to  
second-degree murder in the shaking death of 16-month-old Timothy 
Post in the toddler's Council Grove home. 
</P>
<P>
	Timothy, the son of Adam's girlfriend, suffered massive brain  
swelling caused by violent shaking, according to expert testimony 
at Adam's preliminary hearing last year. Adam told investigators he 
treated the toddler ``rough'' on several occasions. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam was taking care of the boy and his sisters, ages 2 and 3,  
when Timothy was injured Oct. 21. At the time, Adam was on parole 
for the earlier killing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Chides Foreign Policy Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said  
Wednesday Congress does not understand the harm it is causing the 
United States by not giving President Clinton all the money he 
wants to finance U.S. foreign policy. 
</P>
<P>
	One result of congressional cuts is that the United States is in  
debt to the United Nations and, Albright said, ``they resent us 
deeply because we are not paying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By U.N. accounting, the bill is about $1.5 billion. If the  
United States does not pay $350 million by January, it could lose 
its vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a lack of understanding in Congress about the toll it  
takes on the American position if we don't have the money,'' 
Albright said of the cuts in foreign spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright agreed with congressional critics who say that the  
United Nations should do more to trim its spending, but she said 
Secretary-General Kofi Annan had ordered some worthwhile reforms in 
U.N. operations. 
</P>
<P>
	And Albright said that the U.S. share of U.N. costs -- 25 percent  
of the budget and about 30 percent of peacekeeping operations -- was 
unfair and that several other nations were prosperous enough to pay 
a larger share. 
</P>
<P>
	But, she said, the United States is ``the backbone'' of the  
United Nations and should pay its debts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seahawks, Galloway Agent To Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) -- When Mike Holmgren heard Joey Galloway's  
agent wanted to meet with the Seattle Seahawks this weekend, he 
decided to try to move up the timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seahawks' first-year coach-general manager told the team's  
negotiator, Mike Reinfeldt, to call Eric Metz, Galloway's 
Scottsdale, Ariz.,-based agent, to try to set up a soon-as-possible 
meeting here before the team left for Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to fly them in here,'' Holmgren said at his news  
conference Wednesday. ``I don't want to wait until this weekend. 
Why wait until Pittsburgh? We'll pay for their plane tickets and 
get them in here. If they think we can get something done this 
weekend, let's not wait.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Metz on Wednesday said thanks, but no thanks.  
</P>
<P>
	He said he'll talk by phone with Reinfeldt on Thursday and meet  
with him in person in Pittsburgh on Friday evening, saying a 
Pittsburgh meeting fit his schedule better. He emphasized there had 
been no new offer from the Seahawks and no deal was imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	Galloway has no plan to be in Pittsburgh for the meeting, Metz  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off a 14-13 victory in Chicago last weekend to even their  
record at 1-1, the Seahawks will play at Pittsburgh (2-0) on 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Metz said Tuesday that Galloway would end his holdout  
immediately if the Seahawks would promise not to use their 
``franchise player'' designation to limit Galloway's options after 
the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would definitely do that if you would promise me you'll  
sign,'' Holmgren said. ``I want him here. If he wants to be here, 
which I think he does, let's get the thing done now. Let's do this. 
</P>
<P>
	``My stance hasn't changed. I have high hopes for him and what  
he can do and how I think I can help him become a player who can 
maximize his potential. I'm surprised it's lasted this long.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Galloway, 27, is considered the top talent in the Seahawks'  
offense. He caught 65 passes for 1,047 yards and 10 touchdowns last 
season. In 63 games with Seattle, he has 261 career catches for 
4,122 yards and 36 TDs. 
</P>
<P>
	He was scheduled to be paid $1.58 million in the final year of a  
five-year contract that he signed as a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	On July 14, the Seahawks made him what they said was a final  
offer, a $35 million deal for seven years, including a $7 million 
signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm willing to tweak here now because I want this thing to get  
done,'' Holmgren said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren sounded almost conciliatory in his remarks about his  
missing receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not so concerned about making a statement,'' he said.  
``It's a good learning experience for me and it's one right out of 
the chute. I really hope it gets fixed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Galloway's holdout has cost him $416,000 in lost salary and  
fines, but Holmgren hinted the fines against Galloway weren't 
written in stone. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll cross that bridge when we come to it,'' he said.  
``That's a lot of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For every game that Galloway misses, the team gains $93,000  
under its NFL-mandated salary cap. If Galloway misses enough games, 
the team could use that money toward the signing of a free agent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
