<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Mexico St. Football Back on Map </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- Four hundred years ago, Spanish explorer  
Don Juan de Onate came to southern New Mexico's Mesilla Valley in 
search of gold and treasure. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't find any, but those who followed discovered a fertile  
valley where today fields of chili, groves of pecan trees and acres 
of cotton and vineyards stretch for miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The valley has always been fertile territory for a lot of  
things, but not football. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the last three decades, few major college programs in the  
nation have rivaled New Mexico State's pigskin futility. Just two 
winning seasons since 1968 and an especially embarrassing stretch 
from 1985 through 1991, when the school won eight games and lost 
69. 
</P>
<P>
	The drought finally may be over.  
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies are 3-0 after last week's stunning 35-7 victory over  
then-No. 22 Arizona State in Tempe and a win Saturday at Texas-El 
Paso would give New Mexico State its best start since 1974. 
</P>
<P>
	Though it's still early in the season, and the Aggies could fade  
again, football fever hasn't been this high in Las Cruces since the 
school won consecutive Sun Bowls in 1959 and 1960 behind 
quarterback Charley Johnson, who went on to a career in the NFL 
with the old St. Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's great excitement in town. You can't beat success,''  
said Jim Bradley, coach at Las Cruces' Mayfield High School and the 
coach of the 1974 New Mexico State team that, despite its early 
winning streak, still ended up with a losing record after dropping 
its final five games. 
</P>
<P>
	So ecstatic were Aggies fans after the ASU victory in Tempe that  
some of them tore down one of the goalposts at the empty New Mexico 
State stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like turning on an electric light switch. The bulb was  
out before, or at least very dim,'' said Jack Nixon, the school's 
play-by-play commentator for 20 years. ``People are energized now. 
Before, it was we think it will be better. We hope it will be 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The architect of better times is former Nebraska player and  
assistant Tony Samuel. A soft-spoken disciple of hard work and a 
relentless recruiter, Samuel brought his Cornhuskers roots and 
connections with him when he became the Aggies' 31st coach two 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, Samuel was merely curious.  
</P>
<P>
	``I really came just to look,'' Samuel said. ``I knew about the  
history of the program. I knew they were battling for the basement. 
But that's all I knew. I didn't know much about the city and didn't 
know much about the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The legacy of losing didn't keep Samuel from taking a closer  
look. He desperately wanted to be a coach, so much so that for 2 1/2 
years prior to taking the New Mexico State job, he had been 
contacting other assistants he wanted on his staff. His listed 
included former Nebraska players like Rich Glover, the 1972 Outland 
Trophy and Lombardi Trophy winner; Barney Cotton, Jeff Jamrog and 
Gerry Gdowski, all of whom joined him in Las Cruces and are still 
here. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the 11 members of Samuel's staff played at Nebraska.  
</P>
<P>
	``All of them are good coaches, good people,'' Bradley said.  
``They've brought something to this community that's very good. 
They're clean-cut people who work their tail off and know what 
they're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samuel also brought much of Nebraska's playbook. On defense, the  
Aggies run the same multiple 4-3 defense as the Huskers and 
offensively run a variety of schemes to free up their running 
backs. 
</P>
<P>
	Against Arizona State, the running back trio of Walter Taylor,  
Chris Barnes and Keeon Johnson produced 295 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies didn't win much more in Samuel's first two seasons  
than they had in the previous 30. They finished 2-9 in 1997, losing 
41-10 to Arizona State in Samuel's debut and 61-24 the following 
week to New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season the Aggies were 3-8, but four of the losses were by  
four points or less. 
</P>
<P>
	Samuel and has staff have steadily built depth and the talent  
pool by recruiting players from throughout the country. Often, 
they've tapped their Nebraska connections. For example, sophomore 
running back Kenton Keith is the cousin of former Nebraska running 
backs Roger Craig and Heisman Trophy winner Johnny Rodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got ex-teammates calling us and recommending, and we  
have good connections with people who know talent,'' Samuel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Samuel's staff also has found players off the usual recruiting  
highway. Players like starting safety Donald Malloy, who graduated 
from Friendly High School in Port Washington, Md., and considered 
walking on at Rutgers or Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew the coaches here were from Nebraska,'' Malloy said. ``I  
thought, `I'll take my chances with these guys.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Another former walk-on, wide receiver Ryan Shaw, came across  
town from Mayfield High and has turned into the Aggies' go-to 
receiver with 19 career touchdown catches. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with the euphoria over the Aggies' start has come  
speculation that if New Mexico State does have a good year, Samuel 
and his staff will be lured away by a bigger school and more money 
than the $158,000 base salary he now earns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have time to worry about that,'' Samuel said. ``Those  
kind of things, if they happen, they happen. I preach to the team 
all the time, to focus on one game at a time. If I don't do the 
same thing, I'm lying to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Brian Faison thinks those offers will come.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to do everything we can to try to keep him,''  
Faison said. ``The job he's done is tremendous. I think 
realistically, if we have the kind of season that we hope we can, 
he's going to be a very attractive candidate for a lot of 
programs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samuel says New Mexico State, too, can be an attractive program  
in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the proper support, this is a gold mine,'' he said.  
``We've proven that we can compete with anybody. I said that the 
day I came. It's only a graveyard if you believe it is.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
