<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawaiian Air Buying 13 Boeing 717s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- Hawaiian Airlines said Wednesday it has agreed  
to buy 13 Boeing 717-200 airplanes for $430 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The carrier said the order eventually will replace its entire  
fleet of 15 interisland aircraft, with all of the new planes flying 
by the end of 2001. Hawaiian also has an option to buy seven more 
airplanes before 2005 for an additional $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a major investment in the future of the company,''  
Hawaiian president Paul Casey said. ``It underscores our commitment 
to the future of interisland travel.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Replacing the current fleet of airplanes will save $200 million  
in cash operating expenses during the first 10 years, with the bulk 
of the savings coming from not having to maintain the current fleet 
of 15 aging, DC-9-50 aircraft manufactured by McDonnell Douglas. 
</P>
<P>
	Launched as the MD-95 in October 1995, the airplane was renamed  
the Boeing 717-200 after McDonnell Douglas was merged into Boeing 
two years ago. The first of the new models, produced in Long Beach, 
Calif., is scheduled for delivery Thursday to AirTran Airways 
</P>
<P>
	The new planes will be configured by Hawaiian for 123 seats, 10  
fewer than the current planes, but will have more overhead storage 
space, Casey said. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's 12th-largest carrier will be able to increase  
volume by flying more flights because the new aircraft are more 
efficient and less costly to operate. Hawaiian also expects more 
passengers through code-sharing arrangements with American, 
Northwest and Continental, Casey said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Operationally, it's more efficient, way more reliable and it  
brings with it enormous cost savings,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	By following through on the order, Hawaiian would be the fifth  
airline to order the 717. The Hawaiian Airlines order brings the 
total number of orders for the model to 128, with options taken on 
117 more. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, Boeing announced plans to cut more than 600 jobs  
at the Long Beach Division fabrication shop as the company moves 
most of its work from the surburban Los Angeles plant. The 717 
program will remain, while production of the Delta rocket program 
and the C-17 military airlift program will be moved to a yet-to-be 
determined site. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing is also shutting down three of its four Long Beach  
production and fabrication lines -- the MD-80, MD-90 and MD-11. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle-based Boeing is the second-largest defense contractor  
after Lockheed Martin Corp. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
