<HEADLINE> Ladies Baseball Founder Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A former broker who founded the now defunct  
Ladies Professional Baseball league admitted Wednesday that he 
defrauded investors of $2.8 million to help support his failed 
sports enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Ribant, 42, pleaded guilty in federal court to one count  
each of mail fraud and tax evasion. He is expected to be sentenced 
to 30 months in prison during a hearing Dec. 14, said assistant 
U.S. Attorney Carol C. Lam. 
</P>
<P>
	Ribant, who is from San Diego, defrauded two dozen investors of  
the $2.8 million between 1993 and 1998 through his now closed 
brokerage firm, Trinity Capital, Lam said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trinity clients who lost money believed their capital was being  
invested, but Ribant admitted that he used the money for personal 
expenses and some of the costs of the six-team Ladies Professional 
Baseball league, which failed in 1998 because of low fan interest. 
</P>
<P>
	The league had teams in Long Beach and San Jose in California,  
and in Phoenix, Buffalo, N.Y., Florida and New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Some investors have received at least partial reimbursements of  
their capital from the Securities Investor Protection Corporation, 
which insures up to $500,000. The agency has paid $1.5 million so 
far and additional payments are expected, Lam said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission on Aug. 13 barred Ribant  
from associating with any broker or dealer in the future. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
