<HEADLINE> Two Arrested in Minister's Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISONVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Two people have been arrested in the  
murder of a minister who was found beaten to death and burned on 
his rural property. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of the Rev. William B. Petty Jr. was discovered  
Saturday and his car was located Monday about 30 miles away in 
Andrews, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathan Hass and his wife were arrested outside St. Louis at  
around midnight Tuesday, Richard Brogan, an agent of the Tennessee 
Bureau of Investigation, said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities were still trying to verify Mrs. Hass' first name.  
Additional details of the arrest were not immediately released. 
</P>
<P>
	Brogan said Hass was hitchhiking when he was picked up by the  
56-year-old minister, then got into a fight with Petty and killed 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Hass then drove Petty's car across the state line to North  
Carolina's Cherokee County where he lives, picked up his wife and 
fled, Brogan said. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no evidence Mrs. Hass participated in the murder,  
Brogan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Petty was clubbed on the head with a piece of wood, which was  
then burned with the body and clothing, authorities said. He had to 
be identified from a college class ring. 
</P>
<P>
	He had been a lawyer for three decades in Chattanooga before  
recently leaving his profession to become a United Methodist 
minister in charge of five small congregations in Meigs County. 
</P>
</TEXT>
