<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GAO: Blood Supply Is Tightening </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The blood supply is tightening as donations  
drop, but a prediction of nationwide blood shortages striking next 
year is exaggerated, a congressional report says. 
</P>
<P>
	``While there is cause for concern about shortages of certain  
blood types or in certain regions, the blood supply as a whole is 
not in crisis,'' says the report by the General Accounting Office 
being released at a House Commerce subcommittee hearing today. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts have become increasingly worried about the adequacy of  
the blood supply, as donations have dropped over the last decade 
while transfusion demand has increased. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Blood Data Resource Center has predicted that next  
year, Americans will donate just under 11.7 million units of blood, 
while hospitals will need 11.9 million units. 
</P>
<P>
	That prediction came before the Food and Drug Administration's  
recent ban on blood donations by anyone who spent six months or 
more in Britain since 1980, when that country's ``mad cow disease'' 
crisis began. The FDA anticipates that ban will cut the blood 
supply by 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the GAO's investigation says the prediction of a crisis next  
year is overblown. ``The blood supply has declined more slowly'' 
than previous studies suggested, it concluded. Also, blood banks 
``may be able to increase collections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts can disagree on how soon severe shortages could strike,  
but the nation needs to prepare now, responded Marian Sullivan, 
executive director of the National Blood Data Resource Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly action needs to be sooner rather than later,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 8 million Americans donate blood -- just 5 percent of  
eligible donors, the GAO noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortages, usually of Type O or Type B blood, already occur in  
certain regions, particularly around holidays. Almost 9 percent of 
hospitals in a recent survey said they had canceled elective 
surgeries due to blood shortages at least once in 1997 -- the latest 
year data is available. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the ``mad cow'' donation ban promises to hit hardest in  
major cities, home to more affluent blood donors who can afford 
frequent travel, the GAO said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The GAO's findings give us many reasons to be concerned,''  
said Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., who ordered the GAO probe as part 
of his House Commerce Committee's investigation of blood safety and 
availability. 
</P>
<P>
	The most up-to-date count of donated blood is due in November,  
when Sullivan's center completes a survey of whether the supply 
improved or worsened this year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 18:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Molasses Spill Hits Michigan River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAY CITY, Mich. (AP) -- A river of molasses began leaking from a  
tank at Monitor Sugar Co. before dawn Wednesday, oozing around the 
plant and dripping into the Saginaw River. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 4,000 tons -- the equivalent of 8 million pounds --  
of the thick, gooey liquid escaped, said company spokeswoman Judy 
Bagley. She said the cause of the spill was under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews were dumping sawdust onto the spill Wednesday to absorb  
the molasses and make it easier to clean up. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured and the molasses posed no public health  
threat, but officials said it could affect wildlife in the river. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Silfven of the state Department of Environmental Quality  
said specialists were trying to determine how much molasses got 
into a drain leading to the river. He said most of the molasses 
appeared to have pooled on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Molasses is a byproduct of sugar beet refining. The molasses  
sold in stores comes from sugar cane; the beet variety is sometimes 
used in livestock feed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 07:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Airport Reduces Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- In a bid to attract more flights, Hong Kong's  
top airport official announced Wednesday that aircraft landing and 
parking charges would be reduced by 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Victor Fung, chairman of the Airport Authority, said the airport  
would lose as much as $36 million with the move but that 
transferring some airport operation expenses to the government 
would help buffer the loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a competitive package aimed to strengthen our position  
as an air hub in the region,'' Fung said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan takes effect Jan. 1, Fung said.  
</P>
<P>
	Lower charges mean that airlines operating from Chek Lap Kok  
airport could expand services and increase passenger traffic to 
Hong Kong, Ronnie Choi of the Board of Airline Representatives said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will give passengers greater choices and flexibility in  
their travel arrangements,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes amid increasingly vociferous complaints from the  
group representing airline interests that Hong Kong is losing out 
on passenger traffic because of high fees at the new $20 billion 
Chek Lap Kok airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline officials said charges were 34.1 percent higher for  
large planes at Chek Lap Kok airport than they were a year earlier 
at the old Kai Tak international airport. Smaller planes were 
paying 14.7 percent more, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges were about double those of Singapore's Changi  
Airport, which slashed its charges 10 percent last year in a bid to 
compete for Asian traffic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
