<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Hog Farmers Can't Save Herds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.C. (AP) -- The smell of burning coals and rotting  
flesh mixed on Allen McCoy's farm Wednesday as a front-end loader 
scooped up dead hogs -- two or three at a time -- and dumped them 
into an incinerator superheated to more than 1,800 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	McCoy, a hog farmer since 1973, tried his best to save much of  
his herd when Hurricane Floyd struck last week. Instead, he's had 
to round up more than 3,000 carcasses and watch them go up in 
flames. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is sweat and blood you're talking about,'' McCoy said.  
``I've lost basically what I've worked for the last 40 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCoy, who lost more than half a million dollars in animals,  
buildings and equipment, is just one of hundred of farmers across 
eastern North Carolina whose livestock herds and fields were left 
in ruin. The hurricane destroyed the prized breeding operation he 
built with his cousin Phillip. 
</P>
<P>
	Statewide, officials estimate at least 100,000 hogs, 2.4 million  
chickens and 500,000 turkeys drowned. Early estimates of crop and 
farm structural losses totaled $333 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The threat of disease from rotting carcasses led state officials  
to send portable incinerators into counties with the most extensive 
livestock deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	At 30 feet long, 9 feet wide and 9 feet tall, the incinerators  
resemble boxcars filled with flames. Scrap lumber and timber are 
dumped in to feed the fires, which are stoked with the help of 
large blowers blasting like jet engines. 
</P>
<P>
	As the burning went on at McCoy's farm Wednesday, hundreds of  
decomposing hog carcasses lay in a pile a few feet away, their 
snouts buried in the mud. At the water's edge, scores of other dead 
pigs, still pink, appeared as if they were sleeping. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a very high-quality herd,'' said state veterinary  
officer Jim Kittrell. ``It was an expensive herd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCoy set out to save his hogs after the hurricane hit last  
Thursday. With floodwaters from the Trent River rising rapidly and 
the road to his hog houses already submerged, he grabbed a chainsaw 
and began cutting a swath through the woods for his tractor. 
</P>
<P>
	McCoy worked with friends and neighbors to rescue as many pigs  
as possible from the floodwaters, which turned his farm into a 
17-acre lake. He said some of the starving hogs had to tread water 
for days before they were saved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unreal how well they can swim,'' McCoy said.  
</P>
<P>
	McCoy recalled how Phillip, 65, waded through chest-deep water  
to drag hogs to safety, and how his nephew, Andy, joined in the 
effort despite battling the side effects of chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
	McCoy has no idea how he's going to pay his farm debts of  
roughly half a million dollars, but he hopes for federal disaster 
assistance. McCoy also vows to continue farming, a profession he 
thinks most Americans take for granted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really have a choice but to hold on if I can,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 10:38:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Criticizes Clinton Travel Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional criticism of President Clinton's  
foreign travel as a waste of taxpayer money is ``ignorant,'' 
Clinton's spokesman said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican complaints that Clinton spent more than $72 million  
on three foreign trips last year displays a glib lack of 
understanding of the economic and political payoffs from 
presidential visits, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's just no other word for it than ignorant,'' Lockhart  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sens. Larry Craig of Idaho, Jeff Sessions of Alabama and Craig  
Thomas of Wyoming released a General Accounting Office study 
Tuesday that detailed the costs of the three trips to Africa, China 
and South America. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers, cost and personnel involved exceeded by a great  
deal my own expectations,'' said Sessions. ``I think this really is 
excessive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The senators acknowledged, however, that they had no basis for  
comparing Clinton's travel costs with those incurred by previous 
presidents. In asking for the GAO study, they inquired only about 
Clinton's spending. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said such comparisons aren't relevant.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about is it reasonable to spend $43 million to  
go to Africa,'' he said. ``This idea of relating it to some others, 
I think, is immaterial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Craig did compare the presidents based on time spent  
abroad: Clinton, 186 days during seven years as president; former 
President Reagan, 84 days during eight years, and former President 
Bush, 86 days during four years. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO said Clinton's six-nation trip to Africa from March 22  
through April 2 last year cost $42.8 million, not counting Secret 
Service expenses, salaries of government workers involved and 
agency planning expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 1,302 government employees from 12 federal agencies  
or departments, including 16 members of Congress, accompanied 
Clinton to Africa. The biggest share of the cost, $37.7 million, 
came from the Defense Department's budget. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Lockhart called criticism of the African trip  
``particularly shortsighted,'' saying the senators ``are trying to 
find a political issue to raise and are missing the point of the 
whole trip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The president traveled Africa like no U.S. president has  
traveled before, really providing new insights for the American 
public on Africa, and new insights for the African public on 
America and our role,'' Lockhart said. ``It, in time, will be seen 
as a groundbreaking trip in terms of our relationships.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO report also found that:  
</P>
<P>
	--Clinton's five-day trip to Chile in April 1998 cost $10.5  
million. It included 592 officials from 13 federal agencies or 
departments. 
</P>
<P>
	--The China trip, from June 25 through July 3 last year, cost  
$18.8 million and included 510 officials from 11 agencies or 
departments. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:45:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Johnson Calls His Final Braves Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Ernie Johnson retired Wednesday after nearly four  
decades as a broadcaster for the Atlanta Braves. This time, he 
means it. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson initially stepped down from Turner Broadcasting System  
in 1989, tiring of the heavy travel at age 65. 
</P>
<P>
	But his retirement lasted only until August 1990, when TBS lured  
him back into the booth to do about 25 games a year for 
SportsSouth, a regional cable network now known as Fox Sports Net 
South. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I've had a lot of people say to me, `I thought you  
were retired. Are you going to give back your gifts?''' Johnson, 
75, quipped before his final broadcast, the NL East showdown 
between the Braves and New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm ready to hang it up now, I really do,'' he added.  
``It's a great game to go out on, trying to win the pennant and 
playing the New York Mets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of Fox Sports Net South's pregame show was  
devoted to Johnson's career. His family -- including his wife of 52 
years, Lois, and their three children -- watched from a private box 
at Turner Field. A small postgame party was planned afterwards. 
</P>
<P>
	During the game, Johnson's picture was shown on the scoreboard  
and Braves fans responded with a standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure I'll feel bad after it's over, knowing it's the last  
one,'' Johnson said. ``I'll miss the camaraderie. Lois will 
probably miss (the broadcasts) more than I will. She's my biggest 
fan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their retirement plans include trips to spring training, playing  
golf and watching Braves telecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, Johnson called home games only, except for two  
midseason telecasts in Milwaukee. Johnson pitched for eight years 
with the Boston and Milwaukee Braves, helping the club win the 1957 
World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	After retiring as a player in 1960, Johnson became the team's  
public relations director. Two years later, he joined the Braves' 
radio broadcast team. When the franchise moved to Atlanta in 1966, 
he took over play-by-play duties. 
</P>
<P>
	Early in his broadcasting career, Johnson received some advice  
from another player-turned-broadcaster, Joe Garagiola. 
</P>
<P>
	``Be yourself,'' Garagiola said. ``Don't be anyone but  
yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've tried to follow that,'' Johnson said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 20:45:32 </DATE_TIME>
