<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers' Means Expects To Be Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Natrone Means doesn't expect to be watching  
Sunday's home opener from the sidelines despite injuries the 
Chargers running back suffered last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Means twisted his left ankle and bruised his right knee in San  
Diego's 34-7 win at Cincinnati last Sunday. He had the knee drained 
Monday, when he had a hard time getting around. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, man, no comparison whatsoever,'' said Means, who didn't  
practice Wednesday. ``The knee feels a lot better. Right now the 
main thing is getting the ankle ready, get some strength in it and 
get some flexibility back and we'll be ready to roll. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no doubt in my mind I'll be ready.''  
</P>
<P>
	That was good news to coach Mike Riley, who wants to see the  
offense play more efficiently. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad he's saying that, because we would miss him badly,''  
Riley said. ``He's gotten a lot better in two days, so we're pretty 
excited about the possibility of him being ready to go by the end 
of the week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Means is trying to get through an entire season for the first  
time since 1994, when he rushed for a team record 1,350 yards and 
helped the Chargers reach the Super Bowl. He missed the last six 
games of 1998 after breaking a bone in his left foot, and missed 
time the previous three seasons with ankle, thumb and groin 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Means rushed 27 times for 79 yards in the Chargers' opener on  
Sunday and caught two passes for 14 yards, including a 12-yard 
shovel pass from Jim Harbaugh for a touchdown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
