<DOCNO> APW19990922.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 22:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid Accused of Overcharging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp. pharmacies in Florida  
allegedly used cash registers that were automatically programmed to 
ring up extra surcharges totaling more than $100,000 over a 
27-month period, according to a lawsuit filed by the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The racketeering lawsuit filed Wednesday by Florida Attorney  
General Bob Butterworth accuses Rite Aid of intentionally 
overcharging 29,000 uninsured customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid had two prices for the same prescriptions, adding an  
average surcharge of $1.15 per prescription for uninsured 
customers, said Mary Leontakianakos, Butterworth's chief of 
economic crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at it, $100,000 doesn't seem like an awful lot  
of money, but a couple of dollars here and there is significant to 
someone who is on Medicaid and living on a fixed income,'' 
Leontakianakos said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid, in a brief statement, said the suit is without merit  
and that ``not one customer was deceived or defrauded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are confident we will prevail,'' the Camp Hill, Pa.-based  
company said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the investigation of Rite Aid covered just over a two-year  
period, Leontakianakos said it appears the practice stretched into 
the last decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were a lot more,'' Leontakianakos said. ``We looked at a  
snapshot. We looked at a 27-month period. Our information is they 
had been doing this since the late '80s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leontakianakos said the Rite Aid policy was likely used in all  
its stores and her office has notified attorneys general in other 
states. She said the company stopped the surcharges three months 
after receiving a subpoena from Butterworth's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Some pharmacists disapproved of the policy and only added a  
penny extra to the prescription costs. Others quit over the policy, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid, the nation's third-largest drugstore chain, had 34  
drugstores in Florida during the period of the allegations. It no 
longer operates in the state, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The attorney general's office is seeking triple damages against  
the chain under racketeering laws and fines of $10,000 or $15,000 
for each violation. The higher fine will be sought in cases when 
elderly customers were charged extra. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities also want Rite Aid to return the nearly $100,000 in  
surcharges. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 11:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Where Candidates Stand on Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Positions of the Democratic and Republican presidential  
candidates on taxes: 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Snapshot: Federal income tax rates range from 15 percent to 39.6  
percent depending on income, with most Americans taxed at 28 
percent or under. The per-person cost of all federal taxes combined 
is estimated at $7,026, up from $4,646 in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Democrats:    	
</P>
<P>
	Bill Bradley: Would make debt reduction more of a priority;  
opposes $792 billion Republican tax cut package. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore: Has called for middle-class tax cuts for  
education and retirement, and higher earning cap for receiving 
Earned Income Tax Credit, all costing $250 billion to $300 billion. 
Opposed Republican plan for $792 billion in wide-ranging cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *Republicans:    	
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer: Favors a 16 percent flat income tax, but retains  
donations for charitable donations and mortgage interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Buchanan: Supports a 16 percent flat tax on earnings over  
$35,000; would drive up consumer prices by raising tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George W. Bush: Has called for billions in tax incentives  
to boost charitable giving and ability of religious groups to 
provide social services; pledges to veto any income tax increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole: Supports targeted cuts, pledges not to raise  
income tax rates, opposes any flat tax ending charitable and 
mortgage deductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Forbes: Has proposed a 17 percent flat income tax after  
``generous'' personal exemptions. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch: Voted for $792 billion tax cut package.  
</P>
<P>
	Alan Keyes: Would replace income tax with national sales tax.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain: Would expand lowest tax bracket so more people  
pay 15 percent; favors targeted cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Quayle: Favors a 30 percent cut in income taxes, capping  
individual and corporate tax rates at 28 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 16:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
