<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Ministers Begin Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Oil ministers from the 11 OPEC countries  
began meeting today to consider maintaining current cuts in oil 
output, despite disagreeing over who should lead the group into the 
new millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries was widely  
expected to reaffirm its reduced level of production until at least 
next March. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers would feel the impact of such a decision in the form  
of bigger bills for heating oil and gasoline. That hard fact 
prompted U.S. Senator Charles Schumer, a New York Democrat, to ask 
President Clinton and Energy Secretary Bill Richardson to sell oil 
from the U.S. strategic petroleum reserve to help ease surging 
crude prices in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC has made cumulative cuts of 4.3 million barrels per day  
over the past two years, in an effort to revive prices that plunged 
to 12-year lows in December. 
</P>
<P>
	There now seems little likelihood that OPEC will boost  
production before early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the tougher statements heard on the subject, Qatar's  
oil minister, Abdullah bin Hamad Al-Attiyah, said Tuesday that OPEC 
should stick to its current level of production until March 2000 
``whatever the consequences.'' His colleagues have made similar 
statements in the days leading up to today's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the group's unity showed signs of cracking on a  
different issue, when Iraq unexpectedly named its own candidate for 
a leadership job already contested by both Iran and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	A three-way struggle for the post of OPEC secretary general  
threatened Tuesday to weaken the solidarity that the group has 
taken such pains to build. The current secretary general, Rilwanu 
Lukman of Nigeria, is stepping down. 
</P>
<P>
	Iran's OPEC governor, Hossein Kazempour Ardebili, said today  
that Iran and Saudi Arabia will jointly propose that their 
respective candidates serve back-to-back terms of three years each. 
</P>
<P>
	Ardebili is Iran's nominee, while Saudi Arabia wants its own  
OPEC governor, Suleiman Jafir Al-Herbish, to get the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they should be discussing is expanding production because  
the market is overheating and has been for some time,'' said Leo 
Drollas, chief economist at the Center for Global Energy Studies in 
London. 
</P>
<P>
	At its last meeting in March, OPEC agreed together with major  
non-OPEC producers like Russia and Mexico to curtail daily 
production by 2.1 million barrels, or 2.6 percent of the global 
supply. The agreement extends through March 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC's ministerial monitoring subcommittee, which met Tuesday,  
backed a plan to keep its current quotas in place ``until at least 
March 2000,'' said its chairman, Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar 
Zangeneh. The subcommittee included Lukman and oil ministers from 
Kuwait and Nigeria. 
</P>
<P>
	Zangeneh told reporters that the subcommittee also determined  
that group members were more than 90 percent compliant with output 
cuts in August. Compliance should be even better in September, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC's apparent resolve to continue pumping less oil bodes  
poorly for consumers, who already are paying higher prices to drive 
their cars and heat their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prices now in the market are normal,'' Iraq's Oil Minister  
Amer Mohammed Rasheed told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC produces more than 26 million barrels of crude each day, at  
least 35 percent of the of the world's total. Its discipline in 
curtailing production since its last meeting has caused world 
prices to rise sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	``This price (level) is good, we think, for both sides of the  
market,'' Zangeneh said, adding that OPEC needed to see ``a 
considerable drawdown'' in global oil inventories before increasing 
its output. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumer disagreed, describing OPEC's apparent refusal to  
increase output as ``nothing less than economic warfare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But higher prices also could prove self-defeating for OPEC over  
the longer term, by tempting its members and other producers to 
pump more oil. This could send prices crashing. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts argued that OPEC will have to boost output before  
next March if it is to prevent prices from becoming too volatile. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some time they're going to have to increase production, and  
it's likely they'll do it before the end of the year,'' said Roger 
Diwan, manager of global oil markets for The Petroleum Finance Co., 
a Washington-based consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC comprises Saudi Arabia, Iran, Venezuela, the United Arab  
Emirates, Kuwait, Qatar, Nigeria, Libya, Algeria, Indonesia and 
Iraq. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
