<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lufthansa Buys Into Italy Airline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILAN, Italy (AP) -- The German airline Lufthansa announced today  
that it was buying a minority stake in a regional airline in Italy, 
a move that would make it the country's largest foreign carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Dolomiti has a fleet of 15 planes and serves 14 airports in  
Italy, mostly in the north. Based in Trieste, it also flies to 
Frankfurt, Munich, Paris and Barcelona. Last year, it operated 
6,500 flights. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined, Lufthansa and Air Dolomiti will serve 323 destinations  
and Lufthansa will have more flights in and out of Italy, which is 
dominated by the Italian national airline Alitalia, than any 
foreign airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the Air Dolomiti deal, Italy was one of Lufthansa's  
biggest foreign markets. Its manager for Italy, Gabriel Leupold, 
said Wednesday that Lufthansa will add a new route between Berlin 
and Milan's Malpensa airport this winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Lufthansa is buying 26 percent of Air Dolomiti, said Lufthansa's  
chief financial officer, Karl-Ludwig Kley. He did not disclose the 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Steel company Gruppo Leali will control 45 percent of the  
airline and a Friuli regional investment fund will hold 15 percent, 
according to Air Dolomiti chief executive Alcide Leali. Other 
minority shareholders will own 15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The accord marks an expansion in routes, joint-ticketing and  
frequent-flyer programs for Lufthansa's Star alliance, which 
includes Air Canada, Air New Zealand, Ansett Australia, SAS 
Scandinavian Airline, Thai Airways International, United Airlines 
and Varig Brazilian Airlines. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
