<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Guilty Pleas in NYC Divorce Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Over the course of their ugly three-year  
divorce, billionaire businessman Ronald Perelman and millionaire 
political fund-raiser Patricia Duff have squandered more than $4 
million on legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	If only they had known.  
</P>
<P>
	Manhattan's chief matrimonial clerk has acknowledged taking  
bribes as tiny as $10 to expedite divorce cases -- perhaps as many 
as 2,000 of them since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the Perelman-Duff case, these divorces were uncontested.  
But the clerk's guilty plea last week has raised questions about 
the validity of the splits involved and the possibility that some 
people unwittingly went on to commit bigamy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sort of bizarre. Common sense tells you that some of  
those people have remarried,'' celebrity divorce lawyer Raoul 
Felder said Wednesday. ``They're people who are technical 
bigamists, but they're really victims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to prosecutors, the bribes -- ranging from $10 to  
several hundred dollars -- were paid to speed up the divorce 
process. Rather than waiting the usual two to six weeks, the bribes 
assured delivery of a divorce decree in less than 48 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Singer, 50, who earned nearly $83,000 a year as  
Manhattan's chief matrimonial clerk, pleaded guilty Friday to three 
charges of taking bribes. He faces seven years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Singer, a court employee for 28 years, admitted that he took  
money from lawyers and divorce mills -- clerical services that 
handle divorce paperwork. 
</P>
<P>
	He never verified the papers' authenticity. Prosecutors said  
some of the papers were fraudulent, with husbands forging their 
wives' signatures on settlements that required minimal child 
support payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation began when a woman called the Manhattan  
matrimonial office to complain that she was served with an 
uncontested divorce agreement that she never approved. 
</P>
<P>
	A sting operation ensued. Using the names of turn-of-the-century  
prosecutors from the Manhattan district attorney's office, 
investigators quickly secured four divorces and moved in on the 
suspects. 
</P>
<P>
	The probe could involve as many as 20 more people, prosecutors  
said. Singer and the operator of a Queens divorce mill have pleaded 
guilty, and two more attorneys and another court clerk were 
indicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that the scam is exposed, partners who were duped by their  
spouses could find a surprise payday, said attorney Louis Newman, 
head of the matrimonial division at Kurzman, Karelsen &AMP; Frank. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ex-spouse might now feel there's leverage, and might say,  
`This is going to cost you a little extra, my dear,''' Newman said. 
``Leverage is everything in life.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 17:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals' Swann Doubtful for 49ers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Arizona Cardinals coach Vince Tobin is  
downplaying the significance of the decision to list defensive 
tackle Eric Swann as doubtful for Monday night's game against the 
San Francisco 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the first time the two-time Pro Bowl performer has been  
listed as anything other than out, since the seventh game of last 
season, because of knee surgery. Since then, Swann has undergone 
two operations on his arthritic right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobin said Swann has yet to be receive the go-ahead to play by  
doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hasn't been cleared for a game yet, but this is Wednesday  
and we'll see what happens,'' Tobin said. ``He would have to be 
cleared before he would be declared eligible to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swann, who has talked to reporters only once this season, wasn't  
talking again Wednesday. Two weeks ago, he said he expected to be 
ready in six to eight weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobin said the Cardinals are approaching the situation  
cautiously. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's getting closer,'' Tobin said. ``To say he's  
getting close, I don't know that, because we haven't done anything 
with him in pads yet. He is cleared to play a few snaps this week 
in pads, but we'll take it very, very slow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Swann was dissatisfied with the surgery preformed by the  
Cardinals' doctor and went to noted knee surgeon Dr. Richard 
Steadman for a more unorthodox surgery that requires more recovery 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	The recovery has taken longer than the Cardinals or Swann  
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said Swann is anxious to  
play. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been chomping at the bit,'' McGinnis said. ``He keeps  
asking to do more, more, more.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
