<DOCNO> APW19990922.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox To Acquire Tektronix Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Xerox Corp. will buy the color printing  
division of Tektronix Inc. for $950 million in a deal that will 
make Xerox second only to Hewlett-Packard in the office color 
printing market. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, announced Wednesday, will give Xerox the Tektronix  
line of Phaser color laser and solid ink printers, which last year 
logged nearly $725 million in sales. Xerox's distribution capacity 
will nearly double to more than 16,000 resellers and dealers 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Tektronix currently holds the second-largest share of the office  
color printing market. Once the acquisition is completed, Xerox 
will take over the No. 2 spot, with more than 30 percent of the 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The cash acquisition, which would be the largest technology  
acquisition ever for Xerox, is expected to close within 60 days. 
The deal is subject to regulatory approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives us an extraordinarily strong hand in one of the most  
exciting technology marketplaces, which is the emerging space for 
color in the office,'' said Xerox President and Chief Executive 
Officer Rick Thoman. 
</P>
<P>
	On the news, Tektronix stock initially shot up 9 percent before  
giving up its early gains on the New York Stock Exchange. In 
trading, Tektronix shares rose $1.31 1/4, or 3.8 percent, to $36.18 3/4. 
Xerox shares rose 56 1/4 cents to $42.56 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Xerox, traditionally a high-end copier company, in the last few  
years has made a move to become a major player in the home office 
and small business environment, through low-end retail channels 
such as Staples and Office Max. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the acquisition of Tektronix is a logical  
outgrowth of that strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they wanted to gain some major share, Tektronix is the one  
they would have gone after. ...It is definitely a good move for 
Xerox and it just further strengthens them against 
Hewlett-Packard,'' said Alyson Frasco, an industry analyst with 
International Data Corp., a market research firm based in 
Framingham, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	According to IDC's research, as of the first half of the year,  
Hewlett-Packard held about 45 percent of the U.S. office color 
printing market, which includes desktop color laser and solid ink 
technology. Tektronix currently holds about 30 percent, while Xerox 
holds 3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Tektronix Inc., based in Wilsonville, Ore., has a portfolio of  
measurement, color printing and video and networking businesses. 
The company had revenues of approximately $1.9 billion in its last 
fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's printing division has approximately 2,400  
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry J. Meyer, chairman and chief executive of Tektronix, said  
the company expects to eliminate the jobs of up to 200 employees 
within the next six months as a result of the acquisition. He said 
most of the job cuts will be made in Wilsonville, although some 
will come from other offices around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoman said Xerox expected ``relatively little'' in the way of  
job elimination at Xerox. ``We think this is really about growth,'' 
said Thoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Xerox will acquire Tektronix proprietary  
technology known as ``solid ink,'' a process Meyer said achieves a 
photo-quality print by loading a color crayon-like substance into a 
printer, then changing its phase from solid to liquid and then 
again to solid when it hits the paper. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tektronix printer operations will remain in Wilsonville.  
Employees of the color printer division will become employees of 
Xerox. Gerry Perkel, currently president of Tektronix' Color 
Printing and Imaging Division, will join the Xerox Channels Group 
as president of the Office Printing Business. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Tektronix announced plans to form separate  
companies for its measurement and color printing businesses, and 
has subsequently announced the sale of its video business. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
