<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Finds Moderate-to-Brisk Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The economy is growing strongly as  
manufacturers continue to rebound and consumer spending fuels brisk 
retail sales, the Federal Reserve said Wednesday in a new survey of 
business conditions around the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``moderate-to-brisk rates of growth,'' however, are  
contributing to widespread labor shortages, the Fed said in the 
survey, which is based on reports from its 12 regional banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey noted ``few reports of acceleration in nominal wages  
and salaries'' even as companies find it difficult to hire 
qualified workers for job openings in the current ``tight'' labor 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey did point out that some areas reported ``a  
substantial upswing in the cost of health-care benefits'' while 
consumer prices continue to be stable. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report continues to paint a picture of an economy that is  
expanding strongly but with still tame inflation,'' said Mark 
Zandi, an economist with Regional Financial Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, known as the ``beige book'' for the color of its  
cover, will be used when Fed policy-makers meet Oct. 5 to review 
the central bank's stance on interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists are split over whether the Fed will boost rates a  
third time at its October meeting in an effort to slow economic 
growth and keep inflation in check. 
</P>
<P>
	The beige book, which was based on information collected before  
Sept. 13, offered ammunition for both sides. The survey reported 
strong growth and tight labor markets, but it also said inflation 
generally remains subdued. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some economists did not believe the Fed survey was the  
definitive piece of economic information. 
</P>
<P>
	``The basic message of the report was expected: the economy has  
a lot of momentum,'' said Mark Vitner, an economist with First 
Union. ``I don't think this report changes anything for the Fed and 
the odds are that the Fed won't raise rates in October.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report ``would argue that the Fed remain predisposed to  
tightening but it doesn't necessarily mean the Fed will make a 
tightening move at its next meeting,'' Zandi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing activity had accelerated in almost every district,  
with the Chicago, Cleveland and St. Louis Fed districts reporting 
solid demand for steel and other metal products, particularly for 
the auto industry, the Fed survey said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston, Dallas and Minneapolis districts noted strong demand  
for semiconductors and computer components while the San Francisco 
district said demand from markets in East Asia, the area hardest 
hit by the global currency crisis, was beginning to rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the production of apparel appears to be down across the  
board, the survey said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the retail front, many areas reported strong back-to-school  
sales and even stronger demand for new autos. Most areas reported 
that retail sales were up from their level last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In most areas, home sales remain high but some slowing has  
occurred recently in both sales and construction, reflecting rising 
mortgage rates and rising building costs. 
</P>
<P>
	In the agriculture sector, the recent drought had worsened crop  
and livestock conditions in the East and parts of the Midwest, the 
survey said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago, Cleveland, Richmond and St. Louis districts rated  
corn and soybean crops as in poor to fair condition. The San 
Francisco district said adverse weather had lowered the quality and 
yield of many grain, fruit and vegetable crops. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, Dallas, Kansas City and Minneapolis reported  
favorable agriculture conditions with corn and soybean crops rated 
as good to excellent with above average yields. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
