<HEADLINE> Bears' Jaeger Says He's Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Chicago Bears kicker Jeff Jaeger said  
Wednesday he is ``90 percent'' recovered from a hip injury and 
should be ready to play at Oakland on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bears coach Dick Jauron isn't quite as optimistic.  
</P>
<P>
	``His problem, if he has one, is he doesn't feel he can swing  
fully at the ball,'' said Jauron. ``Now, he's saying he'll feel 
very comfortable doing that by the end of the week. If he says 
that, we'll go with Jeff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jaeger, who played for the Raiders from 1989 to 1995, hurt his  
left hip during the first week of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears settled on rookie Brian Gowins to take Jaeger's spot.  
But Gowins was cut for the third time this season Monday after 
missing a 50-yard field goal and a potential game-winning 48-yarder 
in Sunday's 14-13 loss to Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be great to go out and beat 'em,'' Jaeger said. ``I  
don't think I was ready last week, but I feel like I am now. As of 
right now, I'm feeling pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Left tackle Blake Brockermeyer will sit out Sunday's game after  
doctors Wednesday diagnosed him with an atypical migraine. 
</P>
<P>
	All tests since Sunday's game, including an MRI Wednesday on his  
neck, have come back negative, the Bears said. Doctors will 
reevaluate him next week. 
  	   	
</P>
