<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seafood Co. Settles Suit for $1.25M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A seafood company has agreed to pay $1.25 million  
to Vietnamese boat workers who complained of racial discrimination 
and inhumane treatment after they got the flu aboard a fishing 
ship. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement involving American Seafoods was announced  
Wednesday by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Agency Chairwoman Ida Castro said the case involved ``egregious  
types of discrimination,'' with Vietnamese Americans singled out 
because of their nationality. 
</P>
<P>
	Company president Mike Hyde said that suggesting the 18  
plaintiffs were treated badly because of their national origin ``is 
just a preposterous allegation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I concluded we did have significant liabilities related to  
their illness claims,'' he said. ``I also concluded we did not have 
any liability related to their discrimination claims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement calls for American Seafoods to conduct training  
on its discrimination policies and procedures, and provide 
quarterly compliance reports to the commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs sued after catching the flu while aboard one of  
the company's ships off Alaska in February 1998. They said American 
Seafoods failed to provide them with treatment and adequate time 
off work for recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers said the company created a hostile work environment,  
denied them training and promotional opportunities, subjected them 
to poor working conditions, demoted them and terminated those who 
sought time off due to illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Hyde said none of the plaintiffs had ever asked for promotion.  
</P>
<P>
	``Processing crews throughout the industry are predominantly  
composed of minorities. They're the backbone of our operation,'' he 
said. ``The only people discriminated against on our boat are 
people who don't work hard.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 14:41:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Golota Expecting To Fight Clean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Michael Grant got some good news from Andrew  
Golota on Wednesday concerning their Nov. 20 fight between 
heavyweight contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``From my side, I think the fight is going to be clean, you  
know, nothing like my other fights,'' Golota, a native of Poland 
living a Chicago, said of the 12-round bout at Trump Taj Mahal in 
Atlantic City, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Golota (34-3, 28 knockouts) is best known for two of his losses.  
He was disqualified twice for fouling Riddick Bowe -- in the seventh 
round July 11, 1996, at New York and in the ninth round Dec. 14, 
1996, at Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant, however, wasn't around to hear Golota's declaration since  
he was more than an hour late for the news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michael Grant -- he arrives on time for the fight,'' Golota  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant (30-0, 21 knockouts), of Norristown, Pa., said that after  
he arrived by train from Philadelphia he was unable to find the 
limousine that was supposed to pick him up at Penn Station. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to apologize,'' Grant said. ``I got a taxi and I gave  
him $20 and told him, `Get me there.' And you know it doesn't cost 
$20 to get here from Penn Station (about 27 blocks).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, it can cost more -- depending on the driver, traffic  
and gullibility of the passenger. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted this fight,'' Grant said. ``I'm happy about this  
fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The winner will be in line for a heavyweight title shot. WBC  
champion Lennox Lewis of Britain and WBA-IBF champion Evander 
Holyfield, who boxed a controversial draw March 13 at New York, 
will fight a rematch Nov. 13 at Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Grant's advisers is Jim Thomas, who is Holyfield's  
lawyer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
