<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Golota Expecting To Fight Clean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Michael Grant got some good news from Andrew  
Golota on Wednesday concerning their Nov. 20 fight between 
heavyweight contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``From my side, I think the fight is going to be clean, you  
know, nothing like my other fights,'' Golota, a native of Poland 
living a Chicago, said of the 12-round bout at Trump Taj Mahal in 
Atlantic City, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Golota (34-3, 28 knockouts) is best known for two of his losses.  
He was disqualified twice for fouling Riddick Bowe -- in the seventh 
round July 11, 1996, at New York and in the ninth round Dec. 14, 
1996, at Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant, however, wasn't around to hear Golota's declaration since  
he was more than an hour late for the news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``Michael Grant -- he arrives on time for the fight,'' Golota  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grant (30-0, 21 knockouts), of Norristown, Pa., said that after  
he arrived by train from Philadelphia he was unable to find the 
limousine that was supposed to pick him up at Penn Station. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to apologize,'' Grant said. ``I got a taxi and I gave  
him $20 and told him, `Get me there.' And you know it doesn't cost 
$20 to get here from Penn Station (about 27 blocks).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, it can cost more -- depending on the driver, traffic  
and gullibility of the passenger. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted this fight,'' Grant said. ``I'm happy about this  
fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The winner will be in line for a heavyweight title shot. WBC  
champion Lennox Lewis of Britain and WBA-IBF champion Evander 
Holyfield, who boxed a controversial draw March 13 at New York, 
will fight a rematch Nov. 13 at Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Grant's advisers is Jim Thomas, who is Holyfield's  
lawyer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
