<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Skirmish Over Bankruptcy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taking turns blocking the other party,  
senators are getting nowhere on a Democratic attempt to raise the 
minimum wage and on several judicial nominations while delaying a 
final vote on a bill overhauling bankruptcy law. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats blocked action Tuesday on the bankruptcy bill and the  
nomination of a federal judge for Utah, and Republicans responded 
by blocking final votes on President Clinton's choices for a 
California-based appeals court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's at their wit's end as to what to do,'' Sen. Dianne  
Feinstein, D-Calif., complained in the midst of the votes. She 
helped lead the charge to block the Utah nomination, saying the 
California appointees have been waiting for years and deserve 
Senate action. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart today cheered the Democrats'  
action, saying the Senate should move forward on all judicial 
nominees and not extend ``preferential treatment for one candidate 
that they have a particular interest in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We at the White House want to work through this impasse  
expeditiously and hope the Senate will provide for a vote on all 
our nominees,'' Lockhart said. ``People have been waiting as long 
as four years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the bankruptcy bill, Democrats derailed action in an attempt  
to have debate and a vote on an amendment to increase the minimum 
wage by $1 over two years. Republicans said they were willing to 
debate the minimum wage measure, but said Democrats also wanted 
votes on unrelated issues such as farm programs and gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 53-45, with one senator voting present, seven short  
of the 60 votes needed to move the measure toward passage. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments later, Democrats blocked efforts to force a speedy vote  
on Ted Stewart, a nominee to become a federal judge in Salt Lake 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart is backed by Sen. Orrin Hatch, the Utah Republican who  
chairs the Judiciary Committee. Democrats complained that while 
Republicans were eager to vote on Stewart, they were unwilling to 
vote on several other Clinton nominees. 
</P>
<P>
	So Democrats held ranks and the Senate voted 55-44, five votes  
short of the needed 60, to hold a final vote on Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, in a rare move, Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South  
Dakota sought to force a vote on two judicial nominees, District 
Judge Richard Paez and an attorney, Marsha Berzon, both of whom 
have been named to the appeals court. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Republicans' turn to block action, and they did so.  
</P>
<P>
	Daschle accused Republicans of seeking to choke off debate on  
the bankruptcy bill prematurely. He also said that dozens of 
Clinton's judicial nominations are awaiting action, including Paez, 
who was appointed more than three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to have these votes,'' Daschle said. ``We've got to  
confirm these nominees. We've got to have a bankruptcy bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a matter of breaking through the procedural morass, and  
I'm going to break through it,'' countered Hatch. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the skirmishing, all three nominations and the  
bankruptcy bill are still alive. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
