<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moss Hopes Vikes Can Start Rolling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Randy Moss swears he's not dwelling  
on his coming out party last year at Lambeau Field. But what better 
stage for the Minnesota Vikings to regain their confidence? 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the memories are always going to be there,'' Moss said  
Wednesday. ``But as far as motivating myself to go out and try to 
do the same thing as last year, I don't want to try to reminisce on 
that because I think that will probably get me away from my game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Oct. 5 last year, Randall Cunningham threw for 442 yards and  
four TDs, two of them to Moss, in the Vikings' 37-24 victory over 
the Packers. The loss ended Green Bay's 25-game home winning streak 
and signaled a shift in the NFC's power structure. 
</P>
<P>
	``It kind of reminded me of when I was at Southern Miss and we  
played teams like Florida State and Alabama and Texas A&AMP;M in that I 
knew we couldn't stop them,'' Packers quarterback Brett Favre said. 
</P>
<P>
	After his stunning 75-yard TD catch was negated by a holding  
call that night, Moss caught five passes for 190 yards and two long 
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, both teams were 4-0 and seeking the upper hand in the  
division race. This time, both are 1-1 and feel fortunate, at that. 
</P>
<P>
	This game is more about survival than swagger.  
</P>
<P>
	Moss, who caught 17 touchdown passes last year, including ones  
covering 52, 44 and 49 yards against Green Bay, has yet to see the 
end zone this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Moss said the Vikings need a breakout like last year's at  
Lambeau. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if we're close to one,'' Moss said. ``Hopefully,  
we are. I think we need one to show ourselves, not anybody outside 
the Minnesota Vikings, that we're ready to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moss has been blanketed by double- and triple-coverage.  
Cunningham's Pro Bowl-studded offensive line hasn't given him much 
time to hit his other targets. And Robert Smith is averaging a 
paltry 2.6 yards a carry. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're doubling, tripling me, we've just got to find a  
way to make it happen,'' Moss said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cunningham said he'll get rid of the ball faster, but that could  
further hamper the downfield passing game that led to 10 TDs of 
40-plus yards for Moss a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to Moss, the Packers chose defensive backs Antuan  
Edwards, Fred Vinson and Mike McKenzie with their first three draft 
picks and said good-bye to old-timers Pat Terrell, Rod Smith and 
Mike Prior. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest with you,'' Moss said, ``I didn't really pay too  
much attention to the draft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the Vikings got pass-rusher Dimitrius Underwood, who  
went AWOL after one practice, eventually leading Minnesota to bring 
Chris Doleman, who will be 38 next month, out of retirement this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings also brought back linebacker Corey Miller on  
Wednesday and cut ties with defensive backs Antonio Banks and Kevin 
Divine and fullback Obafemi Ayanbadejo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it did send a powerful message and opened a lot of  
eyes this morning, guys coming in moping around still with sleep in 
their eyes,'' Moss said. ``And Coach Green just got right to the 
point and let guys know he wasn't playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The players had a jump in their step at Wednesday's workout. And  
Moss said there's a feeling of anticipation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last two games we haven't really been in sync,'' he said.  
``So I think we will be pumped to see if we can get back on that 
path of being dominant. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just look forward to seeing Lambeau again.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
