<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deciding Supremacist's Fate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRYAN, Texas (AP) -- A jury on Wednesday weighed the  
life-or-death fate of a white supremacist who bragged that the 
dragging death of a black man had made him and his buddies ``bigger 
stars'' than O.J. Simpson. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel deliberated for 11 hours before recessing until  
Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	After hearing testimony over eight days, the panel had two  
options for Lawrence Russell Brewer: life in prison or death. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's former prison pal, John William King, 24, already is on  
death row, convicted and condemned in February for the murder of 
James Byrd Jr. A third man, Shawn Allen Berry, 24, is set to be 
tried next month. Prosecutors also will seek the death penalty in 
that case. 
</P>
<P>
	The same jury considering Brewer's punishment on Monday  
convicted the 32-year-old parolee, the ``exalted cyclops'' of his 
Ku Klux Klan splinter group, of capital murder. 
</P>
<P>
	In June 1998, Byrd, a former vacuum cleaner salesman from the  
east Texas timber town of Jasper, was harnessed by the ankles with 
a 24 1/2-foot logging chain to the bumper of a pickup truck and 
dragged for three miles along a rutted logging path and bumpy 
asphalt road. 
</P>
<P>
	``Under the circumstances of this case, obviously there is a  
serious need to protect future victims from this man,'' Jasper 
County District Attorney Guy James Gray told the jury Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's attorneys said the evidence did not support a death  
sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Society is going to be adequately protected'' by a life term,  
attorney Doug Barlow said. 
</P>
<P>
	After they were arrested, Brewer wrote letters to King saying he  
had become a ``hero'' and preferred execution, which he said would 
be ``a little old sleeping medicine,'' to a life sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at O.J.,'' Brewer wrote in one note. ``I do believe we  
are bigger stars, or should I say hero of the day, than what we 
ever expected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brewer's attorneys characterized the writings as mere bragging  
to impress other inmates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
