<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2-Year-Old Colt Bevo Has Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bevo, a top 2-year-old, had surgery to remove a  
bone chip in his left knee and not only will he be out the rest of 
year, but his status was in doubt for next year's Triple Crown 
races. 
</P>
<P>
	The colt was hurt while scoring an upset in Sunday's Belmont  
Futurity. 
</P>
<P>
	Bevo was shipped to the New Jersey Equine Clinic where he had  
surgery on Tuesday. The prognosis for his complete recovery is good 
but, according to trainer Bill Badgett, if it takes as long as four 
months, the outlook would be dim for the 2000 Triple Crown series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Absolutely, it has to go picture perfect,'' Badgett said.  
``With the timing, we'd have to get him back in a time frame that 
will allow us to get a couple of races into him before you get to 
the major races.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bevo, winner of four of his five career starts, won Saratoga's  
Grade II Special and added to his prestige when he upset More Than 
Ready in the Belmont Futurity. 
</P>
<P>
	Badgett believes Bevo suffered the injury nearing the wire in  
the Futurity. ``He was probably getting a bit tired,'' the trainer 
said. ``A lot of times when they run hard and that gutsy, they get 
a little tired. That's when something's going to go if it's going 
to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Badgett expects Bevo to begin his recuperation with a 30-day  
stay at Belmont Park before being shipped to Palm Beach Downs in 
Florida for the winter. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
