<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 14:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Finds World Economy on the Mend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Declaring that global economic conditions have  
``improved markedly,'' the International Monetary Fund on Wednesday 
released a generally upbeat forecast of economic prospects for the 
world through the year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	But IMF officials warned that unforeseen shocks such as a sudden  
plunge in America's high-flying stock market or a precipitous drop 
in the value of the dollar could disrupt the newfound optimism. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time since the Asian crisis struck in July 1997,  
the new IMF forecast actually represented an upward revision in 
growth predictions compared with the previous forecast. The IMF 
last issued a forecast in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF predicted that the global economy would grow by 3  
percent this year and an even better 3.5 percent next year. In May, 
the IMF had put growth this year at a lower 2.3 percent, increasing 
to 3.4 percent in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF said a stronger-than-expected U.S. economy and more  
vigorous and quicker rebounds in Asian crisis countries were the 
major factors contributing to the improved outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	IMF Chief Economist Michael Mussa said the IMF was making its  
forecast for next year ``with increasing confidence'' because of 
the multiplying number of favorable developments. 
</P>
<P>
	He said those developments also include ``a clear end to the  
recession'' in Japan, the world's second-largest economy, and 
shallower-than-expected recessions in Brazil and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said Wednesday that the  
upcoming annual meetings of the 182-nation IMF and World Bank were 
occurring in a far different environment than a year ago when the 
global economy was reeling from the collapse of the Russian ruble 
and the near-failure of a large U.S. hedge fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``A year ago the world was facing what was generally declared to  
be the most serious situation in global financial markets in 50 
years,'' Summers said in a speech at Yale University. ``Important 
challenges remain. But it is fair to say that we have pulled back 
from the abyss.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said the upcoming meetings of finance ministers in  
Washington would launch a new Group of 20, which will include the 
world's seven wealthiest nations and a collection of developing 
countries, to provide a broader forum to address efforts to 
overhaul the global financial architecture to prevent, or at least 
better handle, future financial crises. 
</P>
<P>
	He said this effort will not result in ``construction of a  
single edifice'' but rather ``an organic and ongoing process 
comprising the work of many governments and private sector actors'' 
over a number of years. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF forecast predicted that the gross domestic product in  
the United States would increase by 3.7 percent this year before 
slowing to 2.6 percent in 2000, numbers that would describe a 
hoped-for ``soft landing'' in which interest rate increases by the 
Federal Reserve slow growth enough to prevent inflation but don't 
plunge the country into a recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed has already raised interest rates twice this year and  
Mussa said that more rate increases may be needed. The IMF report 
also singled out the possibility of a sharp drop in the U.S. stock 
market or the dollar as two of the biggest downside risks to its 
forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	Mussa said proper policy coordination among governments will be  
crucial, and he suggested that might include joint intervention by 
the world's seven largest economies to buy dollars in an effort to 
stabilize the U.S. currency, which has dropped sharply in recent 
weeks in value against the Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's slide against the yen is expected to be one of the  
primary discussion topics when finance ministers and central banks 
presidents from the Group of Seven wealthy countries -- the United 
States, Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada -- meet on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF's upward economic revisions were even more dramatic for  
Japan, with Japanese growth forecast to rise by 1 percent this year 
and 1.5 percent in 2000. In May, the IMF was forecasting 1999 would 
be a second year of deep recession for Japan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
