<DOCNO> APW19990922.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Russell Now in Rancho Cucamonga </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) -- Bill Russell works about 45  
miles from Dodger Stadium, where he was employed before being fired 
15 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	It might as well be 45,000 miles.  
</P>
<P>
	Russell managed the Dodgers for nearly two years and spent more  
than 30 years in the organization. Now he works at The Epicenter, 
where he is manager of the Rancho Cucamonga Surfers of the 
California Fall League. 
</P>
<P>
	A hot, desert wind blew gently. Highway 15, the road to Las  
Vegas, is a couple blocks away. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a different life for Russell, who recently managed Orlando  
to the championship of the Class AA Southern League. He will spend 
the next six weeks managing the Surfers, a team of low-level minor 
leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Starting right off, I'll try to get to know everybody,''  
Russell said. ``First of all, I've got to know their names.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russell admits it took him several months to get over being  
fired and feels no vindication from the Dodgers' lack of success 
since. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't even think about it anymore,'' he said. ``I've got  
another job going. I really enjoy it, I want to do well. I'm in the 
minor leagues, I'm just like the players. I hope to get back to the 
major league level. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Dodgers gave me a great shot for over 30 years. That's the  
only way I look at it. I have no hard feelings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But when asked how he felt about the post-Bill Russell Dodgers,  
he replied: ``I have one comment: It was mentioned that the village 
idiot could manage the Dodgers. That's all I want to say about 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davey Johnson made that statement last fall before being hired  
as the team's manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell, who played for the Dodgers from 1969-86, was fired  
along with general manager Fred Claire on June 21, 1998 -- three 
months after the Fox Group took control of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers were 36-38 and finished the season with an 83-79  
record. This year has been a disaster despite several offseason 
additions, led by pitcher Kevin Brown, and one of baseball's 
highest payrolls. 
</P>
<P>
	After he was dismissed, Russell spent his first summer in more  
than 30 years without the structure of baseball. He and his wife, 
Susan, did some traveling. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came reality.  
</P>
<P>
	``I went to the winter meetings last December in Nashville,'' he  
said. ``I was looking for a job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russell, whose overall record as manager of the Dodgers was  
173-149, found one -- manager at Orlando, an affiliate of the Tampa 
Bay Devil Rays. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really pleased about that,'' he said of winning the  
Southern League championship. ``The first half, we really 
struggled. The second half, we started believing in ourselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And winning.  
</P>
<P>
	It took him until spring training to bounce back from the  
firing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurt a lot, at first,'' he said. ``Whenever something like  
that happens for the first time, it's like a death. You're told 
your services are no longer wanted. You have to have time to 
grieve. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team wasn't jelling, (Fox) had just bought the team, they  
wanted to try something different. I had never been fired before. 
Over time, you get over it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 50-year-old manager said he's glad to be back in Southern  
California. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is ideal for me. I can go home every day,'' said Russell,  
who still lives in Glendale, not far from Dodger Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	`We're very happy to have Bill because of the Dodger connection,  
the old Dodger connection,'' said Pat Filippone, the general 
manager of the Surfers and the Rancho Cucamonga Quakes of the Class 
A California League. ``He's a symbol of the old Dodgers. The 
players are excited about playing for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cedrick Bowers, a 21-year-old left-hander who played for Russell  
at Orlando, will play for him again in Rancho Cucamonga. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's comfortable,'' Bowers said. ``He's a great guy, on and  
off the field, not just as the manager. The thing I like best about 
him -- he's straight up with you, he says it like it is.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
