<HEADLINE> Singapore, Indonesia Sign Gas Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Singapore Power Ltd. signed a  
preliminary agreement on Wednesday to purchase $7 billion worth of 
natural gas from Pertamina, Indonesia's state-owned oil and gas 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract is expected to be signed in December.  
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Pertamina will sell 2.27 trillion cubic  
feet of natural gas from fields in south Sumatra over 20 years 
starting in mid-2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore Power signed the agreement through its subsidiary  
PowerGas Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	In the initial stage, Singapore Power will purchase 150 million  
cubic feet of natural gas daily, with the amount increasing to 350 
million cubic feet by 2008, the two companies said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The gas will be piped to Singapore through a 325 kilometer (200  
mile) pipeline from gas fields in the south of Indonesia's Sumatra 
island by the state-owned gas company PT Perusahaan Gas Negara. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian gas fields are operated by Gulf Resources Ltd.  
and Santa Fe Energy Resources Jabung Ltd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
