<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Spur DaimlerChrysler, GM Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Flood-related problems at a parts company in  
North Carolina have created headaches at some auto factories in the 
United States and Canada, forcing automakers to cut production. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers at seven assembly plants owned by DaimlerChrysler AG and  
three owned by General Motors Corp. are working half-shifts due to 
a lack of a single part. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler said it was lacking a ``suspension part,'' while  
GM said it was lacking a disc brake bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	GM spokesman Gerry Holmes said the slowdown was due to flooding  
problems at a Simpson Industries Inc. plant in Greenville, N.C. 
DaimlerChrysler spokesman Dan Moore said the part came from a North 
Carolina supplier, but declined to name the company. 
</P>
<P>
	A Simpson spokesman did not immediately return a message.  
</P>
<P>
	To hold down costs, automakers tend to keep parts inventories as  
low as possible, relying on ``just-in-time'' systems where parts 
are delivered as they are needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes and Moore said production could continue with parts that  
were on their way when the flooding began. Holmes said the main 
problem was that the flood cut off most of the roads to the 
factory, keeping workers and parts from coming and going. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Floyd dumped more than 20 inches of rain in the region  
last week; more rain this week has sent waters rising again. 
</P>
<P>
	The affected DaimlerChrysler assembly plants include Sterling  
Heights, Mich. Warren, Mich.; Belvidere, Ill.; Newark, Del.; one 
plant in Fenton, Mo.; and two in Canada. GM said its 
Detroit-Hamtramck; Orion, Mich.; and Oshawa, Ontario, plants were 
running half shifts Wednesday. Holmes said the Detroit and Orion 
plants will try to run full shifts Thursday. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
