<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dutch Journalist Killed in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- A Dutch journalist was killed and two  
others were assaulted in separate attacks in East Timor blamed on 
anti-independence militiamen, officials and witnesses said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The mutilated body of Sander Thoenes, a 30-year-old reporter for  
London's Financial Times newspaper, was found today in the Dili 
suburb of Becora, the scene of heavy activity by militias and their 
Indonesian military backers, said Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri, 
commander of Indonesian forces in the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorcycle driver Florindo Araujo said he was taking the Dutch  
journalist to Becora on Tuesday, when they approached a roadblock 
staffed by at least six armed men wearing what Araujo said were the 
gray uniforms of the Indonesian police. 
</P>
<P>
	The two turned around, but some of the armed men gave chase,  
firing warning shots and eventually shooting out the motorcycle's 
rear wheel. Araujo, who fled, last saw Thoenes lying in the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoenes was believed to be the first foreigner killed since  
international peacekeeping troops landed in Dili on Monday and the 
first foreign reporter killed in East Timor since six 
Australia-based journalists were slain in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoenes, who also worked for The Christian Science Monitor and  
Dutch news magazine Vrij Nederland, was the Financial Times' 
Jakarta correspondent and previously had worked as its Central Asia 
correspondent based in Almaty, Kazakstan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sander was one of the FT's finest foreign correspondents and a  
wonderful friend and colleague,'' said Richard Lambert, editor of 
the Financial Times. ``He was full of enthusiasm and showed great 
initiative and flair in everything he did. He was devoted to 
getting to the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The International Federation of Journalists expressed outrage  
over Thoenes' death, calling it a blatant attempt to stop 
journalists from reporting on what was happening in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Militiamen have vowed to kill Westerners, whom they accuse of  
helping East Timor in its efforts to break free of Indonesian rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Maj. Gen. Peter Cosgrove, commander of the  
international force in the Indonesian territory, said the militias 
were attempting a show of force in Dili and the attacks were 
``obviously a reaction to our presence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It would appear that the militia have attempted to step up  
some activities as a show that all is not yet secure,'' Cosgrove 
said. ``We are imposing some level of control in the close part of 
the city. However ... it is still a dangerous place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the second incident in the hills near Becora, a car carrying  
London Sunday Times correspondent Jon Swain and Chip Hires, an 
American photographer for the Gamma agency, was attacked by what 
Cosgrove said were assumed to be ``militia elements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hires said their driver lost an eye when he was beaten before  
being taken away. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian troops eventually rescued them.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
