<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's fondness for cigars is a  
bad habit he hasn't kicked, his spokesman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart did not try to square  
the habit with Clinton's vocal opposition to cigarette smoking by 
young people, or with White House support for the Justice 
Department's just-announced civil suit against tobacco companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the president believes that's a bad habit, but it's a  
habit he hasn't broken,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart did not say whether Clinton is trying to give up  
cigars. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House maintains some mystery about whether Clinton  
actually smokes cigars, or merely chews on them, as he has been 
photographed doing. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart has said he has never seen Clinton light up.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will not be the featured speaker at an upcoming National  
Endowment for the Humanities dinner that traditionally features a 
leading academic at the podium. 
</P>
<P>
	The NEH, often accused by Republicans of holding culturally and  
politically liberal biases, was criticized by Republicans and some 
academics for making the unusual speaking invitation to Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't want the important work that they do to be called  
into question,'' Lockhart said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax-supported NEH funds museum exhibits, TV and radio  
programs and other research into the humanities. It is chaired by a 
Clinton appointee. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton never formally accepted the offer to deliver the NEH's  
Jefferson Lecture, and decided against doing so in part to avoid 
questions about whether a politician is an appropriate speaker, 
Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think any ... continuing of debate might have the effect of  
calling what they do into question, and the president wanted no 
part of that,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The White House delayed a veto showdown with the GOP over tax  
cuts on Wednesday, but managed to find a few other opportunities to 
aim some political firepower at congressional Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart called three senators' criticism of Clinton's foreign  
travel glib and uninformed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think, put very bluntly, the comments are just ignorant,''  
Lockhart said, repeating the word several times. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart also was irked by GOP remarks that there is little  
chance of congressional support for China's bid to join the World 
Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., publicly undermined  
U.S. trade negotiators by saying Congress won't have time to 
consider China's WTO bid this year, Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said he doubts the  
measure can win necessary congressional support. Lockhart said the 
timing of that remark ``just doesn't strike me as responsible 
leadership.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
