<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: HMOs in Medicare Reduce Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many of the 6.3 million Medicare recipients in  
HMOs are facing new restrictions on their coverage and increased 
out-of-pocket expenses, Vice President Al Gore said Wednesday, 
pushing for the adoption of an administration plan to revamp the 
program for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	A Health Care Financing Administration review of Medicare  
beneficiaries in HMOs said that about 21 percent currently have an 
annual cap of $500 or less on the amount they may spend on 
prescription drugs. By 2000, that percentage will increase to 
almost one-third of recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, who is running for president, released the findings on  
behalf of the Clinton administration at a Washington meeting of the 
American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also said the 1 million beneficiaries in HMOs who now  
have no copayments for prescription drugs will have to pay by 2000. 
Copayments for brand name drugs will increase 21 percent, with 
generic drugs' copayments increasing 8 percent, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too many of America's working families depending on Medicare  
cannot depend on their HMOs to deliver the affordable, critical 
benefits that convinced them to choose an HMO in the first place,'' 
Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare, the government health insurance program for the  
elderly, provides care to roughly 40 million seniors annually, 
including about 33 million beneficiaries in a traditional 
fee-for-service program. The administration has called for an 
improved payment system for health care providers and a 
prescription drug benefit for the program's beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	At a House Ways and Means subcommittee hearing on strengthening  
Medicare, Chairman Bill Thomas, R-Calif., said Wednesday that the 
program ``cannot keep pace with the changes of the health care 
marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But ``we can improve Medicare both administratively and  
structurally to offer seniors more health care choices,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In July, the administration announced that about 327,000  
Medicare beneficiaries could lose coverage because several large 
managed care providers plan to pull out of the Medicare market. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the report said providers that plan to stay in the  
program will charge higher premiums for enrollment. That means some 
3 million beneficiaries who do not pay premiums now will have to 
pay them by 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human  
services, on Wednesday announced a campaign to enroll children in 
free or low-cost health care programs through the Children's Health 
Insurance Program. The back-to-school campaign will include 45 
events in 25 communities and a $1 million radio campaign. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
