<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davis Love III: Let's Play Five  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Now that he's reacquainted with his golf  
clubs, Davis Love III wants to put them to use. 
</P>
<P>
	Love, who didn't hit a ball for almost three weeks to rest a  
pinched nerve in his neck, said he is ready to play in the maximum 
of five Ryder Cup matches for the U.S. team this weekend, if 
needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I could,'' he said Wednesday after a second day of  
practice on The Country Club course. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think so when I talked to him (U.S. captain Ben  
Crenshaw) at the PGA Championship. I said, `If you want me to not 
play, tell me. Because right now I can't give you a 36-hole day. 
Now I think I'm the opposite.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although it's unlikely that Crenshaw will take him up on the  
offer, it is a good sign for a player who pinched a nerve in his 
neck in mid-August and later went 19 days without touching a club. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team and I are elated over the way he feels, the way he's  
playing right now. He feels wonderful,'' Crenshaw said. ``I think 
the two weeks of rest did him a world of good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Love was at the PGA Championship when he first felt a twinge in  
his neck and numbness in his hands. He played anyway for the next 
two weeks before shutting down completely. 
</P>
<P>
	For 19 days, he didn't so much look at his clubs. The first time  
he touched them again was last Friday to move them from his old bag 
to the red, white and blue one given to the U.S. team members. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as I don't do anything to reinjure it, I think I'm in  
very good shape,'' Love said Wednesday. ``I'd be lying if I said 
I'm 100 percent, but I'm probably 90 percent. I'm hitting the ball 
as good or better than I have all year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never really come back hitting the ball this good from a  
layoff. I was having problems before that were affecting my swing, 
and now they've gone away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament consists of four matches on Friday morning, four  
more in the afternoon and the same schedule on Saturday. On Sunday, 
there are 12 singles matches; it's the only day that everyone on 
the roster must play. 
</P>
<P>
	That means that a golfer can play in as many as five matches and  
as few as one. As is the tradition, Crenshaw has held his cards 
close to his vest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have some things in mind,'' he said. ``My problem right now  
is leaving four guys out the first day because I feel like a lot of 
guys are playing well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crenshaw said Wednesday's rain was beneficial because it gave  
the golfers a chance to see the course under different conditions. 
But for Love, the wet, colder weather also challenged his powers of 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, I think, was a pretty good test,'' Crenshaw said.  
``This is a day where you can feel a few strains here and there and 
he came through wonderful and he played well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But playing 90 holes in 60 hours could be another story.  
</P>
<P>
	``The perfect world for me right now would be to maybe sit out  
an alternate-shot match,'' Love said. ``But I've told Ben, 'Hey, if 
guys are playing better than me, I want to win. I'll sit out all 
four if it means we can win.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
