<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Tells of Vieques Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ending the U.S. military's live-fire training  
on the tiny Puerto Rican island of Vieques would compromise the 
combat readiness of American troops and create a national security 
risk, military officials told Congress on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the inhabited island is the only place on the East  
Coast with all the qualities needed for war games training from the 
air, sea and ground simultaneously, which most closely simulates 
real conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a nutshell, the training on Vieques is critical to the  
readiness of the forces we deploy from the East Coast of the United 
States,'' Navy Vice Adm. William Fallon told the Senate Armed 
Services subcommittee on readiness. ``There is no place that even 
comes close to replicating the target possibilities that exist in 
Vieques.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A moratorium has been placed on live-fire exercises there since  
an errant Marine Corps bomb in April killed a 35-year-old Puerto 
Rican civilian and wounded four others. A four-member Pentagon 
panel is reviewing training on the 22-mile island and is expected 
to make a recommendation to the Clinton administration shortly. 
</P>
<P>
	But the subcommittee's chairman, Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla.,  
said he feared that President Clinton would politicize the Vieques 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	To bolster his contention, Inhofe released a Clinton memo to his  
national security adviser, Sandy Berger, in which he said it ``is 
wrong'' to use Vieques as a training range. The note was written on 
a letter to Clinton from the Puerto Rican Independence Party that 
included a plea to end the target training on Vieques. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't want us there, that's the main point,'' Clinton  
wrote. ``The Navy can find a way to work around it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also wrote: ``What about the prisoners?''  
</P>
<P>
	The president has been under fire for his offer of clemency to  
16 Puerto Rican separatists. He has been accused of making the 
offer to bolster Hillary Rodham Clinton's standing among New York's 
1.3 million Puerto Ricans as she eyes a run for the Senate from 
that state. She opposed the clemency offer. 
</P>
<P>
	A Clinton administration official said the president's note  
shows the ``compassion he feels for the Puerto Rican people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It should not be interpreted to mean that the president has  
made a final determination on Vieques,'' the official said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Puerto Rican lawmakers and their supporters gathered on Capitol  
Hill to reiterate their long-held opposition to the use of Vieques 
for live-fire exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is time to free the people of Vieques from the military  
occupation of their home,'' said Rep. Nydia Velasquez, D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Testifying before congressional committees, Fallon and Marine  
Lt. Gen. Peter Pace stressed that the Rodriguez's death was the 
first in the more than 50 years the military has used the area for 
target practice. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
