<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justice Dept. Sues Tobacco Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- The way Attorney General Janet Reno  
explained it, the government has a duty to sue cigarette makers to 
recover billions of dollars taxpayers have spent treating sick 
smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	The way Oscar Giles and others in America's tobacco belt see it,  
their country has gone to war with their livelihood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people apparently view the tobacco companies as cash cows  
or the Golden Goose. Even the Golden Goose runs out of eggs,'' said 
Giles, president of the union which represents workers at a plant 
where Philip Morris rolls out 730 million cigarettes every day. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department sued the nation's tobacco industry  
Wednesday, seeking billions from cigarette makers it accuses of 
waging a 45-year campaign ``to preserve their enormous profits 
whatever the cost in human lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleges the companies have conspired since the 1950s  
to defraud and mislead the public. The industry concealed data that 
showed nicotine is addictive and smoking causes disease, sponsored 
biased research and suppressed development of safer cigarettes in 
violation of federal anti-racketeering law, the suit alleges. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cigarette companies realized -- at least since 1953 -- that  
the truth poses a mortal threat to their businesses,'' Reno said in 
Washington. Federal health plans spend more than $20 billion a year 
treating smoking-related illnesses, which kill 400,000 people a 
year, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing internal company documents, Assistant Attorney General  
David Ogden traced the alleged conspiracy to a meeting of cigarette 
company chief executives at the Plaza Hotel in New York in January 
1954. They ``agreed there to wage a long-term public relations 
campaign based on fraud and based on deception,'' Ogden said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit names Philip Morris Inc.; Philip Morris Companies; R.J.  
Reynolds Tobacco Co.; American Tobacco Co.; Brown &AMP; Williamson 
Tobacco Corp.; British-American Tobacco P.L.C.; British-American 
Tobacco (Investments) Ltd.; Lorillard Tobacco Co. Inc.; Liggett and 
Myers Inc.; The Council for Tobacco Research U.S.A. Inc.; and the 
Tobacco Institute Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Company lawyers questioned the government's case and motives,  
especially in light of decades of federal government warnings about 
the health dangers from smoking. 
</P>
<P>
	``This blatantly political lawsuit is ... the height of  
hypocrisy,'' said Greg Little, associate general counsel of Philip 
Morris. 
</P>
<P>
	The repeated legal assaults have taken a toll in Virginia and  
especially in Richmond, where tobacco is an economic mainstay. 
Philip Morris employs 6,900 people locally. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people are nervous about their jobs'' Giles said.  
``We've just had seven months of four-day work weeks. That makes 
people very uneasy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the past year, the tobacco industry has agreed to pay nearly  
$250 billion over 25 years to settle lawsuits states brought to 
recover their costs of treating smoking-related illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was fat, dumb and happy four years ago working five, six,  
seven days a week. Now I'm losing 20 percent of my pay,'' said 
Frank Holloman, who has put in 27 years at the Richmond plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia's ties to tobacco date to the 1600s, and painted images  
of tobacco leaves adorn the inside of the state Capitol dome. In 
1997, tobacco accounted for $4.6 billion of the state's $211 
billion economy, according to state figures. Virginia's tax on 
cigarettes -- 2.5 cents per pack -- is the nation's lowest. 
</P>
<P>
	But the leaf is slowly losing ground.  
</P>
<P>
	Ray Emerson has raised tobacco in Pittsylvania County all his  
life, and his son joined him in the family business. Now, Emerson 
sees bleak times ahead and is advising his grandson to stay out. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would like to see him stay on the farm but we just don't  
see any future in it,'' Emerson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're at the place where we can't sell out because we can't  
get anything for our equipment. At the market, the price you get 
keeps going down. It's like we're caught in a squeeze. You keep 
throwing these lawsuits on top of it, it just doesn't seem worth 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sympathy for the tobacco industry, however, is by no means  
universal in Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to see them bankrupt the tobacco companies,''  
said Hilton Oliver, executive director of the Virginia Group to 
Alleviate Smoking in Public (GASP) in Virginia Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety-eight to 99 percent of the people in Virginia have  
nothing to do with tobacco,'' he said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
