<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Come Here Often' Has Some Laughs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Call it the Three Stooges meet Samuel Beckett by  
way of Monty Python. 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, there are only two of them and they go by the names of  
Hamish McColl and Sean Foley. McColl is the intense, more excitable 
one; Foley, his sweetly quizzical sparring partner. Together they 
struggle to survive in an existential fun house called ``Do You 
Come Here Often?'' now on view off-Broadway at P.S. 122. 
</P>
<P>
	It takes a while to warm up to these fellows and the off-kilter  
world they have created under their collective name -- the Right 
Size. One worries beforehand that this will be arty material, 
highbrow humor requiring a Ph.D. in Sarte to laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	No problem. Check your academic credentials at the door. No need  
to hyperventilate about the meaning of life or this duo's 
confinement in a single room during their 70 minutes of high jinks. 
Guys who include yellow rubber ducks in their act and bits of 
physical business that would satisfy Larry, Moe and Curly (watch 
out for that wooden plank!) are A-OK. 
</P>
<P>
	McColl and Foley -- or rather the not-so-sad sacks they portray --  
live together in a bathroom, a space dominated by a toilet, placed 
center stage. Yet the jokes are anything but raunchy. Aunt Mildred 
from Terre Haute and the kids will feel right at home. 
</P>
<P>
	The twosome quibble, bicker, snap and downright fight. McColl  
and Foley also sing and dance in a bit of absurdist vaudeville that 
suggests they could have played the Palace back in the glory days. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't go expecting a plot to slowly materialize. A story has  
been supplanted by bits of funny business that cleverly build 
throughout the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	There are some wonderful sight gags. The best: McColl dressed as  
a flower, his head surrounded by petals, while Foley plays a busy 
bee intent on some pollen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Right Size supplies the right amount of laughs in ``Do You  
Come Here Often?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 08:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Auto Output a Mixed Picture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Domestic production rose at two major Japanese  
automobile manufacturers in August, was steady at a third and fell 
at two others, the companies said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic auto output is closely watched as an indicator of  
economic health because it accounts for a big part of Japan's 
industrial production. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some signs of an economic improvement, Japan is still  
struggling to pull out of its worst economic downturn since World 
War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Production in Japan was up 9.4 percent at both Toyota, Japan's  
largest automaker, and at Honda in August. Domestic production held 
steady at Nissan and was down 5.3 percent at Mazda and 15 percent 
at Mitsubishi. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota's domestic production climbed to 203,925 vehicles from  
August a year ago, marking its first increase in monthly production 
in three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota's sales in Japan rose 3.2 percent to 89,379, giving it a  
38.3 percent share of the domestic market, excluding mini-vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota said exports jumped 15.9 percent to 103,130 in August as  
shipments to North America, Europe and Asia rose. Toyota made 
127,442 vehicles at overseas plants, up 12.7 percent, helped mainly 
by rising output in North America and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda Motor said production in Japan rose 9.4 percent to 84,685  
vehicles, helped by improved domestic demand for its vehicles and 
rising exports to North America and Europe. It was Honda's second 
straight monthly rise in domestic production. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda's domestic sales surged 19.1 percent to 46,561, led by  
continued popularity of its mini-vehicles and wagons. The company's 
total exports rose 15.7 percent to 37,821. Honda produced 84,000 
vehicles at overseas plants, up 3.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan Motor, Japan's second-largest automaker, said its  
domestic production stood at 96,038 in August, unchanged from a 
year ago, but its overseas production climbed 17.2 percent to 
81,497. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan said domestic sales rose 1.5 percent to 47,283, while  
exports fell 8.5 percent to 44,842 vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda Motor and Mitsubishi Motors Corp. reported declines in  
domestic production and sales as well as exports in August. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda's domestic output dropped 5.3 percent to 53,558 vehicles,  
as sales edged down 1.3 percent to 21,266 and exports dropped 15.5 
percent to 33,853. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda said overseas production, however, increased 13.4 percent  
to 9,538, rising for the fourth straight month, boosted by 
increased production of pickup trucks at its joint-venture with 
American automaker Ford Motor Co. in Thailand. Hiroshima-based 
Mazda is 33.3 percent owned by Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitsubishi Motors said domestic production fell 15.0 percent to  
64,375 vehicles, while sales edged down 0.90 percent to 32,746 in 
Japan. Its exports fell 27.5 percent to 33,981 vehicles. 
Mitsubishi's overseas production rose 11.5 percent to 50,501 in 
August. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
