<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ravens' Mitchell Benched Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWINGS MILLS, Md. (AP) -- Scott Mitchell envisioned himself  
duplicating the 1998 season of Randall Cunningham, who resurrected 
his career under the guidance and direction of offensive whiz Brian 
Billick. 
</P>
<P>
	Much to his dismay, Mitchell has become this year's version of,  
well, Scott Mitchell. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Mitchell lost his starting job with the Detroit  
Lions after the second week of the season. He now finds himself in 
the same position with the Baltimore Ravens, having dropped to 
third on the depth chart after two straight ineffective 
performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell, replaced by Stoney Case in the third quarter of  
Sunday's 23-20 loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers, has thrown four 
interceptions and just one touchdown. He's 24-for-56 for 236 yards 
and dead last in the AFC with a dismal 31.5 quarterback rating. 
</P>
<P>
	That's hardly what coach Billick had in mind when he helped  
mastermind the trade that brought Mitchell to Baltimore in March. 
The Ravens, and Mitchell, hoped a change of scenery would enable 
him to display the talent he showed in 1995, when the left-hander 
threw 32 touchdown passes for the Lions and topped the 4,000-yard 
mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Billick had a profound effect on Cunningham last year while he  
was the Minnesota Vikings' offensive coordinator. Cunningham, who 
played in only five games in 1997, finished with an NFL-best 106.0 
quarterback rating and became one of the year's biggest comeback 
stories. 
</P>
<P>
	The stage was set for Mitchell to do the same following a season  
in which he languished on the bench for the final 14 games. But 
Case will start Sunday against the Cleveland Browns, while Mitchell 
will likely be deemed inactive as the third quarterback behind Tony 
Banks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is I didn't play good, for whatever reason. It  
doesn't matter,'' Mitchell said Wednesday. ``The coach felt like we 
needed a change. I'm disappointed about it. I feel like I just 
haven't played to how I'm capable of doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell, 31, bemoaned his fate in Detroit. It's no easier the  
second time around, but he's not feeling sorry for himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``How did he react? The same way anyone in that position  
would,'' Billick said. ``You're not particularly happy with it and 
you don't necessarily see it the same way. But you're going to go 
do your job and be part of the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell led stretching exercises during Wednesday's practice,  
but there is some question as to whether he will ever get the 
chance to lead the Ravens to victory on a Sunday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the way this business is,'' he said. ``So I've got to  
buckle down, get to work and help the team any way I can. I've got 
to try to keep my sanity and hope I get another chance to go out 
there.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
