<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Is Magic Number in Estate Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Three years is the magic number in estate  
planning. To put it bluntly, it sometimes can save you a lot of 
money if you live at least three years after giving away part of 
your estate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Estate tax problems can occur if you die within three years of  
making certain types of gifts,'' says E.G. McBroom, an estate 
planning expert at the College for Financial Planning. 
</P>
<P>
	``People may give away an ownership interest in something, such  
as a life insurance policy or their home, thinking the gift will 
keep the asset out of their estate so it won't face federal estate 
taxes,'' McBroom says. ``But if they die within three years of the 
transfer, certain assets will still be included in their estate and 
be subject to tax.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, you don't need to worry about federal estate taxes  
unless your estate is valued at your death at more than $650,000 in 
1999, or $675,000 in 2000. But if your estate value exceeds that 
total, you may find it beneficial to give away some of your estate 
while you are still alive, says McBroom. The key is knowing what's 
best to give away. 
</P>
<P>
	The most common gifting mistake involves life insurance.  
</P>
<P>
	``People often read that by transferring the ownership of life  
insurance in which they are the insured to an irrevocable life 
insurance trust for their children, they can keep the policy's 
death benefit out of their estate,'' McBroom says. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they may be unaware of, however, is if they die within  
three years of that transfer the death benefit would be included in 
their taxable estate. In short, they've given up ownership of the 
policy, which includes the right to change beneficiaries or to 
borrow against the policy, yet they've not achieved the estate tax 
benefits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One way to avoid the three-year wait is to first set up the  
irrevocable trust and have the trust buy the life insurance on your 
life. The trust owns the policy and there is no three-year rule. 
McBroom cautions that if you already own life insurance, don't drop 
it until the trust has completed purchase of new insurance, just in 
case it turns out that you are no longer insurable. 
</P>
<P>
	McBroom says the three-year rule also doesn't apply if you  
transfer into a trust life insurance you own on someone else's 
life, such as your spouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The home is another asset that faces the three-year rule, says  
McBroom. People often learn that they can avoid probate on their 
home by transferring an ownership interest in the home (called 
``remainder interest'') to their children while retaining the 
lifetime right to live in the home. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps years later the parents or surviving parent become so  
ill they have to go to a nursing home or other long term care 
facility. At that point, they may give up their lifetime rights to 
stay in the home and let their children become full owners. 
However, if the parent dies within three years of giving up their 
lifetime rights, the home will be included in the parent's estate. 
</P>
<P>
	The same issue arises with revocable trusts. It's popular for  
people to set up revocable living trusts in order to avoid probate. 
However, when they learn that the assets held in the trust will be 
included in their estate, they decide to convert it to an 
irrevocable trust. However, as before, says McBroom, they will have 
to live at least three years; otherwise, the assets come back into 
their estate for federal estate tax purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, says McBroom, an irrevocable trust set up and funded  
from scratch, instead of converted from a revocable trust, doesn't 
face the three-year rule, unless the crator of the trust transfers 
life insurance into it or retains certain specified rights to the 
trust. The creator of the trust could die the day after the trust 
is created and assets used to fund the trust such as mutual funds, 
securities, and cash would not be included in the creator's estate. 
</P>
<P>
	McBroom says some people may still be under the impression that  
what was called the ``contemplation of death'' rule still applies 
to lifetime transfers. That rule said that the three-year rule 
applied to all assets that were transferred. But the rule was 
changed in 1981, and now the three-year-wait rule only applies to 
the gifting of life insurance ownership and gifting of other assets 
when the donor retains certain specified rights such as the 
lifetime right to use or income or the right to revoke the 
transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The important thing is to anticipate these transfers far  
enough ahead as you can,'' McBroom says. ``Depending on your 
circumstances, you may then decide whether it's better to give up 
control of life insurance or a home, versus securities or other 
assets not covered by the three-year wait.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *End advance for Thursday, Sept. 23, and thereafter    	
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
