<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris Companies, down 1 1/8 at 34 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department is suing major tobacco companies to  
recover billions of dollars taxpayers have spent on smoking-related 
health care. The long-anticipated civil lawsuit would allege that 
the companies conspired to cover up the health risks of smoking. 

</P>
<P>
	Asarco, up 2 1/16 at 22 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	Cyprus Amax Minerals, up 1 9/16 at 18 13/16  
</P>
<P>
	Phelps Dodge sweetened its offer to acquire the copper makers,  
which already plan to merge and have rejected the unsolicited bid. 
The new bid adds $1 billion in cash to the previously all-stock 
offer, valuing Asarco at $25.47 a share, or $1.01 billion, and 
Cyprus at $19.49 a share, or $1.76 billion. That compares with the 
previous bid of $932 million and $1.62 billion, respectively. 

</P>
<P>
	Tektronix, up 1 5/16 at 36 3/16  
</P>
<P>
	Xerox is paying $950 million to buy Tektronix's color printing  
division. Tektronix, based in Wilsonville, Ore., currently holds 
the second-largest share of the office color printing market. 

</P>
<P>
	EEX, down 1/2 at 4 1/4  
</P>
<P>
	The Houston-based company will temporarily suspend further  
drilling of a well at its Mackerel Prospect in Mississippi Canyon 
in order to conduct additional seismic and geological evaluations. 

</P>
<P>
	Cordant Technologies, down 7 1/4 at 34 7/8  
</P>
<P>
	Howmet International, down 2 1/2 at 15 3/8  
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake City-based manufacturer of aerospace and other  
industrial components expects to report disappointing results due 
to continued production problems at its Howmet Aluminum unit. 
Cardant also said the decrease in the commercial aircraft market 
exceeded internal estimates at its Huck International and Howmet 
International units. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	
</P>
<P>
	3Com, up 1 5/16 at 28 5/8  
</P>
<P>
	The company reported late Tuesday its quarterly operating  
profits jumped 38 percent amid strong demand for its Palm Pilot 
electronic organizers and computer networking equipment. Overall 
revenues declined due to a drop in modem sales, but the report 
easily exceeded Wall Street expectations. 

</P>
<P>
	Laser Power, up 1 1/8 at 2 3/8  
</P>
<P>
	II-VI Inc. formally proposed to acquire Laser Power for $3 a  
share in cash and stock. However, II-VI added, Laser Power has 
again elected not to pursue serious merger discussions. Laser Power 
designs optical devices and lasers. II-VI makes lenses, mirror and 
other optical components used to manipulate laser beams. 

</P>
<P>
	Sinclair Broadcast Group, down 4 3/16 at 10 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	Merrill Lynch, Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter  
downgraded Sinclair following late Tuesday's warning by the 
broadcasting company about profits for the second half of 1999. 
Baltimore-based Sinclair blamed a soft television advertising 
market and aggressive investing to increase local revenue. 

</P>
<P>
	Bottomline Technologies, down 8 1/2 at 16 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	The maker of software for money transactions warned late Tuesday  
it will post disappointing revenues for its first quarter ending 
Sept. 30. Bottomline, based in Portsmouth, N.H., said customers are 
growing hesitant about adding new applications amid uncertainty 
over the Y2K computer bug. 

</P>
<P>
	Chemdex, up 4 1/2 at 32 1/8  
</P>
<P>
	The electronic-commerce company agreed to acquire Promedix.com,  
a Salt Lake City-based operator of an online marketplace for 
medical products, for stock valued at $331.5 million. The deal 
doesn't include Promedix.com's distribution business, which will be 
spun off by the the privately held company. Chemdex is based in 
Palo Alto, Calif. 



  	   	
</P>
