<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Debt Relief Proposals Get a Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration asked Congress on  
Tuesday to support a sharp increase in debt relief for the world's 
poorest countries in a move that supporters praised as the dramatic 
gesture needed to salvage the effort from defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	A plan to offer $90 billion in debt relief to the world's  
poorest nations, many of them in Africa, was endorsed in June by 
the world's seven wealthiest countries in Cologne, Germany, at 
their annual economic summit. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the proposal since then has run into roadblocks  
including a campaign by the gold industry to block direct sales of 
gold from the International Monetary Fund's reserves to finance 
part of the debt relief. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. officials indicated Tuesday they believe they were  
close to overcoming all objections in time for the debt relief 
package to win approval at next week's joint annual meetings of the 
182-nation IMF and the World Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers told reporters the  
administration had sent Congress a new request to more than triple 
the amount the United States will offer in debt relief in the new 
fiscal year, hoping to set an example for other rich countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally, the administration's budget had included $120  
million to support debt relief in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 
1. But Summers said the new request boosts that total to $370 
million, an increase of $250 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also asked Congress to approve another $600  
million over three more years, amounting to a total U.S. 
contribution of $970 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is essential moral policy to write off debts to nations in  
significant parts of the world where a child is more likely to die 
by the age of five than attend secondary school,'' Summers told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Jubilee 2000, a coalition of poverty and religious groups, is  
pressing the debt relief effort through an aggressive lobbying 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Seth Amgott, a spokesman for the private aid agency Oxfam  
International, praised the administration's proposal, saying it 
should spur other wealthy nations, the IMF and the World Bank to 
give more. 
</P>
<P>
	``Secretary Summers is making clear that the United States will  
do what it can to keep the commitment made at Cologne,'' Amgott 
said. ``This is a very positive development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, officials said the IMF was close to approving an  
alternative to its original plan to raise its share of the debt 
relief through sales of gold on the open market. That original 
proposal drew heavy opposition from members of Congress from Utah 
and other gold-producing states that feared it would depress 
further world gold prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of direct sales, the IMF is considering a proposal to  
sell 14 million ounces of its gold to member nations -- not 
including the debt-relief countries -- at market prices and let them 
use the gold to pay for their own IMF loans coming due. Such a 
circular transaction would let the IMF revalue the gold from the 
$47 per ounce on its books to market prices, currently above $250 
per ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF is being forced into this convoluted exercise because  
its rules prohibit an outright revaluation of its gold reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., a leading supporter of debt relief  
who initiated the new gold sales proposal, said he was optimistic 
Congress will approve the administration's increased funding 
request. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cost of funding debt relief is $1.20 a year for every man,  
woman and child in the United States over the next three years and 
the cost of not doing it will be the death of tens of thousands of 
people every day,'' said Bachus. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration released a fact sheet estimating that if  
wealthy creditor countries and multinational organizations meet the 
obligations envisioned by the Cologne initiative, it would reduce 
the debt held by the 33 poorest nations from $127 billion to $37 
billion, a cut of $90 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the fact sheet said Mozambique's annual  
debt-financing costs would be cut in half, from more than 30 
percent of the government's budget to about 15 percent, freeing up 
$30 million a year that could be used for health care or education. 
</P>
<P>
	World Bank President James Wolfensohn told reporters he hoped  
the upcoming meetings would resolve the issue, including how the 
World Bank will finance its share of the debt relief proposal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
