<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Never Alone When TV Talks to You </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On most TV dramas and comedies, the characters  
are happy to talk to one another. 
</P>
<P>
	But on several new series, they also talk to themselves ... and  
to you. 
</P>
<P>
	Just take a look at Fox's high school dramedy ``Get Real.'' At  
the hospital after Meghan's brother Cameron cracks up his car, 
Meghan pulls a ``gotcha'' on the viewer: ``You think we're gonna 
kill my brother?'' she says, laughing into the camera. ``In the 
first episode?!'' 
</P>
<P>
	And when the parents are summoned to a conference about Cameron,  
both are startled by how young the vice principal is. This you 
learn, dear viewer, as their unspoken reactions surface as 
voice-overs: 
</P>
<P>
	Cameron's father: ``What is she -- nine?''  
</P>
<P>
	Cameron's mom: ``I've got ice cubes older than her.''  
</P>
<P>
	Shakespeare knew. A soliloquy can be very handy for putting  
across sentiments that would be awkward to express to another 
character, or hard, if not impossible, to convey visually. 
</P>
<P>
	A few centuries later, TV's ``Burns and Allen Show'' of the  
1950s allowed patriarch George Burns to adjourn to his den, view 
the family downstairs on his magic TV, comment on the action, then 
rejoin it as if he'd never left. 
</P>
<P>
	And a decade ago, ``It's Garry Shandling's Show'' starred the  
stand-up comic as a stand-up comic with a TV show. He and his 
friends all knew they were on a TV show, and frequently remarked 
upon it, even as they were swept up in the stories it depicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Now TV's newly fashionable out-of-body experiences (out of the  
body of the story, that is) continue to serve a number of useful 
and entertaining purposes. A few well-chosen words of narrative can 
do wonders to supply exposition, ease a transition or paper over a 
gap in the plot-line. 
</P>
<P>
	And by going straight to the viewer with his or her message, a  
character mimics the behavior you expect from the hucksters, 
entertainers, journalists and pundits who make up the rest of TV's 
on-screen population. 
</P>
<P>
	You've long been accustomed to this entre-nous relationship with  
TV personalities. So on a TV drama or comedy, it feels right to be 
directly addressed, to be made privy to a character's private 
thoughts, to hear a wisecrack the other characters don't share. 
</P>
<P>
	At a party, Meghan alerts you to another girl's fashion faux  
pas: ``Platform shoes! Hmmmph. Those who forget history are doomed 
to repeat it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But ``Get Real'' (airing tonight at 9 p.m. EDT) isn't the only  
new series that talks to you. 
</P>
<P>
	Little wonder. This is the Age of Irony, when seemingly no  
thought or action is complete without a mocking addendum. This is 
also the Age of Self-Examination, when you are expected to ponder 
to death every moment of your life. 
</P>
<P>
	On the NBC sitcom ``Mike O'Malley'' (airing Tuesdays), 30-ish  
single guy Mike interrupts the story for a flashback chronicling 
how he lost his girlfriend or for a pledge to the audience that 
he'll win her back. 
</P>
<P>
	On Fox's comedy ``Malcolm in the Middle'' (premiering in  
January), 9-year-old Malcolm is a knowing observer of his nutty 
household, as well as an obliging participant. 
</P>
<P>
	In one scene, Malcolm's mother tries to cheer him up as he faces  
his dark future as a genius in an accelerated class. ``Any kid who 
makes fun of you,'' she snaps, ``is a creepy little loser who'll 
end up working in a car wash.'' Malcolm turns to the camera: ``That 
shouldn't make me feel better. But it does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the WB's post-collegiate romance ``Jack &AMP; Jill'' (premiering  
Sunday), David ``Jill'' Jillefsky is about to run into scrumptious 
Jacqueline ``Jack'' Barrett as you hear him, in voice-over, 
fretting over his current girlfriend: ``Elisa was the kind of girl 
I could spend the rest of my life with, y'know? It's just hard to 
know when the rest of your life is supposed to start.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Fox's ``The Badland'' (premiering Oct. 15), Ryan Caulfield,  
the rookie cop, uses voice-overs to confide his excitement and 
fears. 
</P>
<P>
	And on ABC's drama ``Once and Again'' (airing Tuesdays), the  
narrative is intercut with play-by-play commentary from Rick or 
Lilly, the single parents who are falling in love. Shot in 
black-and-white, these sequences are staged as if each of the 
characters were being interviewed, allowing them to reflect on the 
action, or themselves, in safe isolation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not very good when people pull away,'' Lilly muses in one  
of these scenes. ``I always think that it's something I did. I 
guess I take responsibility for everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But among the season's newcomers it's ``Get Real'' that bursts  
the dramatic ``fourth wall'' most rambunctiously. 
</P>
<P>
	When high schooler Meghan hears a fellow student squeal in  
delight at landing admission to a prestige college, she scoffs to 
herself. Big deal -- she got in, too, but turned the college down. 
``Gimme a break,'' she sneers in the voice-over. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, speaking to the camera, she adds, ``I made a decision not  
to go to college and I'm fine with it. Totally.'' She detects your 
skepticism and stares you down: ``What?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Look what you've got: interactive TV!  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`WEST WING': If you liked ``Sports Night'' last season, you'll  
be all the more intrigued with Aaron Sorkin's latest creation. On 
``The West Wing,'' there's the same witty, rapid-fire dialogue and 
sweeping camera work. But where ``Sports Night'' is a half-hour, 
set behind the scenes at a cable network, ``The West Wing'' has a 
much broader canvas: It's an hour series that goes backstage at the 
White House. As the deputy communications director, Rob Lowe is 
only one of an enormous and appealing ensemble that also includes 
Martin Sheen as President Bartlet. Wry but patriotic, funny and 
proud, ``The West Wing'' is a rousing vision of America. Premiering 
tonight at 9 p.m. EDT on NBC, it's a show to salute. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
