<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Cautious on Samaranch Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee expressed a  
wait-and-see attitude Wednesday to a request for its president to 
testify at a Congressional hearing on Atlanta's tainted bid for the 
1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	A top IOC executive, meanwhile, accused U.S. officials of making  
``self-serving'' accusations and of ignoring the ``massive reform'' 
undertaken by the Olympic organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., said Tuesday he would ask IOC  
president Juan Antonio Samaranch to appear at hearings next month 
investigating the ``culture of corruption'' surrounding Atlanta's 
winning bid. He said he would subpoena Samaranch if he declines to 
testify voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't received any official notice from the House  
subcommittee,'' IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said. 
``When we do, we'll consider it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch declined to appear at Senate hearings in April  
prompted by the vote-buying scandal stemming from Salt Lake City's 
successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. Samaranch sent Anita 
DeFrantz, the American IOC vice president, to represent him. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Dick Pound of Canada, who headed an internal  
inquiry into the Salt Lake scandal, said Samaranch would probably 
consult with his executive board about how to deal with Upton's 
request. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to wait and see in what terms the invitation was  
issued, what the scope and purpose of the hearing is,'' Pound said. 
``It will be decided on an ad-hoc basis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House hearing is scheduled for the week of Oct. 11.  
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch has not traveled to the United States since the Salt  
Lake City scandal broke late last year. He and other IOC members 
are subject to possible questioning by the FBI in connection with 
its Salt Lake investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Questions have been raised whether the IOC will go ahead with  
its scheduled executive board meetings in Colorado Springs and Salt 
Lake City in February. 
</P>
<P>
	As in Salt Lake, Atlanta bid officials offered lavish gifts and  
favors in their attempt to win the votes of IOC members. 
</P>
<P>
	Upton said a report on the Atlanta bid, submitted to Congress  
last week by former Attorney General Griffin Bell, shows that IOC 
members often expected gifts and favors and that Atlanta bid 
officials willingly accommodated them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly votes were for sale,'' Upton said.  
</P>
<P>
	Upton said he wanted Samaranch to ``explain exactly how the IOC  
awards games,'' based on some of the ``outrageous revelations'' 
related to the Atlanta bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell and other Atlanta officials have suggested that Atlanta was  
dragged into a corrupt bid culture fostered by the IOC, an 
accusation rejected by Pound. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is particularly self-serving is for someone to say it's  
all the fault of the IOC for creating this kind of atmosphere,'' he 
told The Associated Press by telephone. ``The IOC certainly didn't 
create any such atmosphere all by itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is quite clear the IOC members did not demand all these  
gifts and favors. They may have asked for some, in which case we'll 
take responsibility, but the (people making the offers) have to 
take their own responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pound said Upton and others have not taken into account the  
actions the IOC has taken the past 10 months, including the 
expulsion or resignation of 10 members and the initiation of 
reforms of its structure, rules and procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are talking and acting as if they are unaware any of  
this is going on,'' he said. ``Some of (the Atlanta controversy) 
seems to be taking place in a vacuum. It seems a trifle bizarre.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Congress has to do what it thinks it has to do,'' Pound  
added. ``What you hope is (investigators) will take into account 
all of the relevant facts, which in this case involves a massive 
reform on the part of the IOC. This doesn't seem to be on anybody's 
radar screen. I don't understand that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
