<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Seeks Human Rights Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Indonesia wants its own human rights  
commission to investigate alleged human rights violations in East 
Timor before an international probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas expressed his concerns a  
day after the 53-nation U.N. Human Rights Commission decided to 
hold a special session in Geneva starting Thursday to discuss 
rights violations in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that it will be a good session, but that it will not  
take decisions that turn out to be exacerbating the situation 
rather than improving it,'' he told reporters Tuesday on the 
sidelines of the U.N. General Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-Indonesian militias, backed by Indonesian troops, have been  
blamed for lootings, killings and wholesale destruction in East 
Timor following the announcement that voters overwhelmingly chose 
independence from Indonesia in an Aug. 30 U.N.-supervised ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	The special session of the U.N. rights commission was requested  
by Portugal, East Timor's former colonial ruler. 
</P>
<P>
	The session was backed by Mary Robinson, the top U.N. rights  
commissioner, who has denounced ``a deliberate, vicious and 
systematic campaign of gross violations of human rights'' in the 
territory following its vote in favor of independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Alatas inisited Jakarta ``shares firmly'' the belief that people  
who committed human rights violations should be punished. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``we believe that at this stage perhaps it would  
be better for our national commission on human rights to conduct 
the investigations, with the help of expertise from the Commission 
on Human Rights, rather than go immediately into an international 
commission of the investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal's President Jorge Sampaio said peacekeepers and U.N.  
officials should start gathering evidence of human rights 
violations -- but emphasized it should be done discreetly. 
</P>
<P>
	Once evidence is collected, Sampaio said it will be time to  
assess the mood in East Timor and in Indonesia and determine how to 
proceed. He said he couldn't be certain how the Indonesian army 
would react to possible war crimes charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think any army reacts well when you're just pointing  
the finger at them,'' Sampaio said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990922.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-22 13:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Get This: You Can Bet on Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Investors can literally bet on the weather now.  
</P>
<P>
	Weather futures made their debut Wednesday on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, enabling investors to speculate on what the 
temperature is going to be in four U.S. cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Utilities, insurance companies and other businesses with a lot  
riding on the weather can use the futures to hedge their risk. 
</P>
<P>
	A utility, for example, might seek to protect itself from a  
milder-than-normal winter, which would hold down sales of 
electricity for heating homes and businesses. A peach grower in 
Georgia might want to protect a crop from frost damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Merc, where investors buy and sell futures and  
options contracts on everything from milk to Treasury bonds, says 
weather affects 20 percent of the $9 trillion U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone else determined enough to bet on next year's weather can  
do it, too. A Farmer's Almanac is optional -- all you need to 
``play'' the weather is a commodity brokerage account and a 
bankroll. 
</P>
<P>
	At $100 for each point change in the weather index, the stakes  
can mount up quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Weather touches just about all parts of the economy,'' from  
retail sales to utilities to insurance, said Pete Barker, vice 
president of the exchange. ``Now it's possible to do something 
about that by taking a position on how warm or cold it's going to 
be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But after mixed results with previous innovations -- contracts on  
brine shrimp and Russian ruble futures bombed, eurodollar and 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index futures have boomed -- exchange 
officials are braced for a potentially chilly reception for 
weather. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes they work and sometimes they don't,'' Barker  
admitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Weather futures already have been trading on the  
over-the-counter market for the past two years. The investment is 
known as a ``derivative'' because its value is derived from an 
underlying asset. Instead of being based on swings in a foreign 
currency, stock index or interest rate, this investment is related 
to the temperature. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors place their ``bets'' on the average temperature in  
four U.S. cities: Atlanta, Chicago, Cincinnati or New York. Plans 
call for later adding Dallas, Philadelphia, Portland, Ore., and 
Tucson, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	The Merc offers monthly contracts based on heating degree days  
expected in those cities. A degree day is a measure used to 
describe how much the temperature differs from the standard average 
for one day. 
</P>
<P>
	Headed into fall and winter, the contract is based on an index  
that measures how much the actual daily average temperature in 
those cities is below 65. For example, an average temperature of 55 
degrees for a full day would equal 10 index points. If that 
temperature held at 55 over a 30-day month, the index swing would 
be 300 points. 
</P>
<P>
	For an initial investment, a trader has to put up a down payment  
for each contract traded. For the Chicago temperature contract 
covering October, that would be $1,400 per contract. 
</P>
<P>
	A trader makes money on a contract when the index rises after it  
is purchased. A gain of 20 points, at $100 a point, represents 
$2,000. 
</P>
<P>
	A trader loses money when the index falls after the contract is  
purchased. 
</P>
<P>
	The debut of the first temperature-related derivative to be  
traded on an exchange was hardly stormy for a setting that usually 
is raucous. 
</P>
<P>
	While red-jacketed traders on the exchange floor shouted and  
gestured wildly as they dealt in contracts for live cattle and 
frozen pork bellies, there was only electronic trading of weather 
futures. The action was evident only in the flashing of tiny red 
and green lights showing prices on the overhead quote board and on 
desktop computer screens above the trading pit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Merc said 53 contracts were sold in the first five hours of  
trading, which will continue around the clock. It was a modestly 
successful start. 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange would not reveal its customers, but the majority  
were presumed to be large utilities or insurance firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Four energy trading firms are making the market and guaranteeing  
payment on the contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract's backers, armed with reams of historical  
temperature records, set the initial price levels and were hoping 
the market will take off. 
</P>
<P>
	``Businesses are gambling on the weather anyway, and this allows  
them to hedge their positions,'' said Jeff Porter, vice president 
of Koch Energy Trading of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Insiders already are talking about the possibilities of snowfall  
futures, which could help protect ski resorts or snowblower 
manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago exchange doesn't pretend to be able to predict the  
weather any better than your uncle with a trick knee. But officials 
warn this isn't a place to look for big profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough to predict weather with any accuracy beyond 10-14  
days,'' says Barker. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
